<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 10, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. House Votes To Remove Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- On the day that South Carolina celebrated its first
official Confederate Memorial Day, members of the state House voted Wednesday to
remove the Confederate flag from atop the Statehouse dome. The Senate already
has approved a similar measure to remove the flag and put one up at a monument
on the Statehouse grounds. Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges has said he supports
removal. Lawmakers debated late into Wednesday night, with supporters of the
bill pleading with their fellow House members to approve the plan. The bill
passed 63-56. A procedural vote will be held Thursday before it goes back to the
Senate, which has to agree on minor differences in the two versions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Evacuated for Fire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A blaze that had been set to clear brush but raged
out of control over the weekend spread into Los Alamos and burned homes
Wednesday, forcing the evacuation of all 11,000 residents in this town, the site
of America's most storied nuclear laboratory. With wind gusts up to 50 mph
driving the flames through ponderosa pine, police, sheriff's and fire department
officials went door to door, urging people to pack up and get out as quickly as
possible. Smoke from the fire rose 20,000 feet above the ground.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Attack Appears Imminent in Sierra Leone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Thousands of refugees poured into Freetown on
Wednesday as pro-government troops rushed to key towns near Sierra Leone's
steamy seaside capital to prepare for a feared rebel attack. U.N. peacekeepers,
the Sierra Leone army and pro-government militia fighters were consolidating
their forces along the road into the capital from Waterloo, 15 miles away, where
fleeing residents said they heard the sound of gunfire Wednesday morning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Microsoft Files Rebuttal To Gov't Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying the penalty would far exceed the antitrust
violations a federal judge found the company to have committed, Microsoft on
Wednesday asked a judge to throw out the Justice Department's plan to break up
the company. Microsoft offered its own remedies to correct what U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled last month was illegal anticompetitive
behavior. The company said it was willing to stop displaying the desktop icon in
its Windows operating system that leads users to its Web browser, Internet
Explorer.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FDA Approves Saline Breast Implants
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government ruled Wednesday that saline-filled breast
implants made by two California companies can stay on the market despite
warnings that they break open at ''alarmingly high'' rates. Giving its first
formal approval of the long-sold implants, the Food and Drug Administration
allowed the products to continue selling as long as women are fully informed
that many will have to undergo repeated surgeries.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Poll: Bush Beating Gore in Florida
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has a narrow lead over Al Gore in Florida,
according to a new poll in a state that officials from both parties agree is
crucial for the Republican to build a winning combination of electoral votes.
Texas Gov. Bush had 47 percent while the Democratic vice president had 40
percent in the poll released today by the American Research Group of Manchester,
N.H.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
MP3.com Pulls Plug on Disc Service
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- A legally disputed service that allows consumers to store
popular songs on the Internet site of a digital music company was partially shut
down Wednesday. The Internet site's operator, San Diego-based MP3.com, disabled
the service to prevent anyone from storing music produced by major recording
companies until a copyright lawsuit is settled. A federal judge in New York
earlier this month ruled that the service infringed on the copyrights of the
nation's major record companies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks plunged Thursday, pushed down by continued
weakness on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average shed 440.00 points to
17,261.47 in early trading. On Wall Street Wednesday, The Nasdaq fell 200.28 to
3,384.73 and the Dow Jones industrial average fell 168.97 to close at 10,367.78.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Marlins Beat Braves 5-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves twice loaded the bases with none out and
failed to score, and the Florida Marlins handed Tom Glavine his first loss, 5-3
Wednesday night. Glavine (6-1) had won eight consecutive decisions dating to
Sept. 11, but he fell to 6-11 against Florida, the only team he has a losing
record against.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
