<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Franks, Gormley given slight edge in U.S. Senate primary field  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The Republican field in the race for U.S.
Senate remains too close to call, according to a new poll by
Quinnipiac College.
</P>
<P>
   The poll suggests that U.S. Rep. Bob Franks and state Sen. Bill
Gormley are out in front, but their lead over Essex County
executive James Treffinger and Ramapo College professor Murray
Sabrin is so small it pretty much falls within the poll's margin of
error.
</P>
<P>
   The poll gives Franks 18 percent and Gormley 14 percent among
residents who say they are registered Republicans. Treffinger was
supported by 8 percent and Sabrin by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign chiefs for Franks and Gormley had little quarrel with
the poll outcome, agreeing that the race is wide open and voter
recognition of the candidates so far is minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Quinnipiac surveyed 311 residents who identified themselves as
registered Republicans. It has an error margin of 5.6 percentage
points, which means when the error margin is factored in to any of
the returns, most of the candidates can be said to be running dead
even.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, while Franks, R-Berkeley Heights, was ahead of
Gormley by 4 percentage points, Gormley's 14 percent support could
actually be as high as 19 percent while Franks' 18 percent support
could actually be as low as 13 percent, in effect reversing their
position.
</P>
<P>
   The big leader on the poll returns is Mr. Undecided, which is
how 46 percent of the registered Republicans responded to the poll.
Quinnipiac political analyst Scott McLean said the vast field of
undecided voters shows that all of the candidates have small bases
of support, however loyal, and the potential to gain 15 or 20
percent of the undecided voters in time for a win June 6.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Republican candidates has broadcast TV commercials
yet, and none moved much from the poll results seen in late March.
</P>
<P>
   Along with questions asking how they would vote now, Republican
voters who were surveyed were asked if they recognized and had
favorable or unfavorable views of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Franks had the highest recognition of the field with 16 percent
regarding him as favorable, a result vastly overshadowed by the
fact that 65 percent said they had no opinion of him.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrin, running as an outsider from the mainstream state
Republican Party, had the highest degree of anonymity -- 80 percent
had no opinion of him -- despite the fact that he had run for
governor as a Libertarian in 1997 and got 114,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Franks campaign chief Charlie Smith said the polls have
consistently showed Franks in front despite any adjustment for
error margins.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously all of the campaigns have some work to do, but let's
not forget this is a multi-candidate field in which the winner
ultimately may win with less than 50 percent of the vote,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley campaign manager David Murray said the race is even,
adding, ''Nothing's changed for months.'' He said the undecided
vote is probably closer to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not unreasonable to say that two out of three
Republicans who will come out on June 6 are not yet focused on the
campaign, and don't know what they are going to do on June 6,''
Murray said. ''I think the poll is right in saying the race is
ill-defined.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray discounted Franks' lead in support from county GOP
organizations. ''An organization is not going to let voters know
who he is or what he is going to do for them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith said the Gormley campaign, by focusing on negative
attacks against Franks, has shown that it believes their candidate
is trailing.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Shaftan, Sabrin's spokesman, said he thinks the lead that
Franks and Gormley have will ''get bigger before it gets smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to come on in the last 10 days. The other
candidates are going to say their message and people will see that
there's one conservative in the race,'' Shaftan said.
</P>
<P>
   A phone messages left with the Treffinger campaign office was
not returned Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
