<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Groups urge adoption of profiles for health care workers  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A coalition of groups is accusing the state
Medical Society of jamming progress on a bill to require the
release of more information about health professionals, especially
medical malpractice histories.
</P>
<P>
   The groups Wednesday urged the state Senate to follow through on
promises to institute the physician ''profiles'' before the state
Legislature's regular session ends in the next five or six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Profiles should include information about a professional's
education, experience, history of settlements and jury verdicts and
other disciplinary matters, the advocates said. It would be
available over the Internet, according to plans in the state
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Among those promoting the profiles were the New York Public
Interest Research Group, the Center for Medical Consumers, the
Statewide Senior Action Council, and Best Friends, a group formed
to counsel the parents of children who die as the result of medical
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ''The more that they (legislators) horse around ... the more
they protect the doctors, the more people are going to die,'' said
Caren Catinella of Best Friends.
</P>
<P>
   The groups said they favor New York adopting a physician
disclosure law like Massachusetts', which, they said, has
contributed to less litigation against medical professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ''The number of (malpractice) lawsuits go down because the
patients appreciate not being jerked around,'' Blair Horner of the
New York Public Interest Research Group said. ''The revenge motive
is not so great as when people are being stonewalled.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Senate Health Committee, Republican Kemp
Hannon of Nassau County, has been negotiating with the Medical
Society and the Assembly over resolving differences in the
profiling legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon said those involved in the talks are waiting to see if
Gov. George Pataki will propose legislation, or at least indicate
his preferences for such a measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am highly hopeful because I don't see such a degree of
difference among the parties that with good will can't be easily
resolved,'' Hannon said Wednesday. ''They aren't ideological
differences.''
</P>
<P>
   One stumbling block is over how many medical malpractice
verdicts or settlements must be completed against a doctor before
they are listed in a profile. The Medical Society said three within
the past 10 years should trigger disclosure, though spokesman
Michael Murphy said one or two might also warrant disclosure if
they are ''relevant'' to the competence of the doctor or safety of
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Hannon said that information must also be put into perspective
for medical consumers. A family practitioner, for instance, may
well have no malpractice actions against him while an obstetrician
who performs more high-risk practices may have several, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Society does not believe the size of verdicts
against doctors in medical malpractice cases has a relationship to
the culpability of the doctors and would not favor using the size
of awards in a profile, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   The physicians' group also favors listing any serious
misdemeanor or felony convictions against doctors, regardless of
their relevance to their jobs, in profiles, according to Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, people can get information about state disciplinary
actions against doctors through the state Health Department and
some limited information about doctors' schooling from the state
Education Department. It is harder to find information about other
health care professionals such as pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
   The groups Wednesday also released a survey of more than 700 New
Yorkers they paid the Zogby International polling firm to conduct.
Eighty-two percent of those surveyed said they strongly agreed and
12 percent said they somewhat agreed that consumers should have
''easy access'' to background information about a physician,
including medical malpractice and disciplinary histories.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
