<HEADLINE> Clinton plans to press ahead with campaign  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- While New York's political community
attempts to digest the latest turn of events in the life of her
Senate rival, Hillary Rodham Clinton says she's going ahead with
business as usual on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just going to keep doing what I've been doing,'' the first
lady said Wednesday following an event at the Syracuse Hebrew Day
School. ''I'm going to keep talking about the issues and ideas that
I think matter to the lives of New Yorkers ... because this is an
important campaign about the future of the children and families of
the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came after Senate rival Rudolph Giuliani
announced that he and his wife, Donna Hanover, were discussing a
marriage separation.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest bombshell from the New York City mayor in the
past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the mayor confirmed that a woman he has been seen
with regularly in recent months, Judith Nathan, was his ''very good
friend.'' A week earlier, the mayor said he had treatable prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the mayor's announcement of separation discussions,
Clinton said, ''I don't have anything to say.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has lived through her own marital strife,
including her husband's public disclosure that he had a sexual
relationship with White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said that she and the mayor had had ''a short but
very cordial exchange'' in St. Patrick's Cathedral on Monday when
they attended the funeral mass of Cardinal John O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him I was praying for him,'' the first lady said. ''I
think all of us are hoping for the best for him.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, however, Clinton ducked a question about whether
she would like to see the mayor stay in the Senate race, waving off
the query with ''I'm on my way'' as she walked away from reporters
covering her appearance at the day school.
</P>
<P>
   At the school, Clinton said the anniversary of Israeli Freedom
Day was ''a happy celebration.'' She spoke to about 150 students,
teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the first lady addressed a convention at
Crouse Hospital of more than 250 nurses who are members of the
Service Employees International Union.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the nurses that she was participating in Sunday's
Million Mom March in Washington against gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a public health problem,'' Clinton said of gun violence.
''And those of you who are on the front lines, you know the health
problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
