<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Arrest Falun Gong Followers  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES HUTZLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Followers of the banned Falun Gong sect honored
the birthday of their movement's founder Thursday, protesting by
the dozens in Tiananmen Square only to meet swift and sometimes
forceful arrest by Chinese police.
</P>
<P>
   Followers tried to unfurl banners and raise their arms in a
meditation pose used by the group. Plainclothes police darted
across the vast plaza to quell the separate acts of civil
disobedience by small groups of sect members. Police vans raced
back and forth to pick up the captured.
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 people were taken away within about 90 minutes.
Tourists, taken aback by the frenzy on the normally crowded but
peaceful square, watched the protests. At least two Western
tourists were detained, apparently for taking pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The scene resembled the confrontation on April 25, when
followers gathered for the first anniversary of a 10,000-person
demonstration. The earlier protest had shocked China's leaders and
three months later they banned Falun Gong as a public menace and
threat to Communist Party rule.
</P>
<P>
   Followers insist that Falun Gong promotes health and good
citizenship. Falun Gong, also known as Falun Dafa, is a blend of
slow-motion exercises, Buddhist and Taoist philosophy and the often
unorthodox ideas of Li Hongzhi, an ex-government grain clerk who
founded the group in 1992 and now lives in New York.
</P>
<P>
   By the traditional lunar calendar once used in China and much of
Asia, Thursday marked the anniversary of the birth of the Gautama
Siddhartha, the founder of Buddhism. To Falun Gong followers, it is
Li's birthday too. China claims Li was born on July 7, 1952, but
changed his records in 1994 to build up his mystique.
</P>
<P>
   In the 9{ months since the group was banned, dozens of principal
organizers have been convicted and human rights groups say
thousands have been sent to labor camps without trial. Yet Falun
Gong followers have staged protests nearly every day, embarrassing
police who have been ordered to quash the sect.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the public defiance, the government claimed victory anew
over the group Thursday. In an editorial carried in national
newspapers, the official Xinhua News Agency claimed that 98 percent
of all Falun Gong followers had severed ties to the group.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
