<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Teacher Talks of Scandal  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE ZIEGLER DIZON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Five years ago, Jerry Plecki's phone rang nearly
incessantly. He couldn't eat. He couldn't sleep. And he wouldn't
answer the one question on everyone's mind: ''Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Plecki, the coach of a group of high school students caught
cheating its way to the state title in an academic competition,
left town to escape the frenzy. But now, as HBO prepares to air a
movie on the scandal, he's talking -- about the Chicago public
schools, his students and the decision to cheat.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no moral absolutes on this given topic,'' Plecki
told The Associated Press on Wednesday in his first interview since
the 1995 Illinois Academic Decathlon scandal broke.
</P>
<P>
   Plecki, an English teacher at Steinmetz High School, helped his
team cram from a stolen copy of the test, then shared in their
glory as they beat a rival Chicago magnet school that had won the
previous nine years.
</P>
<P>
   But the team's score was too good -- 9,400 points more than it
had scored at regionals. The second-place school, Whitney Young,
asked for a review, and decathlon officials determined the jump was
too great to be normal. They asked Steinmetz to take a ''validation
test,'' then stripped the team of its title when members refused.
</P>
<P>
   After a few team members broke down and admitted to cheating,
Plecki resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a horrible experience,'' Plecki said. ''But I'm an
adult, and I can handle it. What was more horrible to me was how
the media at the time turned the lives of these kids upside-down.''
</P>
<P>
   The former teacher, now a businessman in the Chicago area, looks
distinctly uncomfortable as he rehashes the scandal. He says he
agreed to consult on the HBO movie ''Cheaters'' and talk publicly
only to give the matter some closure.
</P>
<P>
   Plecki offers no apologies for his actions, nor does he defend
them. He instead asks, ''What if? What if it were you?''
</P>
<P>
   Plecki contends his team, all bright and high-scoring students,
had no chance to win in a public system that puts most of its
resources into a few magnet schools for elite students. Steinmetz
is in a blue-collar neighborhood, and Plecki said many team members
were from low-income, single-parent families and spoke English as a
second language.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney Young not only had the best teachers and more money than
Steinmetz, it had working bathrooms and the system's belief that
its students were the cream of the crop, Plecki said.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago schools officials declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Constantine Kiamos, Steinmetz's principal for the past 16
years, disputed the idea that there was no way for his school to
win without cheating.
</P>
<P>
   ''Out of a high school of 2,300, I certainly can find 10 or 12
great kids,'' Kiamos said.
</P>
<P>
   The principal said there's no gray area to what Plecki did -- it
was simply wrong. Steinmetz has not competed in the academic
decathlon since.
</P>
<P>
   ''He taught them to cheat. That is unacceptable,'' Kiamos said.
</P>
<P>
   Jolie Fitch, a student on Plecki's tight-knit team, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   Fitch, now 21 and working in a department store, is portrayed in
''Cheaters'' as the group's leader, the ultra-smart student who
wanted to show up Whitney Young at any cost. She says the students
decided as a group to use the stolen test and that Plecki did not
push them into any decision.
</P>
<P>
   She contends Steinmetz could have won without cheating -- the
team had to figure out the answers for the stolen test on its own --
but needed the extra boost of confidence the test provided.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't regret what I did. I learned a lot from it,'' Fitch
said. ''If I had to do it all over again, the only thing I would
change is getting caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitch, portrayed by Jena Malone, is the only student whose real
name is used in ''Cheaters,'' set to air May 20. Jeff Daniels takes
on the role of Plecki, while Paul Sorvino plays Kiamos.
</P>
<P>
   Director John Stockwell said his goal was to present an
''unflinching look'' at the scandal through the eyes of the people
lost in the frenzy: the students and their teacher.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is not a defense of cheating, Stockwell said, but
rather a way to highlight ''the hypocrisy in some of the platitudes
that we always spout.''
</P>
<P>
   Stockwell said he pursued Plecki for months before the teacher
agreed to talk. Plecki said he was paid for his help but declined
to discuss the amount.
</P>
<P>
   The former teacher said he misses teaching but is trying to move
on from the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not obsessed with this. I think about it often,'' Plecki
said. ''My hope is that everybody associated with it continues to
prosper.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   HBO: http://www.hbo.com/cheaters/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 0111 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Candidate Said Anti-Immigrant  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISERLOHN, Germany (AP) -- Applause mingles with the scent of
bratwurst in front of the ornate town hall as the conservative
candidate for governor shouts a simple message to a crowd of
supporters: German jobs should go to Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Ruettgers' anti-immigration slogans in North
Rhine-Westphalia won't turn the tide in state elections this
Sunday, polls predict, leaving Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
Social Democrats in control of Germany's most populous state.
</P>
<P>
   But the campaign has shown that the Christian Democrats are
ready to fight and spark national debate after a slush fund scandal
centered on ex-Chancellor Helmut Kohl sent the party's reputation
plunging.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is what has become known as the ''Kinder statt Inder''
campaign -- German for ''children, not Indians'' and an attack on
Schroeder's drive to bring in 20,000 foreign computer experts to
fill a shortage in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Democrats and Ruettgers argue jobless Germans
should be retrained instead.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does anyone really believe they would stay only temporarily?''
Ruettgers told a crowd of 200 during a recent rally in this
struggling industrial town. ''When they come, their families will
come too.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming it's ''deeply immoral'' for Germany to drain poor
countries of their best and brightest, he adds: ''I believe those
jobs should first of all be given to Germans.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers denies being anti-foreigner, saying he is pointing out
gaps in the state education system and the need to care for those
Germans left behind by economic change.
</P>
<P>
   But while the local Social Democrats seem to have survived a
recent sleaze scandal of their own, Ruettgers is battling not only
the furor set off by Kohl but also charges of racism.
</P>
<P>
   Despite grabbing national headlines, Ruettgers has failed to
revive the momentum of last fall when his party won a string of
state elections and swept city councils in North Rhine-Westphalia.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign has a model. A drive against relaxed citizenship
rules won Hesse state for the Christian Democrats last year.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, even the new party leaders have been lukewarm
about rhetoric that prompted the Social Democrats to compare
Ruettgers to Joerg Haider, the Austrian far-right leader criticized
for his past comments praising aspects of the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
   North Rhine-Westphalia, a former coal and steel region in
western Germany that is now home to many high-tech and media
businesses, has been firmly in Social Democratic hands for 34
years.
</P>
<P>
   Defeat here, considered possible before the Christian Democrats
sank into scandal last December, would be a huge blow to Schroeder
and his coalition with the small Greens party.
</P>
<P>
   The same alliance governs North Rhine-Westphalia, headed by
incumbent Gov. Wolfgang Clement, 59, a business-friendly
technocrat.
</P>
<P>
   Ruettgers, 48, is straining to persuade voters that he stands
for a fresh start -- even though he served as Kohl's education
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, newspapers headlined unconfirmed reports that
Bonn prosecutors had found enough evidence to charge Kohl with
breach of trust for his role in the scandal. The Christian
Democrats accused prosecutors of leaking information to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl sparked the scandal by admitting he took $1 million in
secret -- and thus illegal -- donations for his party while
chancellor in the 1990s. Many conservative voters aren't ready to
forgive yet.
</P>
<P>
   Anemone Kemper, a teacher put off by Ruettgers' choice of words,
said she would probably vote for the Free Democrats, a small
pro-business party trying to get back into the state legislature
after a five-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Christian Democrats' slogans are idiotic, of course,'' she
said on the quaintly refurbished Iserlohn town square. ''But the
basic idea of filling jobs with our own people is OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 0111 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Faces Long Flood Recovery  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   XAI-XAI, Mozambique (AP) -- Sitting in his aging pickup truck,
Jose Santini stared at the 2-month-old river that has cut his
hometown in two.
</P>
<P>
   He had been hoping -- though without much conviction -- that work
would have begun on restoring the main road, which floods from the
overflowing Limpopo River had cut off on both ends of the low-lying
area of Xai-Xai -- turning it into an island.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fixing the road is the most important thing,'' Santini said.
''Without it, we cannot begin to rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   The floods killed at least 700 people and destroyed the homes or
jobs of an estimated 2 million more. Other nations pledged more
than $450 million at a donor conference in Rome earlier this month,
but reconstruction efforts are expected to take years.
</P>
<P>
   Santini had watched from his first-floor apartment two months
before as the river surged through streets and buildings, tearing
concrete benches from the sidewalk and dumping a gasoline tanker in
a ditch. The river has subsided, but left behind a new tributary.
</P>
<P>
   Rubber boats shuttle people back and forth. Only a single
asphalt strip is passable by car. The other streets were turned
into shallow gullies.
</P>
<P>
   Xai-Xai's sidewalks are strewn with rubbish and the ruined
possessions of the town's residents. Outside the remains of the
bank, someone has painstakingly laid out soaked lumps of illegible
records. Further down stands the remains of the central market.
</P>
<P>
   Most residents who were evacuated to the higher areas of Xai-Xai
during the floods have stayed there, returning occasionally by boat
to try to salvage a few belongings.
</P>
<P>
   In some areas, there are signs of progress in restoring basic
services. The town of Chokwe, which was badly hit by a surge of
water on Feb. 27, has been cleaned up, and its 40,000 residents
have returned to start rebuilding their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But in other places there appears little sense of urgency.
Nowhere is this more evident than on the EN-1, the main north-south
road and a vital artery for transporting goods and distributing aid
to flood victims.
</P>
<P>
   Badly damaged in the floods, the road has had makeshift repairs
that enabled it to be reopened a few weeks after the rivers
receded. But little has been done since then, and light rains near
the southern town of Chibuto recently turned a dirt section of the
road into a muddy swamp, stranding thousands of people en route to
the capital, Maputo.
</P>
<P>
   On the road leading to Xai-Xai, the provincial capital of the
southern Gaza province, construction of a metal bridge spanning an
offshoot of the Limpopo River had ground to a halt, despite the
construction materials stacked next to the road.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the work had stopped, workers simply shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, vast tracts of land elsewhere remain under water and
thousands of people are unable to return home.
</P>
<P>
   The influx of foreign aid money will provide an immediate boost
for the economy and the government's coffers, but the flood victims
-- predominantly peasant farmers who are being given seed and
agricultural implements -- will have to wait some time before they
start earning an income again.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. World Food Program plans to feed 600,000 people until
the end of September, when they expect harvesting to resume.
</P>
<P>
   Arminda Mahlanga of Chokwe has spent weeks sleeping on the
ground, having lost everything she owned in the floods. ''I can't
get my stuff back, because I am not working,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Santini, a restaurateur who estimates he lost $60,000 in the
floods, said Mozambicans were worse off during the 17-year civil
war that followed independence from Portugal in 1975 and claimed
600,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
   ''The floods are just another disaster,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
