<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani announces he and wife are moving toward legal separation  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and his wife Donna
Hanover are moving toward legal separation, confirming
long-standing speculation that the two have a troubled marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very, very painful,'' Giuliani said at a news conference
Wednesday. ''For quite some time, it's probably been apparent that
Donna and I lead, in most ways, independent and separate lives.
It's been a very painful road and I hope we'll be able to formalize
that in an agreement that protects our children, that gives them
all the security and protection that they deserve. That is
something that we have to work out (and that) we have to strive
for.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time Giuliani, 55, has confirmed that his
marriage with Hanover, 50, a television personality and actress, is
strained. The couple have two children, Andrew, 14, and Caroline,
10.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure caps a bizarre two week period for the mayor, who
guards his privacy zealously but has recently been forced to make a
series of public announcements about exceedingly personal matters.
</P>
<P>
   First, on April 27, Giuliani announced he had been diagnosed
with treatable prostate cancer and said it could affect his run for
the Senate. Then, on May 3, he acknowledged that Judith Nathan, a
45-year-old divorcee with whom he has been seen around town, was a
''very good friend'' but refused to further characterize the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Republican mayor, who is running for the U.S.
Senate against first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, said his
disclosure has nothing to do with politics and that he does not
expect his announcement to harm him politically.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't really care about politics right now,'' he said. ''I'm
thinking about my family, the people that I love and what can be
done that's honest and truthful and that protects them the best.
... Politics comes at least second, maybe third, maybe fourth,
somewhere else at least.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''It will all work itself out some way politically.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, Giuliani appeared at a campaign fund-raiser at
a private home in suburban Westchester County, a key demographic in
the Senate race. His aides said the campaign is ''all systems go.''
</P>
<P>
   However, political experts said that the talk of separation --
combined with his prostate cancer -- cannot help but affect the
campaign. Democratic political consultant George Arzt said it
raised questions about Giuliani's determination to run and might
hurt him among socially conservative groups like Catholics and
Orthodox Jews.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about Giuliani's marriage by reporters at a Syracuse
event, Hillary Clinton replied, ''I don't have anything to say.''
</P>
<P>
   After Giuliani's comments, Hanover summoned reporters to Gracie
Mansion and said the marriage had been strained for years and
alluded to a relationship the mayor had with an unnamed staff
member.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today's turn of events brings me great sadness,'' she said,
her eyes welling with tears. ''I had hoped that we could keep this
marriage together. For several years, it was difficult to
participate in Rudy's public life because of his relationship with
one staff member.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ''Beginning last May, I made a major effort to bring
us back together. Rudy and I re-established some of our personal
intimacy through the fall. At that point he chose another path.
Rudy and I will now discuss the possibility of a legal
separation.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports three years ago implied an affair between the mayor and
his then-director of communications, Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas,
35, who has since left City Hall and was recently married.
</P>
<P>
   There was never any confirmation of a romantic link between the
mayor and the aide and Hanover's statement did not elaborate on the
nature of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Now the president of the city's Convention and Tourism Bureau,
Lategano-Nicholas said in a statement Wednesday, ''I have no desire
to speculate why Donna Hanover decided to issue the statement that
she did. Understandably, this is a difficult time. I wish both the
mayor and Donna Hanover a successful resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Hanover have not appeared in public together in
years, although the mayor has been seen at both public and private
functions with Nathan during the past 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   At Wednesday's press conference, the mayor said he had
''tremendous respect'' for his wife, whom he called ''a wonderful
woman (and) wonderful mother.'' He went on to describe Nathan as
''a very, very kind person.''
</P>
<P>
   ''She's been a very good friend to me,'' said Giuliani. ''I rely
on her and she's helped me a great deal. And I'm going to need her
more now than maybe I did before.''
</P>
<P>
   Nathan is a registered nurse who lives with her 15-year-old
daughter on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani -- who usually keeps his emotions to himself and told
reporters ''I feel terrible'' and that he was ''very sad'' --
revealed a side that he has never shown before publicly and that
contrasted sharply to the upbeat manner in which he announced last
month that he has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Looking wan and weighing each word, Giuliani spoke of the
emotional pain his troubled marriage has created and in part,
blamed the media.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm motivated by all the tremendous invasion of privacy that's
taken place,'' he said. ''My family's, Judith Nathan's family. This
is something that had developed over some period of time and it is
something between Donna and me, not anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   But while appealing for some privacy, Giuliani acknowledged that
as an elected official that his ''private life is open to
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He said neither he nor his wife plan on moving out of Gracie
Mansion, the mayor's residence, for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ''A separation agreement is not a divorce,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
