<HEADLINE> Cardinals Pitcher's Father Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. (AP) -- Soon to be imprisoned for participating
in a cocaine and marijuana trafficking operation, the father of St.
Louis Cardinals rookie pitcher Rick Ankiel was arrested for
allegedly throwing a loaded handgun from his car.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ankiel, 43, was arrested Wednesday and charged with
possession of a firearm by a felon and culpable negligence. He was
being held without bail late Wednesday at St. Lucie County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel was arrested after a motorist complained that a man in a
pickup truck had pointed a gun at him. As officer tried to pull the
truck over, a loaded 9 mm handgun was thrown from the passenger
side window, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel admitted throwing the gun, telling officers he was
scared, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel had been scheduled to report to federal prison on July 24
to begin serving an almost six-year sentence. He pleaded guilty
last year to two counts of conspiracy to possess with intent to
distribute cocaine and marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   He had been free on $100,000 bond pending his surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Ankiel, a 20-year-old Port St. Lucie High School graduate,
is 3-2 for the Cardinals and has hit two homers.
</P>
