<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iowa Adjusts To Immigrant Population  </HEADLINE>
By BECKY BOHRER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Dann Speichinger wants to know what
planet is third from the sun and a boy with a heavy Spanish accent
answers correctly: ''Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The multi-grade classroom fills with spontaneous chatter in
Spanish, French, even an African dialect. Speichinger, who teaches
English as a second language in the Sioux City Community School
District, is at a loss. He speaks only English.
</P>
<P>
   Speichinger and other native Iowans have watched the state's
racial fabric change over the past few years as they welcome -- and
confront -- a booming Hispanic population.
</P>
<P>
   There are 31 million Hispanics in the United States and the
minority group is the nation's fastest-growing. By the year 2050,
their numbers are expected to triple and they may account for one
of every four Americans, up from 12 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, there were 33,000 Hispanics in Iowa, compared
with about 48,000 blacks, Census Bureau figures show. But Iowa
State University researchers say Hispanics are expected to
outnumber blacks as the state's largest minority population when
2000 figures are released.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau counted approximately 73,000 Hispanics in Iowa in
1998. Many of the new arrivals come from Mexico, drawn to
meatpacking jobs that offer $9-an-hour entry-level positions and
don't require fluent English.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics already have changed the face of Sioux City, a
Missouri River community of 83,000 in the state's northwestern
corner. In many ways, Sioux City is a microcosm of the change afoot
in Iowa: New students arrive almost daily for ESL classes, there
are new Mexican clothing shops and there's even a Spanish-language
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Change is catching some by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if this is a good thing or not yet,'' Bill Kai
said recently, adjusting his Pennzoil racing cap as he drank coffee
at the Eagles club with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess it's our fault, really. We don't want them jobs and
they've gotta find someone to fill them.''
</P>
<P>
   Immigration has long been a touchy subject in Iowa. Some state
lawmakers have pushed to make English the state's official
language, their efforts failing again this year.
</P>
<P>
   During the political campaigns that preceded the Iowa caucuses
in January, there were anti-immigrant advertisements run on
television and in newspapers, sponsored by groups based on the East
Coast.
</P>
<P>
   One ad, by the Washington, D.C.-based Federation for American
Immigration Reform, claimed a flood of immigrants had reduced the
quality of life in Storm Lake, a western Iowa town of about 8,800
people, to a ''memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Many state leaders, including Gov. Tom Vilsack, criticized the
ads and pledged their support of diversity, even as editorial pages
printed letters full of anti-immigrant sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sad sometimes that I have to explain why I'm here or why
it is my right to be here,'' said Alejandra Magana, who recently
passed her citizenship exam. ''Immigrants are here to work. We're
not leeches.''
</P>
<P>
   The unrest is compounded by concern that many immigrants are
here illegally. Iowa, like other Midwest states, has consistently
low unemployment, meaning nearly everyone who wants a job has one.
</P>
<P>
   The controversial Operation Vanguard, which included Nebraska
and western Iowa, was put on hold last year after the Social
Security Administration balked at plans to run the names of
meatpacking workers through its records. The Immigration and
Naturalization Service effort was aimed at finding illegal
immigrants working in packing plants.
</P>
<P>
   Early last year, about 300 protesters rallied against Operation
Vanguard outside the Marshall County Courthouse, some carrying
signs that read: ''Don't Panic, We're Just Hispanic.''
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, two INS agents were put in Sioux City, with Rep.
Tom Latham, R-Iowa, saying the move was ''something that many
northwest Iowans felt was needed to address our growing drug and
illegal immigration problems.'' More agents were added last year.
</P>
<P>
   Still, more than 3,500 illegal immigrants are expected to be
arrested this year in Iowa and Nebraska alone, according to Michael
Went, a top INS official in the Omaha, Neb. In 1994, just 423
people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Many Hispanics say they have confronted anti-immigrant feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Tears well in Tomasa Salas' eyes as she remembers an unhappy
encounter years ago. Her car door dinged a pickup in a grocery
store parking lot. She heard the man inside the pickup say, ''Why
don't you go back to where you came from?''
</P>
<P>
   ''I told him, 'I'm clean. I took a shower today.' I don't know
why, but that's the first thing that came to mind,'' said Salas,
who has lived in Sioux City for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do have racism in this community and that is a fact,'' said
Belia Stauder, a translator who works with immigrants. ''There are
people who do not want immigrants here. If they could get rid of
them, they would.''
</P>
<P>
   Magana, 26, lives in a trailer park in South Sioux City with her
brother Juan, a laborer. She said she is tired of explaining to
Iowa residents why she left Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all come from someplace. We're proud of that. We're proud
of our culture,'' she said. ''I wish people would understand
that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Iowa's Commission on Latino Affairs:
http://www.state.ia.us/government/dhr/la
</P>
<P>
   Federation for American Immigration Reform:
http://www.fairus.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
