<DOCNO> APW20000511.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA Judge Delays Thai Toddler Return  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT JABLON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- What happens when children from abroad find
themselves all alone in America?
</P>
<P>
   In the case of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, it was political
uproar, street confrontations, vast media exposure and an armed
federal raid to return him to his Cuban father.
</P>
<P>
   For 2-year-old Phanupong Khaisri of Thailand, it was a brief
confrontation between Thai civic leaders in Los Angeles and federal
immigration officials that led to a court order temporarily barring
his deportation.
</P>
<P>
   While both cases captured public attention, neither is
indicative of what happens to the vast majority of children who
enter the United States illegally and fall under the jurisdiction
of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other minors who arrive on U.S. shores are quietly
held in detention centers or shipped back home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is a very focused attention on certain celebrity
cases when it's in the interest of U.S. foreign policy or when it's
in the interest of specific sectors,'' said Sasha Khokha,
spokeswoman for the National Network for Immigration and Refugee
Rights in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't hear this kind of outcry about the approximately
8,000 Mexican children under the age of 17 that the United States
government expelled in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 4,607 children under 18 were in INS custody. On
average, 475 are in custody at any time, the agency said, and they
usually are deported within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Delays can be made for medical reasons. Elian, for example, was
treated for severe dehydration, while Phanupong had surgery for an
ear infection.
</P>
<P>
   In Elian's case, his Miami relatives are seeking his political
asylum over the U.S. government's order to return him to his
father, who wants the boy to return with him to Cuba. A federal
appeals court is weighing the case.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law treats Cubans differently than other immigrants. It
allows any Cuban who reaches American soil to apply for permanent
residency after being in the United States for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Elian fell under this law because he was brought to a hospital
in the United States after being rescued at sea Nov. 25. If he had
come from almost any other country, he would have been deported
right away.
</P>
<P>
   While Phanupong's case has gained less attention, he has
benefited from the support of Thai community leaders in Southern
California. He has no relatives in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   When the boy arrived in Los Angeles on April 11, authorities
said he was being used as a prop by a man trying to smuggle a
Chinese woman into the country. The intent was to make the three
look like a family.
</P>
<P>
   Phanupong's local caretakers, chosen by the Thai consulate, are
seeking political asylum for him, but only until they are convinced
the toddler will go home to a safe environment and won't wind up in
the hands of smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   ''This isn't a custody battle at all,'' said Hae Jung Cho,
project director for the Coalition to Abolish Slavery and
Trafficking. ''This isn't a political issue. It's just a case of a
little boy who was a victim of a human rights abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Thai Community Development Center enlisted several lawmakers
to pressure the INS to delay the boy's deportation and sued to
block his return home. The group won a two-week delay Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Thai boy's paternal grandparents have agreed to adopt him,
and the toddler could be back in Thailand for his third birthday
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Phanupong's caretakers and their lawyer allege the INS tried to
rush his repatriation and delay Elian's because Thailand has
friendly relations with the United States and Cuba doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The INS says it followed standard procedures in both cases.
</P>
<P>
   When unaccompanied minors arrive in the country, the agency
works with their native government to have them placed with local
relatives or sent back to parents ''within 72 hours, if at all
possible,'' said Karen Kraushaar, an INS spokeswoman in Washington,
D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our view is that a child is always better off with caring
relatives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Immigrant rights activists say they hope the high-profile cases
of Elian and Phanupong will raise awareness of the often-tragic
circumstances of immigrant children.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, Khokha said, Americans will be persuaded to help ''the
thousands of other immigrant children that may not have their
stories told and ... their voices heard.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Network for Immigration and Refugee Rights:
http://www.nnirr.org
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service: http://www.ins.usdoj.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 0123 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agassi Wins Match at Italian Open  </HEADLINE>
By ELLEN KNICKMEYER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- If Andre Agassi were to write a ''Career-Counseling
Guide to Long-Term Success,'' it likely would have some tips you
wouldn't find anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Such as: slack off once in a while. Let yourself get distracted.
Don't give it your all -- at least, not always.
</P>
<P>
   ''In 1997, I played 12 times. It wasn't much. You can argue I
didn't even play those 12,'' Agassi said after an easy second-round
win at the Italian Open. He was trying to explain why his career is
surging again at age 30 while the months-younger Jim Courier's has
just ended.
</P>
<P>
   Courier announced his retirement Tuesday, after a stalled three
years that included just one of his 23 career titles.
</P>
<P>
   ''My career has been different than Jim's, you know,'' the
top-seeded Agassi said Wednesday, advancing in a tournament where
he once routinely lost in the earliest rounds, and seemed happy
enough to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jim has worked hard every single day, every single year of his
whole career, you know,'' he said. ''I've tried to live a large
part of my life during my career.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Jim said it best when ... he talked about, now it's
time for his life, because it's always been tennis first. And I can
understand that,'' Agassi said. ''But for me, it hasn't always been
tennis first. So I think I'm a little fresher.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresher, he clearly is. And confident, after a clean start in
his first appearance since being sidelined by a thigh injury in
April, and in his first European event since his French Open
triumph last year.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi won with ease Wednesday against qualifer Gaston Gaudio of
Argentina to move to today's match against No. 15 Dominik Hrbaty of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Today's other matches pitted No. 3 Magnus Norman of Sweden
against Andrei Medvedev of Ukraine; No. 4 Gustavo Kuerten of
Brazil, the defending champion, against No. 14 Younes El Aynaoui of
Morocco; and No. 7 Thomas Enqvist of Sweden against an
up-and-coming 19-year-old Australian, No. 9 Lleyton Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   Yevgeny Kafelnikov, the No. 2 seed, presumably is heading home,
getting in some last-minute Rome sightseeing or otherwise making
plans after Wednesday's fourth straight early exit from a
tournament this season. The Russian fell to Mariano Puerta of
Spain, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Australian Open champion, Kafelnikov was docked
appearance fee money earlier this season for alleged apathy on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Agassi, now in his seventh appearance at Rome,
conveys himself as earnest, gracious toward the event's young
competitors, and intent on his game.
</P>
<P>
   All this at a tournament -- and on a surface, clay -- where he
once was more usually lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Agassi came to Rome days early with Steffi Graf,
played at a charity event, and managed to be fairly charming even
in translation in a drop-by on an Italian TV variety show.
</P>
<P>
   It was in Rome last year, when he advanced to the third round,
that Agassi made the turnaround into what became an extraordinary
12 months -- regaining the top spot, and becoming only the fifth man
to win all four Grand Slam titles.
</P>
<P>
   Staying fresh, Agassi made clear after his second-round victory,
also is a matter of one tip that's a career-counseling standard:
motivation.
</P>
<P>
   He's got that too.
</P>
<P>
   ''For me, it's truly a question of understanding if I still have
my best tennis ahead of me,'' he said. ''You know, I think there
are areas that I feel like I can still get better; I feel like I
have the opportunity to still get better. And I think that that
helps with the desire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
