<HEADLINE> El Salvador Army Warehouse Explodes  </HEADLINE>
By DIEGO MENDEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- An underground arms warehouse
caught fire and exploded in San Salvador, injuring dozens and
flinging unexploded grenades into nearby residential neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of Wednesday's fire was unknown, said Salvadoran
Defense Minister Gen. Juan Martinez Varela.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers extinguished the fire and evacuated 500 people
from nearby neighborhoods where at least 1,000 unexploded grenades
landed during the explosion, said Defense Ministry spokesman Col.
Roberto Alas.
</P>
<P>
   At least 50 military explosives specialists were sent to the
area to recover the grenades. Fire from the explosion spread to
several homes, but the blaze was quickly extinguished. The
explosion also destroyed vehicles and shattered windows.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Miguel, a gas station employee working near the
warehouse, said he heard the explosion, and then ''it started
raining rocks, splinters, and grenades, which fortunately didn't
explode.''
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said they saw several wounded soldiers from the
warehouse being transported from the scene. Officials have not
given an exact number of injuries, saying only that dozens were
injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
