<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Kids' Pneumonia Deaths Down  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   The children of baby boomers are highly unlikely to
die of
pneumonia, researchers reported today.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pneumonia deaths among children dropped 97 percent between 1939
and 1996 -- from 24,637 two generations ago to 800, according to a
report in today's New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread immunizations and government health care programs for
poor children are probably major reasons, according to researchers
at the National Center for Infectious Diseases.
</P>
<P>
   The American Lung Association credits penicillin, which was
discovered in 1928 but not available in quantity until 1944, with
moving pneumonia out of the most common cause of death in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: New England Journal of Medicine:
http://www.nejm.org/content/index.asp
</P>
<P>
   National Center for Infectious Diseases:
http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
