<HEADLINE> LPGA Back in Music City Area  </HEADLINE>
By TERESA M. WALKER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKLIN, Tenn. (AP) -- After coming to Nashville for 12 straight
years and winning three times, Meg Mallon had a hard time driving
past her usual hotel for the LPGA Tour's new spot 15 miles south of
Music City.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very strange,'' Mallon said. ''We're just so happy to
come back to Nashville. When we saw this facility, it's just a
fabulous facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of playing 54 holes at the Hermitage Golf Course, she
will tee off today with players like Karrie Webb and Nancy Lopez 30
miles away in the 72-hole, Electrolux USA Championship at The
Legends Club's Ironhorse Course.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the LPGA would lose Nashville as a stop a year
ago when Sara Lee pulled its sponsorship of an event that lasted 12
years and was the first major professional sporting event in Music
City.
</P>
<P>
   Tour officials held off announcing its 2000 schedule, giving
Nashville time. The new 72-hole tournament wasn't put together
until last November when Raycom Sports put together an agreement to
run the event with Electrolux as the sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes a course changes. Sometimes the sponsor changes,''
Mallon said. ''This time both happened. It's definitely different
for me. But it's still Nashville, and I still have such fond
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Those memories include the late Heather Farr, who is remembered
with a statue in front of the Hermitage's clubhouse. Farr, who died
of breast cancer in 1993, had attempted a comeback there.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville also is a very popular stop, luring the top players
every year with its mix of country music celebrities and
hospitality. Singer Vince Gill and his new wife, Amy Grant, are the
official hosts for this week's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lopez even postponed surgery to remove her gallbladder
until next week just to play here.
</P>
<P>
   ''That just goes to show how great the Nashville area and fans
are to Nancy and the rest of us,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   The Electrolux will feature a very different course. The
6,479-yard, par 72 course plays long, and undulating greens likely
will prevent the shootouts that regularly forced playoffs to
determine the Sara Lee winner.
</P>
<P>
   ''This week it's going to be completely different as far as the
golf course goes. Hopefully, I'll have success in a different
way,'' Mallon said.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite again is Webb, who already has won four times on
the LPGA Tour this year and is the leading money winner. She also
has won two non-tour events, including last weekend in Japan.
Mallon said fatigue might be Webb's biggest enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ''That'll hold her back for about two holes,'' Mallon said.
</P>
<P>
   Gill said he hopes both players and fans will be forgiving as
tournament officials work out any kinks left from planning
everything in just five months. He thinks the tournament, which now
includes his yearly pro-am called The Vinny and another pro-am
hosted by Grant, has lots of potential.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just putting one foot in front of the other,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
