<HEADLINE> Los Alamos Evacuated for Brush Fire  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF SIMONS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A blaze that had been set to clear brush
but raged out of control over the weekend spread into Los Alamos
and burned at least 30 homes Wednesday, forcing the evacuation of
all 11,000 residents in this town, the site of America's most
storied nuclear laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday night, the intense fire had forced firefighters to
pull back from whole neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in a retreat situation,'' said county spokesman Bill
Lehman said, adding the blaze had spread into two west-side
subdivisions and crews were running out of water.
</P>
<P>
   An aerial view of the city showed pockets of neighborhoods up in
flames. The office of Gov. Gary Johnson said he had seen at least
30 homes in flames and firefighters told him at least 50 homes had
burned.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you have to evacuate an entire town, it's got to be one
of the worst fires in New Mexico (history),'' Lehman said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire also forced authorities to ask residents in parts of
Espanola, about 10 miles from Los Alamos, to leave their homes,
Mayor Richard Lucero said.
</P>
<P>
   Flames had marched to a tree-covered ridge overlooking downtown
Los Alamos, lighting the night sky. Billows of flame leapt from
treetops and smoke rose 20,000 feet above the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Homes in western and northern parts of the city began burning in
late afternoon. The extent of the damage was not immediately known
and officials could not give an estimate of how many homes had
burned. Overall, 4,500 acres had burned by Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, with wind gusts up to 50 mph driving the
flames through ponderosa pine, police, sheriff's and fire
department officials went door-to-door and urged people to pack up
and get out as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Alamos nuclear laboratory has been closed since Monday,
and lab officials said explosives and radioactive material stored
there were protected in fireproof facilities. Late Wednesday, the
lab declared a general emergency as brush fires swept through the
area, but no explosive material was affected and damage appeared to
be light.
</P>
<P>
   Even the fire command post was forced to re-establish itself
farther away from the fire. Wednesday night, a school bus stood by
at the new command post, a police headquarters, in case they or
anyone else needed to evacuate again.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fire was so intense they were told to pull back,'' Lehman
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said firefighters were frustrated, but ''there was just
nothing we could do, because of the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Winds died down Wednesday night, but they were expected to pick
up again Thursday with gusts of at least 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared the city a disaster area, giving the
Federal Emergency Management Agency discretion to use whatever
resources are necessary to handle the emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the first time I felt fear,'' said Jaret McDonald, 28,
who had been evacuated three times before for fires. ''When you're
against Mother Nature, you can't contain it. You'll lose every
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Water-dropping helicopters and airplanes dropping pink fire
retardant bombarded the blaze. Los Alamos County spokesman Bill
Lehman said efforts were hampered by winds blowing embers and
firebrands and starting spot fires.
</P>
<P>
   The fire burned out of control after the National Park Service
set it last week to clear brush at the nearby Bandelier National
Monument. Five hundred homes were evacuated Sunday night, and 3,700
acres had burned by Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos, 70 miles north of Albuquerque, is essentially a
company town for the federal laboratory. It sprang up in the 1940s
as the base of operations for the Manhattan Project, which built
the atomic bomb. There are still military barracks and
military-style housing in Los Alamos, along with relatively
upscale, newer developments.
</P>
<P>
   The fire moved closer to the laboratory Wednesday, and a
research building was in its path, fire spokesman Jim Paxon said.
Laboratory officials were prepared to fight the fire, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the blaze was not near any buildings containing nuclear
materials, ''and those buildings are rated to survive severe fires,
747 crashes, those kinds of things,'' lab spokesman Jim Danneskiold
said. ''They're bunkers, basically.''
</P>
<P>
   The emergency declared late Wednesday came after grash and brush
fires sprang up at three areas in the lab's southwestern quadrant.
The lab's weapons-engineering tritium facility at Technical Area 16
was swept by fire, but the masonry building did not catch fire.
Bunkers storing explosives at TA-16 were unaffected, lab officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Alamos Inn was among the homes and businesses forced to
evacuate Wednesday afternoon. Spokeswoman Brenda Lucero noted that
some of the 40 guests had been staying in the hotel because they
had evacuated their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's black smoke -- smoke everywhere,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many customers at Katherine's Restaurant in Los Alamos' White
Rock area were alerted to the evacuation by calls on their cell
phones at lunch. ''They're just jumping out of their seats and
leaving,'' said waitress Chris Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury hotels in Santa Fe offered discounts to evacuees: $25 a
night for rooms that normally go for as high as $239. There was a
great outpouring of support. Many people offered their homes as
shelter and donated food, clothing and blankets.
</P>
<P>
   The blowup was the worst thing firefighters could have imagined
after the Park Service set the fire. At a news conference Monday,
park Superintendent Roy Weaver took responsibility for the fire and
said conditions had seemed right for a controlled burn.
</P>
<P>
   However, a copy of the special weather forecast faxed to
Bandelier shortly before the fire was started, and obtained by The
Associated Press, was practically a blueprint for a spreading fire.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast told park officials that there was a maximum
potential for fire growth, that winds were about to increase, that
temperatures were about to rise and that the potential for the
usual increase in nighttime humidity was diminished.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver had to evacuate Wednesday and could not be reached for
comment by the AP. However, CNN reported that Weaver said he never
saw the forecast.
</P>
<P>
   While Los Alamos faced disaster, fire victims in Ruidoso, a
resort 200 miles south, had better news. The 8,600-acre fire had
forced up to 400 people to flee their homes Monday, but the wind
eased Wednesday and most residents were allowed to return home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've caught a break,'' fire spokeswoman Karen Miranda said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 0153 </TRAILER>
