<DOCNO> APW20000511.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banker, Boss Compete for N.D. Gov.  </HEADLINE>
By DALE WETZEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) -- Imagine competing against your own boss
for a big promotion -- and a pay cut.
</P>
<P>
   That's one way to look at this year's race for governor in North
Dakota, where the president of the nation's only state-owned bank
is opposing the attorney general who helped give him his job.
</P>
<P>
   John Hoeven, who has run the bank since 1993, once praised
Democratic Attorney General Heidi Heitkamp as among the state's
most capable officials. But since he switched to the Republican
Party, Hoeven has taken to describing her as a career bureaucrat.
</P>
<P>
   Heitkamp, finishing her second term after six years as tax
commissioner, is seeking to become the state's first female
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there's probably a few people out there who will say,
'Boy, I don't know that that is something a woman ought to be
doing.' Occasionally, you'll get a comment here or there,''
Heitkamp said. ''But I think for the most part, this is about
vision, and leadership, and who can get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the nation's older, more rural states -- almost one of
every five North Dakotans is 60 or older -- the race matches up two
people who would be among the nation's youngest governors. Hoeven,
at 43, is a year younger than Heitkamp.
</P>
<P>
   Neither candidate faces opposition in North Dakota's June 13
primary election.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeven reports to the state Industrial Commission, a
three-member panel made up of Heitkamp, Republican Gov. Ed Schafer
and Roger Johnson, the Democratic agriculture commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   He is paid $144,972 annually, while Heitkamp makes $65,753. The
new governor will earn $83,013.
</P>
<P>
   Heitkamp says Hoeven's challenge doesn't bother her.
</P>
<P>
   ''As long as he understands the boundaries, and as long as he
does the work of the bank, I don't have a complaint about it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of North Dakota was founded in 1919, born out of
farmers' frustration with tight credit, high interest rates and low
wheat prices. Both the bank and a state-owned flour mill, which
opened in Grand Forks in 1922, have since become part of North
Dakota's political fabric. And the bank reported record profits
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeven is relying on a campaign blueprint used by Schafer,
himself a political newcomer in 1992 who emphasized his business
background in two successful campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans regarded Schafer as a cinch for a third term and
begged him to seek it, but the governor decided eight years in the
job was enough.
</P>
<P>
   Hoeven, who worked at his family's Minot bank before taking the
state job, said his emphasis will be on bringing prosperity to
rural communities, many of which shrank or stagnated during the
1990s. Last year, 52 percent of taxable sales and purchases came
from four cities -- Fargo, Bismarck, Grand Forks and Minot.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer ''has really got us focused on building and diversifying
the economy,'' Hoeven said. ''That effort has really started to
take hold in our larger communities. Now we have to focus on
pushing that development out into our small towns.''
</P>
<P>
   During Schafer's administration, North Dakota's number of
wage-earning jobs off the farm grew 17 percent, and Hoeven believes
the state's economy has become less dependent on its mainstays of
agriculture and energy production.
</P>
<P>
   Heitkamp says North Dakota's economic health has not been as
robust as that of other states in the region. Her assessment is
shared by the state's own economic forecaster, Dismal Sciences Inc.
of West Chester, Pa., which the state budget office uses to help
compile tax collection estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis earlier this year, the company ranked North
Dakota's employment growth 49th among the states, and described its
economic performance as ''lackluster.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's more reason to worry. Census data published last
December estimated that North Dakota was one of only three states
to lose population during the 1990s, declining 0.8 percent to
633,666. And for 1998, the most recent year available, per capita
personal income was $21,708, far below the national average of
$26,482.
</P>
<P>
   ''As we look at our sister states ... we aren't doing as well as
they are,'' Heitkamp said. ''You really need to ask the question,
why not?''
</P>
<P>
   She plans to visit high schools and colleges to make a pitch for
graduates to remain in the state and promises a stepped-up effort
to bring former North Dakotans back.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my experience, if you want to change the image, it happens
one on one. It happens through political leadership. It happens
with an extended hand and a lot of visiting,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 0159 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Millionaire' contestant sues over allegedly ambiguous question  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It might not have been in the stars for Robert
Gelbman to win $1 million on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' but
now he is hoping to get more than that in court.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbman, of Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., says a poorly worded
question about zodiac signs cost him a shot at $1 million on the
television quiz show and he has filed a $2 million lawsuit against
the show's producers.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbman, 34, was a contestant on the show that was taped Aug. 17
and aired Aug. 18. He was eliminated at the $32,000 level by a
question about the zodiac. He left with a $1,000 check that he says
he still hasn't cashed.
</P>
<P>
   The question: ''Beginning in January, which of the following
signs of the zodiac comes last -- (a) Aquarius (b) Aries (c) Leo (d)
Scorpio?''
</P>
<P>
   Gelbman said he was thinking out loud and was ready to choose a
final answer when ''somebody in the audience gasped. That scared me
so I used my 50-50. I said Aquarius, and they said that was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ''After I left the hot seat and went backstage, I told them,
'You just robbed me of $31,000,''' said Gelbman, who says he is a
former student at Antioch College in Ohio and member of the high-IQ
society, Mensa.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem is that the question doesn't specify whether its
based on the zodiac cycle or the calendar year,'' Gelbman
explained. ''If it's based on the zodiac, then my answer is correct
because out of those choices, Aquarius is the last sign.''
</P>
<P>
   To remove ambiguity, said Gelbman, a computer programmer, the
question should have asked: ''Beginning in January, which of the
following signs comes last in the calendar year?''
</P>
<P>
   Gelbman said he asked for another chance as a ''Millionaire''
contestant but his request was denied.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed Tuesday in Manhattan's State Supreme Court,
Gelbman says the show ''unreasonably'' prevented him from
proceeding to the next level, and they ''failed to follow their own
rules and procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit names ABC, Walt Disney Co. and a Disney subsidiary,
Valleycrest Productions, as defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sewell, director of media relations for the ABC television
network, said her office had not seen the lawsuit and could not
comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbman, originally from Belle Harbor, Queens, said his lawyer
tried last November to get him another appearance on ''Who Wants to
Be a Millionaire?'' At this point, he says, he would not accept a
chance to become a contestant.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gelbman wants the $2 million he sued for. He accuses
the show's producers of intentionally inflicting ''severe emotional
distress and harm'' on him and breaching their contract with him.
</P>
<P>
   Gelbman said he was, coincidentally, the next contestant after
David Honea, a doctoral student in computer engineering from
Raleigh, N.C., who had won $32,000 but was stopped by a question
about the Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The $64,000 question asked which of the five Great Lakes is the
second largest in area after Lake Superior. Honea, 31, said Lake
Huron. The show's host, Regis Philbin, told him that the correct
answer was Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   After the show other contestants urged Honea to talk to the
show's producers. After several hours of fact-checking, executive
producer Michael Davies told Honea he was correct and the show was
wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-11-00 0202 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
