<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big Game Winners Keeping Quiet  </HEADLINE>
By JIM IRWIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, Mich. (AP) -- The Big Game fever has finally broken.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly three months and 23 consecutive drawings without a
jackpot winner, lottery officials announced that two tickets
matched all the numbers drawn Tuesday night. Somewhere, at least
two people are figuring out their moves in claiming $363 million,
the biggest prize in U.S. lottery history.
</P>
<P>
   One of the tickets that beat odds of more than 76 million to 1
was sold at a gas station in Lake Zurich, Ill., 30 miles northwest
of Chicago. The other was sold at Mr. K's Party Shoppe, located in
a strip mall near this quiet suburb 20 miles north of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Neither winner immediately stepped forward publicly.
</P>
<P>
   But Michigan Lottery officials said they were contacted
Wednesday by a ''remarkably quite calm'' man they believe holds one
of the winning tickets.
</P>
<P>
   The man didn't identify himself, but the validation numbers he
recited from his ticket matched the winner, lottery spokeswoman
Sarah Lapshan said. He didn't say where he was from or whether the
ticket was his alone or bought for a group.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pretty confident this is the winning ticket,'' Lapshan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois Lottery officials said they had not been contacted by
anyone claiming to hold the other winning ticket, which was bought
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We certainly would understand if they were going to get some
good financial advice, legal advice'' before coming forward,
Illinois Lottery Director Lori Montana said.
</P>
<P>
   The winners have up to one year to claim their prize. Unlike
some state lotteries, jackpot winners in the seven-state Big Game
are publicly identified.
</P>
<P>
   The winning numbers drawn Tuesday were 1, 2, 12, 33, 37 and Big
Money Ball 4. To win, a ticket had to match all six numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The drawing capped days of frenzy that sent lottery veterans and
first-timers alike scurrying for $1 chances at the big dream. Some
bought single tickets; others spent hundreds or even thousands.
Some went it alone, while others joined with friends and co-workers
for more chances.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it was over, the states that jointly offer the Big
Game had sold some 358 million tickets since the previous jackpot --
$15 million, in the Feb. 11 drawing -- was claimed by a resident of
Warren, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   How much the winners will take home depends on state taxes in
Michigan and Illinois. Lottery officials in both states estimated
each ticket could be worth about $7 million per year before taxes
in 26 annual payments.
</P>
<P>
   John Sweeney, owner of Sweeney's Citgo in Lake Zurich, struck it
rich in the form of a $1.8 million bonus for selling a jackpot
winner. Under Michigan's different rules, Mr. K's owner George
Kassab gets $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The big jackpot easily topped the previous American record, a
$295.7 million Powerball jackpot split two years ago by 13
machinists in Westerville, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The world lottery record is $1.2 billion, set in December by
Spain's El Gordo, or the Fat One, but that game spreads itself thin
by awarding thousands of prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Big Game: http://www.theofficialbiggame.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
