<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, May 11, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Appeals Court To Hear Elian Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The judicial panel from the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals scheduled a hearing Thursday to determine if 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez
is too young to seek asylum over the objections of his father. So far,
immigration officials and a federal judge in Miami have rejected the asylum
application signed by Elian and filed by his great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
Lawyers for both the U.S. government and Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the boy's father,
say Elian is not mature enough to make such choices. They say the father is the
one to decide for his son.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. House Votes To Remove Confederate Flag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Members of the South Carolina state House voted
Wednesday to remove the Confederate flag from atop the Statehouse dome. The
Senate already has approved a similar measure to remove the flag and put one up
at a monument on the Statehouse grounds. Democratic Gov. Jim Hodges has said he
supports removal. Lawmakers debated late into Wednesday night, with supporters
of the bill pleading with their fellow House members to approve the plan. The
bill passed 63-56. A procedural vote will be held Thursday before it goes back
to the Senate, which has to agree on minor differences in the two versions.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
IBM Launches New Web Servers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- International Business Machines Corp. on Thursday announced
it is shipping three new models of Web servers, the powerful computers that send
Web pages and other data over the Internet. One of the new models is set to
replace servers from rival Sun Microsystems Inc. in powering the ''phone book''
of the Internet. IBM said the new M80 is the world's fastest eight-processor Web
server, capable of serving out more than 3,200 average Web pages per second. It
also launched a cheaper six-processor Web server and a smaller server aimed at
e-business.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Arrest Falun Gong Followers
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Followers of the banned Falun Gong sect honored the birthday
of their movement's founder Thursday, protesting by the dozens in Tiananmen
Square only to meet swift and sometimes forceful arrest by Chinese police.
Followers tried to unfurl banners and raise their arms in a meditation pose used
by the group. Plainclothes police darted across the vast plaza to quell the
separate acts of civil disobedience by small groups of sect members. Police vans
raced back and forth to pick up the captured. At least 50 people were taken away
within about 90 minutes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
El Salvador Army Warehouse Explodes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- An underground arms warehouse caught fire
and exploded in the capital Wednesday night, spreading flames to nearby homes
and spewing at least 1,000 unexploded grenades into residential neighborhoods.
Dozens were injured. The cause of the fire was unknown, said Salvadoran Defense
Minister Gen. Juan Martinez Varela. Rescue workers extinguished the fire and
evacuated 500 people from nearby neighborhoods where at least 1,000 unexploded
grenades landed during the explosion, said Defense Ministry spokesman Col.
Roberto Alas. At least 50 military explosives specialists were sent to the area
to recover the grenades.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Evacuated for Fire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- A blaze that had been set to clear brush but raged
out of control over the weekend spread into Los Alamos and burned homes
Wednesday, forcing the evacuation of all 11,000 residents in this town, the site
of America's most storied nuclear laboratory. With wind gusts up to 50 mph
driving the flames through ponderosa pine, police, sheriff's and fire department
officials went door to door, urging people to pack up and get out as quickly as
possible. Smoke from the fire rose 20,000 feet above the ground.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Attack Appears Imminent in Sierra Leone
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Thousands of refugees poured into Freetown on
Wednesday as pro-government troops rushed to key towns near Sierra Leone's
steamy seaside capital to prepare for a feared rebel attack. U.N. peacekeepers,
the Sierra Leone army and pro-government militia fighters were consolidating
their forces along the road into the capital from Waterloo, 15 miles away, where
fleeing residents said they heard the sound of gunfire Wednesday morning.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks plunged Thursday, pushed down by continued
weakness on Wall Street. The Nikkei shed 440.00 points to 17,261.47 in early
trading.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers 97, Suns 96
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kobe Bryant, shrugging off an ineffective game, made a
15-foot jumper with 2.6 seconds remaining Wednesday night to give the Los
Angeles Lakers a 97-96 victory over the Phoenix Suns and a 2-0 lead in the
Western Conference semifinals. Shaquille O'Neal led the Lakers with 38 points,
20 rebounds and four blocked shots.
</P>
