<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Execs: Good Times Will Continue  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER, AP Economics Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy should slow a bit this year
but still turn in a record-breaking 10th year of uninterrupted
growth, the nation's top business executives are forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Council, composed of chief executives of the
nation's largest corporations, issued a revised outlook Wednesday
that predicted slower growth and higher inflation this year. But
the executives saw nothing on the horizon that will derail the
current expansion, which in February became the longest in history.
</P>
<P>
   ''The United States clearly continues to defy expectations and
council members don't see too much change over the near term,'' the
group said in a report presented by Sanford I. Weill, chairman of
financial giant Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said in the current economic good times, the top
priority for the Clinton administration and Congress should be
paying down the national debt but saw the administration's forecast
of total elimination of the debt held by the public by 2010 as too
optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   For the economy overall, the executives said they were expecting
a slowdown this year after three straight years in which the gross
domestic product expanded by more than 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve, which has already raised interest rates
five times in an effort to slow the economy and keep inflation
under control, is widely expected to raise rates again next Tuesday
given that the GDP grew at a brisk annual rate of 5.4 percent in
the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The business executives believe that inflation will increase
from last year's 2.7 percent rise in consumer prices but remain in
a moderate range for this year and coming years below 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they were forecasting a rise in overall inflation,
most council members said their own firms' pricing power is either
weaker than it was six months ago or little changed and they said
the big jump in oil prices has had little effect on their own
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the council members reported that labor market
conditions remained tight and many said that they were increasing
salaries to retain workers or boosting benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The business executives were evenly split over whether Democrat
Al Gore or Republican George W. Bush will win the White House in
November, while a slim majority believed that the Republicans would
retain their majority in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The business executives were nearly unanimous in their support
for President Clinton's push to get Congress to eliminate its
annual review of China's trade privileges with the United States,
thereby giving China permanent normal trade status.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Council, composed of more than 300 current and
former chief executives of large U.S. corporations, was meeting
today and Friday at a resort in White Sulphur Springs, W.Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
