<HEADLINE> Banks Given Privacy Rule Delay  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Over the objections of lawmakers and consumer
groups, federal regulators have agreed to delay by seven months the
deadline for U.S. banks and other financial companies to comply
with new rules designed to protect consumers' personal data.
</P>
<P>
   The privacy rules were supposed to take effect and become
mandatory in November. Preliminary drafts, however, elicited a
deluge of written comments from banks, investment firms, insurance
companies and other financial businesses contending it would be
difficult to meet that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Their complaints persuaded Federal Reserve governors, including
the central bank chairman, Alan Greenspan, to vote Wednesday to
make compliance voluntary Nov. 12 and mandatory by July 1, 2001.
The six other federal agencies involved in drafting the privacy
rules also granted the delay.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are gaining the right to request, in writing, that
their banks, securities firms and insurance companies not share
accountholders' personal data with third parties, such as
telemarketers.
</P>
<P>
   The rules also apply to a number of ''money'' businesses,
including consumer finance companies, department stores that issue
credit cards, money transmitters and money-order businesses, debt
collection agencies and credit bureaus.
</P>
<P>
   All financial companies will have to disclose their privacy
policies to customers at least once a year.
</P>
<P>
   The protections were mandated by legislation enacted last year
that removed Depression-era barriers and allowed banks, investment
firms and insurers to get into each other's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve officials suggested that financial services
companies able to beat the new deadline for disclosing their
privacy policies to customers can use that as a marketing tool.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver Ireland, the Fed's associate general counsel, said at an
open meeting of the Fed governors that banks and other financial
companies ''are going to have to use a lot of common sense'' in
following the rules. ''It's very difficult to know exactly how it's
going to play out in'' a financial company, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fed governor and vice chairman Roger Ferguson acknowledged that
regulators were giving the financial companies seeking the delay
''the benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Their decision angered some lawmakers and consumer activists.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Edward Markey, D-Mass., who has been active in consumer
privacy issues, has gathered signatures of 30 of his colleagues on
a letter of protest to Greenspan and the heads of the other
agencies, including the Treasury Department, the Federal Trade
Commission, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and the Securities
and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, 15 consumer and privacy groups, including the
Consumer Federation of America, Consumers Union, the American Civil
Liberties Union, Junkbusters and the Privacy Rights Clearinghouse,
also complained about the delay in a letter to the regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: New privacy regulations on Federal Reserve Web site:
http://www.federalreserve.gov/BoardDocs/press/boardacts/2000
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
