<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weak Euro Concerns Interest Rates  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- Economists have been looking for signs
the European Central Bank might step in to halt the euro's
tailspin.
</P>
<P>
   Boosting interest rates is one weapon the ECB might use today
when its governing board meets for one of its regular twice monthly
meetings. But economists largely expect the bank to keep its main
rate unchanged because it was increased to 3.75 percent just two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have speculated, however, that the central bank could
intervene in currency markets to boost the euro by buying up the
currency and selling dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Traders made a run on the euro last week, sending it to a record
low of 88.45 cents. The dive compelled finance ministers and the
ECB to issue a rare joint statement expressing support for the
common currency, which is shared by 11 European countries.
</P>
<P>
   The ECB's main concern is that a weak euro makes imports more
expensive, fueling inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to stem that tide, the ECB raised rates a
quarter-percentage point April 27. But that rate hike had little
impact on markets, mostly because investors expected it and
factored it into their investments.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the ECB really wants its hike to have an impact, it should
use a surprise effect,'' said Deutsche Bank economist Stefan
Schneider, although he said raising rates unexpectedly today could
just as easily spook markets.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts agreed saying raising rates that soon could be
seen as a knee-jerk reaction, contrary to the ''calm and stable
monetary policy'' that ECB President Duisenberg said late last
month the central bank was pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, rumors that the central bank would buy euros and sell
dollars halted the euro's tumble and pushed it back over the 90
cent mark.
</P>
<P>
   ECB officials have refused comment on whether the bank would
intervene in currency markets, saying only that it is one option
they have at their disposal. But intervention would take the
central bank into uncharted and potentially risky territory.
</P>
<P>
   The bank would have to delve into its foreign currency reserves
to sell dollars. And if it did so but was still unable to halt the
euro's decline, it could spark a panic reaction in currency
markets. Economists say the ECB is unlikely to intervene without
coordinating with the U.S. Federal Reserve and the Japanese central
bank, neither of which has yet shown a willingness to cooperate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
