<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Nears Passage of Land Bill  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite a vigorous debate over property
rights, the House appears to be steamrolling toward approving a $3
billion annual conservation fund for new parks, more federal and
state land purchases and restoration of coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which has broad bipartisan support and the
endorsement of the White House, was expected to pass when it comes
for a final vote today in the House. Its prospects in the Senate
are uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   In a string of votes late Wednesday, the House by solid margins
turned back amendments that would have reduced the amount of money
for new land purchases by the federal government and other
proposals aimed at providing increased protection to private
landowners.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill said the amendments were designed to
derail the legislation, which had been crafted during long
negotiations and represented -- as Rep. Don Young, R-Alaska
characterized it -- ''a fragile House of cards'' balancing various
political interests.
</P>
<P>
   The bill had 316 co-sponsors as it reached the House floor on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation calls for spending nearly $45 billion over 15
years on various conservation measures from creating urban parks
and to buying private inholdings surrounded by federal land.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the money is earmarked for coastal restoration
in areas affected by offshore oil and gas drilling -- including
wetlands restoration and dealing with beach erosion. Millions of
dollars also would go for wildfire protection, endangered species
programs and creation of conservation easements to help landowners,
including ranchers, avoid having to sell to developers.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the legislation calls for spending $900
million a year -- half by the federal government and the rest by
states -- to set aside public lands. Another $125 million would be
provided to local communities for urban parks and recreational
areas and $350 million for wildlife conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly $3 billion a year would come from the $4 billion to
$5 billion the government receives annually from oil leases, mainly
offshore drilling in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Young, chairman of the Resources Committee, called the bill
''the most comprehensive conservation and recreation legislation
the Congress has considered in decades.'' He dismissed criticism
that it threatens private land owners.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the bill unleashed a vigorous debate over property rights
with some western lawmakers arguing that it will open the way for a
rush of federal and state land purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ''What this is all about is federal acquisition of new land,''
declared Rep. Richard Pombo, R-Calif., during eight hours of debate
that lasted past midnight Wednesday. But Pombo's amendment to cut
the amount of federal money for land purchases in half, was
defeated 109-315.
</P>
<P>
   ''This bill does not hurt private property,'' insisted Young,
who along with Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., and Rep. George Miller,
D-Calif., had crafted the legislation in Young's committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't tell me it protects private property. It doesn't,''
declared Rep. Helen Chenoweth-Hage, R-Idaho, pounding the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the aim was to make good on promises that government
made long ago to set aside wild lands for future generations and to
create more open spaces and parks.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   House Bill: HR701
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   For more information on bill http://www.house.gov/resources/ocs
</P>
