<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 09:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School district considers same-sex prom dates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MECHANICVILLE, N.Y. (AP) -- A school board will consider changing
a prom policy that bars homosexual couples.
</P>
<P>
   Board president Joseph Waldron said recent media attention has
forced the board to look at the policy that prohibits same-sex
dates, single attendees and groups of more than two. Several
district students and the New York Civil Liberties Union called the
policy discriminatory against gay and lesbian couples.
</P>
<P>
   Waldron said the policy in place for years was intended to
protect the spirit of the prom, a formal celebration different from
other school dances. Other school dances, including a formal event
earlier in the year, are open to all students.
</P>
<P>
   ''This policy has never been about discriminating against
anyone,'' Waldron told The Daily Gazette of Schenectady. ''But I
think we can change it a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Any change, however, would likely be too late for Friday's prom.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have concerns with the policy,'' said Louise Roback,
director of the local chapter of the NYCLU. ''What it says to gay
and lesbian students is 'Stay home.'''
</P>
<P>
   Waldron said the issue probably will be addressed May 18.
Waldron said he would call a special meeting before the prom if a
formal request is made by a gay or lesbian couple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
