<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thunderstorms batter state  </HEADLINE>
The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Violent thunderstorms stalked the state
Wednesday, whipping up winds, pelting golf ball-sized hail and
swelling creeks and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Severe flooding in the Southern Tier put some bridges
underwater. Some 10 families in Newark Valley in Tioga County were
evacuated because of the storms. The Red Cross set up a shelter at
Newark Valley High School, and more than 20 roads were closed due
to the flooding. The school west of Binghamton is closed today
after as many as three dozen Tioga County roads were closed at one
point Wednesday because of flooding.
</P>
<P>
   High water washed out two bridges -- one in Newark Valley, the
other in nearby Owego. Several secondary roads in Tioga County also
were damaged. Earlier in the day, roadway flooding occurred in
several communities in Broome County.
</P>
<P>
   The storms also caused minor damage to a few buildings in the
Southern Tier. A large chunk of concrete fell from one downtown
Binghamton building, narrowly missing pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   In the Albany suburb of Colonie, two people were struck by
lightning, with one of them hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day Rome car dealer Wayne Vogt said he'd sooner forget.
</P>
<P>
   ''Basically, the storm came and was in and out in about 10
minutes,'' Vogt said. ''But it came with a vengeance. It got every
vehicle on the lot -- new, used. I've got about 100 new and probably
150 used vehicles, and there's damage on them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogt said the damage was fixable, but the cars will never quite
look the same.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Lyman, spokesman for the Niagara Mohawk utility company,
said that fallen trees and lightning bolts had caused scattered
power outages in Saratoga County and other areas of eastern New
York. The outages, except for perhaps some isolated cases, were
corrected by today, Lyman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're working on them all,'' Lyman said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Cortland and Tompkins counties reported flash
flooding and downed trees and utility poles but no major problems.
Two-inch hail was seen in Chenango County with smaller hail spotted
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Madison County officials reported hail one-inch in diameter.
</P>
<P>
   The southern part of the state received about one-and-a-half
inches of rain.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rain and hail came down in a burst, caused some flooding,
and then it was over,'' said Michelle Egburtson, a dispatcher with
the Penn Yan Police Department in Yates County. Emergency
management officials there measured hail of up to 1} inches.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday afternoon, the National Weather Service advised
conditions that could spawn a tornado near Ithaca, but the twisters
never developed.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were a bunch of individual storm cells,'' said Mike
Cempa, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service in Albany.
''It was somewhat of an unusual event.''
</P>
<P>
   Cempa said two fronts collided in the southern part of the state
and sent the strong weather systems northward.
</P>
<P>
   Rain and thunderstorms were expected to continue throughout the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday will bring mostly cloudy skies and the chance of
showers and highs in the 60s, Cempa said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
