<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Open Higher in New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher in early trading today as a
report of lower retail sales calmed investors who have been selling
stocks amid fears about rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 69.22 at 10,437.00.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. the Nasdaq composite
index was up 22.47 at 3,407.20, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 9.65 at 1,392.70.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose after the Commerce Department said retail sales fell
by a surprising 0.2 percent. Analysts had expected a gain of 0.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were quick to cite bad weather in April that kept many
Americans out of the stores. But the decline raised some hopes that
the Federal Reserve's series of interest rate increases is
succeeding in slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is widely expected to raise interest rates again at its
May 16 meeting. Economists are divided on whether central bankers
will stick to their strategy of boosting rates by a
quarter-percentage point at a time, or whether they will opt for a
half-percentage point increase this time.
</P>
<P>
   Rate-sensitive stocks rose after the retail sales report was
released. J.P. Morgan rose 2 15/16 to 125 9/16..
</P>
<P>
   But recent weakness in the technology sector prevailed. Applied
Materials fell 4| to 80. After the close of trading Wednesday, the
company reported operating earnings of 55 cents a share, in line
with analysts' estimates. Investors had hoped for the company, a
leading maker of equipment used in the semiconductor industry, to
exceed estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 123.64 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.15 to 478.43.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stocks overcame a steep selloff in Japan. The Nikkei stock
average plunged 4.63 percent to its lowest close in 7{ months, with
technology, telecommunications and financial-services stocks
leading the way down. Traders blamed the weakness on Wall Street's
decline on Wednesday, when the Dow fell 168 points and the Nasdaq
plunged 200 points.
</P>
<P>
   European markets were unscathed by the heavy selling in Japan.
Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 0.8 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
was up 2.2 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
