<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise in New York   </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today as a report of a
slowdown in retail sales calmed investors who have been selling
stocks amid fears about rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 137.07 at 10,504.85.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. the Nasdaq composite
index was up 85.80 at 3,470.53, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 21.20 at 1,404.75.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose after the Commerce Department said retail sales
surprisingly fell 0.2 percent. Economists had expected a gain of
0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were quick to cite bad weather in April that kept many
Americans out of the stores. But the decline raised some hopes that
the Federal Reserve's series of interest rate increases is
succeeding in slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is widely expected to raise interest rates again at its
May 16 meeting. Economists are divided on whether central bankers
will stick to their strategy of boosting rates by a
quarter-percentage point at a time, or whether they will opt for a
half-percentage point increase this time.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sales report alone won't dissuade the Fed from the
harsher, half-point increase, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that the volatile stock market and higher interest
rates have started to slow consumer spending,'' said Stan Shipley,
