<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scott Smith sentenced to 6 years in prison  </HEADLINE>
By STRAT DOUTHAT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- Former New Milford police Officer Scott
Smith was sentenced today to six years in prison for the fatal
shooting of a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, the first Connecticut officer charged with murder for an
act in the line of duty, faced 5 to 40 years in prison after he was
convicted of intentional manslaughter in the December 1998 death of
Franklyn Reid.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was white; Reid was black.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing came four days after Judge Charles D. Gill
rejected Smith's request for a new trial. Defense lawyers had
argued that juror misconduct tainted the trial. The judge said he
found little evidence that would support that.
</P>
<P>
   A group of black activists and more than 20 nonuniformed
officers sat in the packed courtroom as Smith said he ''sincerely
believed (Reid) was trying to gain access to a weapon. I shot
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Smith told the court in quiet tones how he had gone to
work that day and felt he was doing his duty as he assisted a
fellow officer in pursuing Reid, who was wanted on several
outstanding warrants including harassment and failure to appear in
court.
</P>
<P>
   Before handing down the sentence, Gill spoke of the difficulties
police officers face every day on the job. But he said a crime had
been committed and the law had to be upheld.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the sentence was fair,'' said Pearlylyn Reid, the
victim's mother. ''We had faith in Judge Gill from day one.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney John J. Kelly immediately asked that Smith be
freed on bond pending appeal, and Gill granted the request. Smith
posted the $250,000 bond soon after the sentencing and left the
courthouse, flanked by his attorney and New Milford police
officers.
</P>
<P>
   He paused to wave to a group of about a half-dozen people who
sang hymns and held signs that read ''Support Scott Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I appreciate all the support,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said he was grateful the judge handed down the minimum
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, 28, who was fired after his conviction, said he shot Reid
after a foot chase because he believed Reid was reaching for a
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the shooting, Reid, 27, was unarmed. A short
folding knife was discovered in the pocket of a jacket found a few
feet away from his body.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, witnesses reported seeing Smith chase Reid.
One witness said he saw Smith draw his gun and saw Reid sitting
down. Another testified that Smith's foot was on Reid's back just
before the shooting. Prosecutors said evidence from Reid's clothes
and autopsy backed up this version of events and contradicted
Smith's claim that Reid was on his knees and possibly reaching for
a weapon when he fired.
</P>
<P>
   ''This community has viewed the shooting as morally and legally
improper,'' said Waterbury State's Attorney John Connelly, who
prosecuted the case. ''Justice was served.''
</P>
<P>
   The defense filed a motion for a new trial three weeks after
Smith was convicted. Kelly cited nine instances of possible
misconduct, including allegations that one juror flashed a badge
and claimed special knowledge of police procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Gill met last week with all 12 jurors, questioning them about
some of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court, after listening and observing all 12 jurors on the
subject, finds that there is absolutely no basis for this claim of
misconduct,'' Gill ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past two months, the town of 24,000 has seen two of
its police officers convicted in charges relating to separate
civilian deaths. A month after Smith's conviction, William
Scribner, a 14-year veteran of the police force, was found guilty
of negligent homicide stemming from the June 1998 death of
17-year-old girl whose car was struck by his speeding cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Former New Milford Police Chief James Sweeney retired last
summer to take a job with a private school. He said his departure
had nothing to do with the department turmoil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-11-00 1152 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0084 </DOCNO>
