<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Mostly Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today as a report of a
slowdown in retail sales calmed investors who have been selling
stocks amid fears about rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 160.12 at 10,527.90.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 94.69 at 3,479.42, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 21.60 at 1,404.65.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose after the Commerce Department said retail sales fell
0.2 percent. Economists had expected a increase of 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were quick to cite bad weather in April that kept many
Americans out of the stores. But the decline raised some hopes that
the Federal Reserve's series of interest rate increases is
succeeding in slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is widely expected to raise interest rates again at its
May 16 meeting. Economists are divided on whether central bankers
will stick to their strategy of boosting rates by a
quarter-percentage point at a time, or whether they will opt for a
half-percentage point increase this time.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sales report alone won't dissuade the Fed from the
harsher, half-point increase, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that the volatile stock market and higher interest
rates have started to slow consumer spending,'' said Stan Shipley,
senior economist at Merrill Lynch. ''However, this one-month
slowdown should not derail the Fed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rate-sensitive stocks rose after the retail sales report was
released. J.P. Morgan rose 4] to 126, and American Express rose 1
5/16 to 49 1/16.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which fell sharply on Wednesday, rebounded 5 15/16 to
112, contributing to the Dow's advance.
</P>
<P>
   But some skittishness in the technology sector prevailed.
Applied Materials recovered from a steep early drop and was up ~ to
85{. After the close of trading Wednesday, the company reported
operating earnings of 55 cents a share, in line with analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said Applied Materials failed to get a bounce from the
strong earnings report because many investors were hoping for the
company, a leading maker of equipment used in the semiconductor
industry, to exceed estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 7-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 437.03 million
shares, ahead of Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 10.49 to
484.77.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stocks overcame a sharp selloff in Japan. The Nikkei stock
average plunged 4.63 percent to its lowest close in 7{ months, with
technology, telecommunications and financial-services stocks
leading the way down. Traders blamed the weakness on Wall Street's
decline on Wednesday, when the Dow fell 168 points and the Nasdaq
plunged 200 points.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
