<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Chides Tech Biz Over Pay Gap  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even in the high-flying, highly paid world of
high technology, women earn less than men, President Clinton said
today.
</P>
<P>
   ''The gap is still far, far too wide'' in high-tech and other
fields, ''and women and their families are paying a terrible
price,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, women earn about 75 percent as much as equally
qualified men, according to a variety of government and independent
studies. The results are about the same for the information
technology, or IT, industry, even though the industry has
experienced a dramatic growth in jobs and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fewer than one in three of these high-tech, high-wage jobs are
women,'' Clinton said at a White House commemoration of ''Equal Pay
Day,'' the theoretical point in the year when women and better-paid
men begin earning equal pay for equal work.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the disparity ''another digital divide,'' the
term he uses to describe the shortage of computer skills and access
in poor and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   He was joined by Karen Simmons-Beathea, who was fired by a
Baltimore cable television station after complaining about her
salary. Her male replacement, whom she considers less qualified,
was offered a salary some 20 percent higher, according to an Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ''I grieved the loss and I called the EEOC,'' she said, to
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Information technology work, which includes computer
programming, design and engineering, is growing at a furious pace.
Since 1983, employment in the industry grew 81 percent, according
to the White House report, while job growth in the general economy
was 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Women benefit from the overall affluence of the industry --
making salaries nearly 50 percent above women in the wider work
force, the White House report found.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, an important gender employment gap exists in the IT
occupations,'' said the report from the White House Council of
Economic Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Women make up only 29 percent of the five basic information
technology job categories studied in the report, although they are
47 percent of the work force at large, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, women are scarcest in the high-tech jobs that pay the
most, the report found. For example, only 10 percent of electrical
engineers are women, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   While 20 percent of male high-tech workers earn $69,740 or more,
only 7 percent of female workers earn that much, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   None of that is very surprising to Jason Mahler, vice president
and general counsel for the Computer and Communications Industry
Association, a Washington trade group.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's difficult to argue that there isn't some truth to it,''
Mahler said. ''Anyone who knows anything about the tech industry
can just anecdotally tell that there's a lower number of women.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mahler said much of the problem begins in schools, long
before women vie for high-tech jobs. Too few women seek education
in fields that will prepare them for the best-paying jobs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something we for a long time have tried to address.
... We haven't fully succeeded,'' Mahler said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1254 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bridgeport, Conn., bishop named to succeed O'Connor in New York  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bishop Edward M. Egan said today that the spirit
of the late Cardinal O'Connor will be with him when he takes the
helm of the nation's most visible Roman Catholic archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ''The archdiocese of New York is an extraordinary community of
faith. To be invited to serve this splendid archdiocese as its
shepherd is quite humbling,'' the 68-year-old bishop of Bridgeport,
Conn., said at a news conference. ''The responsibility has,
however, been accepted with great joy.''
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, which comes a week after O'Connor's death from
brain cancer, was announced this morning at the Vatican by Pope
John Paul II. It will be formalized at a June 19 ceremony at St.
Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   Facing reporters in a simple black priest's suit with a white
clerical collar, Egan first praised his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   After a brain operation last September, O'Connor ''suffered a
great deal, and showed us all how to live with physical weakness.
... He was an inspiration to a countless number of people, and we
are grateful for his leadership and his courage.''
</P>
<P>
   The bishop said he remembered his time working with the cardinal
in New York in the 1980s, and said of his new responsibilities, ''I
think the cardinal will be on my side.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on how he feels about moving from a relatively small
diocese to New York, he said: ''My first reaction was, 'Edward, get
down on your knees and beg the Lord to give you a hand, and don't
get up too quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   His second reaction: ''Edward, get up off your knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall and stately, with a stentorian voice, the bishop is a fine
speaker who follows a cardinal known for his eloquence and humor.
</P>
<P>
   With Egan, the Vatican has put a staunch conservative in the
Roman Catholic Church's most prominent position in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   As head of the Connecticut diocese since 1988, he is known for
backing the pope's condemnation of abortion, homosexual acts and
contraception. He has also raised controversy in his diocese for
his defense of the church in the face of a sexual molestation suit
against local priests.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the post as spiritual leader of New York's 2.4 million
Catholics, Egan is widely expected to be elevated to cardinal the
next time the pope selects new ''princes'' of the church.
</P>
<P>
   He handled the media in a personable but authoritative manner,
telling about 100 reporters, ''I look forward to having great fun
with you in this wonderful diocese,'' and noting jokingly: ''I
don't feel like the boss, but give me a little time and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan said his first action will be to meet with the priests in
his new archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that the number one attraction ... is a happy group
of priests and a happy group of religious,'' meaning nuns, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Answering some questions in Italian and Spanish, the
archbishop-designate demonstrated that he'll quickly be in touch
with two ethnic groups that comprise more than half the
archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   But he also showed the kind of toughness expected in a city Pope
John Paul II has called ''the capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the problem of teen-age pregnancy, Egan became a bit
testy, telling a reporter: ''I didn't hear you and your question is
out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   And like O'Connor, he was not at a loss for words when politics
popped up.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would take advice from Hillary Rodham Clinton,
a Chicago-area native like the bishop, he said, ''Perhaps Mrs.
Clinton could give me some advice about being a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   An expert on canon law, Egan is well known at the Holy See after
years of work at the Vatican. In his dozen years in Bridgeport, he
won a reputation as a tireless recruiter of new priests and a deft
fund-raiser in a diocese that includes Fairfield County, one of the
richest in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, he faces an archdiocese strapped for funds and
struggling to keep its schools and institutions solvent.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment brings him back to a city where he was appointed
in 1985 by O'Connor, at the pope's request, to be auxiliary bishop
and vicar for education.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was born in 1932 in the Chicago suburb of Oak Park,
birthplace of Ernest Hemingway, and ordained a priest for the
Chicago archdiocese in 1957. He studied theology at Rome's
prestigious Gregorian Pontifical University, where he went on to
obtain a doctorate in canon law.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a bachelor's degree in philosophy from St. Mary of the
Lake Seminary in Mundelein, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Egan served from 1972 to 1985 on the Vatican tribunal that
decides important juridical matters, including whether to grant
annulments. Once elevated to cardinal, Egan would vote in a
conclave for a new pope following the death of a pontiff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
