<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Delphi Shareholders Rebuff Board  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KOKOMO, Ind. (AP) -- Shareholders of Delphi Automotive Systems
Corp. rebuffed the board's recommendation and voted to eliminate a
corporate provision to discourage hostile takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   The nonbinding vote came at the first annual meeting on
Wednesday since the auto parts company was separated from parent
General Motors Corp. a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   In the vote, 213 million shares were voted to eliminate the
poison pill while 140 million were cast against a repeal.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman J.T. Battenberg III said Delphi directors will review
the issue and consider the available options, but said the board is
not compelled to repeal the poison pill.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the favorable vote represented a minority -- 38
percent -- of the company's total 563 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The board had recommended keeping the poison pill policy, which
triggers a variety of defenses whenever a single shareholder
acquires 15 percent or more of the outstanding stock.
</P>
<P>
   The ''poison-pill'' defense was adopted in 1998 when Delphi
still was part of GM.
</P>
<P>
   The shareholder who submitted the proposal to end the policy,
John Chevedden of Redondo Beach, Calif., argued it did not give
shareholders a voice in such situations.
</P>
<P>
   He said stockholders ought to have the opportunity to vote on a
new policy and argued the plan currently in place gives Delphi's
directors absolute power to veto any proposed business combination,
even one regarded as beneficial to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The Troy, Mich.-based Delphi employs about 201,000 workers in 37
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
