<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Massive Party Held at Cannes  </HEADLINE>
By JOCELYN NOVECK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France (AP) -- As the sun rose over Cannes on Thursday
morning, the big business news was that Miramax had bought the U.S.
rights to ''Vatel,'' a lavish period piece set in the court of
Louis XIV. But that's not what anyone was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   They were talking about the film's opening-night party.
</P>
<P>
   There are parties and there are parties, and they happen every
night at this festival on the Riviera. So it's easy to get a bit
blase. But this one, it's safe to say, will remain on the lips of
Cannes-goers for a while to come.
</P>
<P>
   Some lips, though, were sealed -- namely those of Gaumont, the
French company that financed the film, when asked the party's price
tag. ''No, we'll never reveal that,'' said a spokeswoman -- who then
asked that her name not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Director Roland Joffe was only a bit more forthcoming, saying
the party did indeed cost less -- ''a little less'' -- than the $35
million it took to make the film.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vatel,'' starring Uma Thurman and Gerard Depardieu, is based
on the tragic, true story of Francois Vatel, a steward to a French
prince who's called upon to prepare an elaborate, three-day feast
for the visiting Louis XIV and his entire Versailles court.
</P>
<P>
   Vatel, played by Depardieu, is loyal to his aging boss, who
desperately needs to gain the king's favor, organizing the most
dazzling festivities in his power, with scarce resources. The food
is exquisite, as is the entertainment: exotic dancers, singers on
floats suspended in the air, sudden bursts of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
   The film's strength is its faithful recreation of these events.
The party's strength was its faithful recreation of the film.
</P>
<P>
   For one evening, the multistory festival palace was transformed
into the prince's Chateau de Chantilly. As 700 guests -- among them
Thurman and Depardieu, Jeremy Irons, Andie MacDowell, Kristin Scott
Thomas and Jennifer Jason Leigh -- entered, they were greeted by
nearly 100 actors in period costume, going about the business of
throwing a huge party.
</P>
<P>
   Young noblemen tipped their wide-brimmed hats to the ladies. A
young girl sang softly, accompanied by a harpist. Inside,
maidservants in headscarves folded laundry. Pheasants and roosters
hung from hooks. Gargantuan fish waited to be cleaned and cooked.
Rows of onions and potatoes stood by the chopping block.
</P>
<P>
   Recreating the glorious ice sculptures in the film, a real-life
ice sculptor carved into the evening. A pastry chef turned out
concoctions, offering guests a taste.
</P>
<P>
   In the dining room, menu cards in 17th-century writing announced
the feast: charlotte of lobster, sea bass with fennel, a raspberry
dessert (with Chantilly cream, of course). On a lighted stage
behind a screen sat the royal party: actors dressed as the king and
queen, entertained all night by dancers and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   And then the finale. Just as in the film, where bursts of
fireworks come out of nowhere, delighting the king and his court,
flames of white erupted about the room. And when the crowd thought
it was over, the flower pots on each table suddenly erupted,
showering cascades of sparkles. (One shuddered to think of the fire
hazard, but it worked as planned.)
</P>
<P>
   Film companies regularly throw parties to fete their films at
Cannes, and Gaumont's party for ''The Fifth Element'' in 1997 was
also huge and expensive. But many Cannes-goers said the ''Vatel''
party was the most memorable in years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the real Vatel would have been proud,'' Joffe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1329 </TRAILER>
