<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossils Found in Georgia Republic  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL RECER, AP Science Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fossils unearthed in the Republic of Georgia
and dated at 1.7 million years old may be from the first humanlike
species to migrate from Africa, possibly the ancestral home of all
humans.
</P>
<P>
   A team of researchers reports in the journal Science that parts
of two skulls found by accident at the site of a medieval castle
are the fossilized remains of an early human species called Homo
erectus thought to have arisen in Africa about 1.8 million years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery suggests the early Homo erectus became the first
two-legged migrants within a few thousand years of their
evolutionary appearance in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the first time that we have seen fossils that look very
much like Africa fossils outside of Africa,'' said Susan C. Anton,
a co-author of the study. ''We believe these fossils represent the
first (humanlike) species to move out of Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   The study will appear in Science on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Anton, an expert on early humans at the University of Florida,
Gainesville, said the fossils were discovered with primitive stone
tools -- little more than rock flakes -- that were first developed in
Africa about 1.8 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies had suggested that human migration from Africa
waited for the development about 1.6 million years ago of more
sophisticated stone tools, called Acheulean tools, before they left
the cradle continent and dispersed into the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   But Anton said the new finding shows it was biology, not new
technology, that prompted the dispersal.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are hominids with bigger brains and bodies than the ones
who came before,'' said Anton. ''The ability to disperse may have
something to do with this biological change.''
</P>
<P>
   Homo erectus, which is called Homo ergaster by some experts, had
more animal fat and meat in its diet than earlier hominids, she
said. The drive for meat may have prompted the species to leave
Africa in search of better hunting grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Dating of the fossils is key to the conclusions, and co-author
Carl C. Swisher III of the Berkeley Geochronology Center in
California said the age of 1.7 million years is nailed down in
three different ways.
</P>
<P>
   A lava layer found just below the fossils was chemically dated
at 1.8 million years. Found with the human remains were fossils of
a rodent known to have lived only between 2 million and 1.6 million
years ago. And, finally, rocks found with the fossils bear the
signature of change in the Earth's magnetic polarity that is known
to have happened 1.7 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything fits on the age,'' said Swisher. ''There is no
discrepancy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1401 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cop Kick Falun Gong Protesters  </HEADLINE>
By CHARLES HUTZLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- Police on Thursday tackled, kicked and dragged
away dozens of devotees of the banned Falun Gong sect who attempted
to mark the birthday of their movement's founder in Beijing's
central Tiananmen square.
</P>
<P>
   Sect followers who dropped to the paving stones to meditate or
tried to unfurl banners were swiftly snatched up by plainclothes
and uniformed security officers and forced inside waiting vans.
Police kicked several followers after they were shoved into the
vans and one woman who ran from officers was tackled and sent
sprawling.
</P>
<P>
   Security officers raced through the square to stop the protests
and by midmorning had detained some 50 followers -- among them a
middle aged woman. Police vans circled the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Two Western tourists were also detained by police, apparently
for taking photographs of the demonstrations. At least three
foreign journalists had their film confiscated.
</P>
<P>
   The protest seemed much like a replay of the confrontation
between sect members and police on April 25 when followers gathered
for the first anniversary of a demonstration by 10,000
practitioners. The 1999 demonstration had shocked China's leaders,
and three months later they banned the group as a public menace and
a threat to Communist Party rule.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong followers have continued to stage protests nearly
every day in Tiananmen Square, despite 9{ months of repression, a
smear campaign in the state media and the jailing of thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's demonstration was unusually large.
</P>
<P>
   The day marked what Chinese traditionally regard as the
anniversary of the birth of Buddhism's founder, Gautama Siddharta.
Falun Gong followers believe their master, Li Hongzhi, was born on
that day as well.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chinese practitioners assume this is the date to honor the
master,'' said Gail Rachlin, a spokeswoman for Falun Gong in New
York. She expected more protests Saturday, Li's birthday by the
Western calendar and the anniversary of Falun Gong's founding in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials say records show that Li was born on July 7,
1952 and accuse him of changing his birth date to add to his
mystique.
</P>
<P>
   The sect's leader has not been seen in public since shortly
after China banned Falun Gong last July and few clues are available
as to his whereabouts. Li left China for New York in 1998 after the
government quietly banned his books, and the group's overseas Web
sites show a picture of him meditating in the mountains without
saying when or where the photograph was taken.
</P>
<P>
   A former government grain clerk, Li founded Falun Gong as an
offshoot of traditional slow-motion exercises known as qi gong. To
those, he added a blend of Buddhist and Taoist philosophy and his
own often unorthodox ideas. Followers claim that practice promotes
health and good citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government, however, has accused the group of
causing 1,559 deaths -- mostly among devotees who refused medical
treatment -- leading to psychiatric problems in 600 others and
cheating people by making them spend lavishly on books and
teachings.
</P>
<P>
   The government claimed victory anew over the group Thursday. In
an editorial carried in national newspapers, the official Xinhua
News Agency claimed that 98 percent of all Falun Gong followers had
severed ties to the group.
</P>
<P>
   ''The victory has greatly raised the political vigilance of the
nation, saved and protected a large number of the cheated, punished
the evil and maintained the social stability of the country,''
Xinhua said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1404 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 153; Nasdaq Up 83  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today as a report of a
slowdown in retail sales calmed investors who have been selling
stocks amid fears about rising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 153.18 at 10,520.96.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 83.43 at 3,468.16, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 20.20 at 1,403.25.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose after the Commerce Department said retail sales fell
0.2 percent. Economists had expected a increase of 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were quick to cite bad weather in April that kept many
Americans out of the stores. But the decline raised some hopes that
the Federal Reserve's series of interest rate increases is
succeeding in slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is widely expected to raise interest rates again at
meeting on Tuesday. Economists are divided on whether central
bankers will stick to their strategy of boosting rates by a
quarter-percentage point at a time, or whether they will opt for a
half-percentage point increase this time.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sales report alone won't dissuade the Fed from the
harsher, half-point increase, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that the volatile stock market and higher interest
rates have started to slow consumer spending,'' said Stan Shipley,
senior economist at Merrill Lynch. ''However, this one-month
slowdown should not derail the Fed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rate-sensitive stocks rose after the retail sales report was
released. J.P. Morgan rose 4 9/16 to 127 3/16, and Citigroup rose 1
13/16 to 58\.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which fell sharply on Wednesday, rebounded 7 3/16 to
113\, the strongest gain among all 30 Dow components.
</P>
<P>
   But some skittishness in the technology sector prevailed.
Applied Materials recovered from a steep early drop but remained
down ] at 84\. After the close of trading Wednesday, the company
reported operating earnings of 55 cents a share, in line with
analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said Applied Materials failed to get a bounce from the
strong earnings report because many investors were hoping for the
company, a leading maker of equipment used in the semiconductor
industry, to exceed estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 637.73 million
shares, slightly behind Wednesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 10.90 to
485.18.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stocks overcame a sharp selloff in Japan. The Nikkei stock
average plunged 4.63 percent to its lowest close in 7{ months, with
technology, telecommunications and financial-services stocks
leading the way down. Traders blamed the weakness on Wall Street's
decline on Wednesday, when the Dow fell 168 points and the Nasdaq
plunged 200 points.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
