<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Interest Rates Unchanged  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- European Central Bank president Wim
Duisenberg refused to take the role of scapegoat Thursday over the
euro's decline, keeping the door open to the possibility of market
intervention and variable interest rates in his continuing battle
to keep consumer prices stable.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not prepared to take the blame for the decline in the
euro,'' Duisenberg said after the ECB's governing council decided
to keep its key interest rate steady at 3.75 percent during its
regular, twice-monthly meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are achieving the main goal we at the ECB were hired for --
achieving price stability,'' Duisenberg said, denying rumors he
would resign.
</P>
<P>
   His comments echoed those made by the ECB last Friday after
traders made a run on the euro, sending it to a record low of 88.45
cents. The dive compelled finance ministers and the ECB to issue a
rare joint statement expressing support for the common currency,
which is shared by 11 European countries.
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's rate decision, the euro dropped a quarter of a
cent to 90.56 cents and languished around that level for the rest
of the afternoon. In New York, the euro was trading at 90.10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the stock markets barely budged after the expected
decision, though many finished the day higher, cheered by news from
the United States about weaker-than-expected consumer spending
data.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has lost 24 percent of its value since debuting in
January 1999. Nonethless, Duisenberg repeated the ECB's cheery
mantra Thursday, underlining rosy forecasts for economic growth and
trying to reassure average citizens that the withering euro is not
draining their pocketbooks.
</P>
<P>
   ''The citizens of Europe can be confident that their savings and
pensions will keep their value over time,'' Duisenberg said. ''How
can one call a currency characterized by stable prices weak? I
don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Inflation in the region peaked at 2.1 percent in March, but is
expected to tail off for the rest of the year and remain below the
ECB's mandate of keeping price rises under 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem on the horizon is that a weak euro could push
inflation higher again by driving up the prices of imports, which
can spill over into higher consumer prices at the corner store.
</P>
<P>
   Boosting interest rates is one weapon the ECB could have used to
bolster the value of the faltering euro. But the bank kept its
hands off Thursday -- after increasing its main refinancing rate by
a quarter-percentage point to 3.75 percent just two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is best for today is for the ECB to just sit and wait,''
said Bernhard Pfaff, an economist with Commerzbank in Frankfurt.
''Markets are pretty nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Duisenberg would not rule out using two other tools that
could turn the euro around: intervention in currency markets by
buying up the currency and selling dollars, or switching to
variable interest rate system.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, rumors that the central bank would buy euros and sell
dollars halted the euro's tumble and pushed it back over the 90
cent mark.
</P>
<P>
   Another option is for the bank to shift from a fixed interest
rate of 3.75 percent to a variable rate. Variable rates are set by
banks telling the ECB not only how much money they want to borrow,
but also what interest rate they want to borrow at.
</P>
<P>
   That can lead to overall higher interest rates. But it can also
leave the ECB's main interest rates exposed to the ravages of
market speculation that could boost rates too high, too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Duisenberg said switching to variable rates Thursday would be
the wrong thing to do, although he said such a switch could still
be down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ''In volatile and violent markets which we are going through
now, we didn't want to install a new element of uncertainty and
volatility,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
