<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Rick Thoman, just 13 months into his
tenure as chief executive officer of troubled business machines
manufacturer Xerox Corp., was fired Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman was asked by members of the board of directors to resign,
a source familiar with Thursday's events told The Associated Press.
An announcement from the company was expected after the stock
market closed Thursday afternoon, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox spokeswoman Crista Carone said the company had no
immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox last month reported a $243 million loss in the first
quarter and has struggled for more than a year with slumping sales
and a balky sales force restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   The loss had been expected following the announcement in March
that the company would lay off 5,200 employees and close several
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox took a pretax charge of $625 million to cover the
restructuring. The company also took a pretax charge of $27 million
for research and development costs associated with its acquisition
of Tektronix Inc.'s color printer division.
</P>
<P>
   Before the two extraordinary charges, Xerox had quarterly
earnings of $220 million, or 30 cents per share, down 36 percent
compared with $343 million, or 48 cents per share, a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues in the quarter rose 3 percent to $4.43 billion, up from
$4.30 billion in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman, former chief financial officer at IBM, was hired as the
No. 2 executive at Xerox in June 1997. A cost-cutter who helped
reverse IBM's declining fortunes, he was seen as a leader who could
help Xerox regain its dominant position in the small and large
office machine markets.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, best known for its photocopying machines, has struggled
against Hewlett-Packard and Canon in the small and home-office
markets.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate word on a successor to Thoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
