<DOCNO> APW20000511.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parishioners and priests offer new archbishop prayers and good wishes </HEADLINE>
By JUDIE GLAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bishop Edward M. Egan's appointment by Pope John
Paul II as the ninth archbishop of New York was received Thursday
with prayers and good wishes from parishioners and those who know
him.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's a man of vision and foresight,'' said Monsignor
Peter Finn, who worked in the archdiocese's press office when Egan
was an auxiliary bishop here.
</P>
<P>
   The pope announced this morning that Egan, 68, would succeed
Cardinal John O'Connor, who died May 3 of brain cancer. And at his
first news conference since taking the helm, Egan seemed at ease
with the press.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't feel like the boss, but give me time and I will,'' he
said with a broad smile. ''I want to be a New Yorker,'' he said at
one point.
</P>
<P>
   ''Archbishop Egan will be a strong and dynamic leader, and he
brings many priestly gifts and talents to this challenging
responsibility,'' said Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of Newark,
N.J., a onetime candidate to succeed O'Connor. ''His mission of
energetic and caring, pastoral leadership of the Church of
Bridgeport has well prepared him for the leadership of this most
important American diocese.''
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Finn, who is now pastor at St. Joseph-St. Thomas
Church in Staten Island, predicted Egan would be well-received in
New York. He called Egan ''a very energetic and forward looking
leader'' and remembered him as ''a man with a wonderful sense of
humor, a bright man.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan has been bishop of the Bridgeport, Conn. diocese since
December 1988, but he earlier served 3{ years as an auxiliary
bishop and vicar of education in New York.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Patrick's Cathedral -- the Fifth Avenue landmark and seat
of Egan's new archdiocese -- prayers were offered for him at two
early morning Masses. Parishioners going in and out of the
cathedral said they would welcome the new archbishop's leadership --
though many noted O'Connor still was greatly missed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He looks like a good man,'' said Elssy Mino, 58, a saleswoman
from Bayside, Queens. ''Nobody's going to replace O'Connor, but I
think Egan will be OK. He seems very sweet and nice.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure, O'Connor is a hard act to follow, but so was Spellman,''
said Martin Shanahan, a consultant from New Jersey, who often
attends Mass at St. Patrick's. ''He'll do fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People are open minded and so it'll be just fine,'' Marc
Taylor, a financial analyst from Queens said outside the cathedral.
''After all, it's really between you and the man upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The telegenic Cardinal Francis Spellman headed the archdiocese
during the 1950s and turbulent 1960s -- a time of vast change in the
Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Auxiliary Bishop Patrick Ahern, of Manhattan's Church of
St. Thomas More, said the archdiocese's 2.4 million Catholics could
not help but make comparisons between Egan and O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course, there will always be noticeable differences,'' said
Ahern. ''Everybody's fingerprint is unique and each comes to his
task bringing his own talents, charisma, intelligence and
abilities.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Ahern said O'Connor was a true preacher who
enjoyed celebrating Sunday Mass. Egan rarely led services in
Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor's predecessors, Cardinal Terence Cooke and Spellman,
rarely celebrated Masses either.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was known in Bridgeport for his fundraising abilities and
efforts to bring new priests into the diocese.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to remember that Cardinal O'Connor was as different
from Cardinal Cooke as chalk from cheese,'' said Ahern. ''Different
personalities but both served New York well, as I'm sure Bishop
Egan will.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan becomes the 12th bishop of New York and ninth archbishop.
New York was a diocese, run by a bishop, from 1808 until 1850 when
it was elevated to an archdiocese. It stretches across 10 counties
and includes three boroughs in the city -- Manhattan, the Bronx and
Staten Island -- and seven northern suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Though some in Catholic circles expressed surprise at Egan's
appointment, in part because many archbishops retire at 75, Ahern
did not see it as a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has a lot of steam in his engine; a lot of energy, a lot of
gifts left to give,'' the 81-year-old Ahern said of the new
archbishop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-11-00 1511 </TRAILER>
