<HEADLINE> Serial killer to be sentenced Friday  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- The sentencing of serial killer Michael
Ross could start a whole new round of appeals and legal arguments
about how the death penalty is administered in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Barring any last-minute defense motions for life in prison,
Superior Court Judge Thomas P. Miano on Friday will impose six
death sentences on Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Miano is bound by a jury's verdict that Ross, 40, should die for
kidnapping and killing four teen-age girls in New London County in
the 1980s. He was convicted in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Ross' victims and people in favor of a life
sentence for Ross may speak at the sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Supreme Court automatically reviews all death
sentences. Additional federal appeals are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Ross, in an interview from death row at Northern Correctional
Institution in Somers last month, said he respects the jury's
verdict and does not want his lawyers to file any non-mandatory
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been 16 years,'' Ross said. ''You know, it's got to end.
I can't let this go another 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The victims were Robin Stavinsky, 19, of Norwich; Wendy
Baribeault, 17, of Jewett City; and two 14-year-old friends, Leslie
Shelley and April Brunais, both of Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   Ross already is serving two life sentences for killing Tammy
Williams, 17, of Brooklyn and Debra Smith Taylor, 23, of Griswold.
</P>
<P>
   Ross preyed on the girls as they walked or hitchhiked down quiet
country roads in eastern Connecticut. He raped some of them.
</P>
<P>
   In his defense, he claimed a disorder called sexual sadism drove
him to rape and kill -- a defense the jury rejected.
</P>
<P>
   It may take years for Ross' case to reach the state Supreme
Court. The review can be limited to the appropriateness of the
sentence, or can be broader to include allegations of error during
the death-penalty hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Such an appeal in 1994 upheld Ross' conviction but found that
information was withheld from the defense that might have helped
Ross get life in prison. The high court ordered a new penalty
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers raised numerous issues at Ross' monthlong
penalty trial that may be used in an appeal. Miano and the lawyers
were forging new law for death penalty cases, since Ross was the
first person in Connecticut to have one penalty hearing for four
murders.
</P>
<P>
   Public defenders who are representing Ross also want to use his
case to highlight alleged racial inequalities in the death penalty
system. Ross is white and his victims were white, but lawyers think
Ross' case is part of a pattern where all death penalty victims are
white.
</P>
<P>
   Ross' case already has taken several roller-coaster rides
through the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Ross and prosecutors reached a written agreement to
waive appeals and put Ross to death. The Supreme Court refused to
answer questions about the legality of the deal and Miano later
rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of a new penalty hearing last summer, the case ended
up before the high court again over ground rules for the
prosecution and the defense in the hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-11-00 1525 </TRAILER>
