<DOCNO> APW20000511.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wary on U.S. Missile Shield  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN LEICESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China may opt to boost its nuclear arsenal or
make its warheads more accurate if the United States goes ahead
with a system to shoot down incoming missiles, Beijing's chief arms
negotiator said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed U.S. National Missile Defense ''could neutralize''
China's ''very small arsenal'' and has already prompted Russia and
China to begin discussions on ways to overcome it, said Sha Zukang,
director of arms control and disarmament at the Chinese Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   The missile shield ''will have a serious effect and therefore it
could affect China's security,'' Sha said in a telephone interview.
''I have been told that we could have a series of options. One of
the options can be maybe to increase the number of our warheads.''
</P>
<P>
   Other options could be improving the accuracy of Chinese
warheads or considering other countermeasures to overcome the
missile shield, Sha said.
</P>
<P>
   Sha said no decision has been taken yet. He stressed that China
does not want to spend precious resources on countering the
proposed system, which the Pentagon wants to have operating by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the last things we want to do. China is a developing
country. We have still millions of people living under the poverty
line,'' Sha said. ''That's why we are strongly advising the
Americans not to go ahead with this program. It's not in their
interest. It's certainly not in China's interest. It's not in
anybody's interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The shield, if it works, would fire interceptor rockets at
incoming missiles. President Clinton may decide as early as this
summer whether to give it a green light. Washington says the shield
is designed to shoot down a small number of missiles fired from
''rogue'' nations such as North Korea, which is developing
long-range ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Sha laughed when reminded of these U.S. assurances, saying they
were not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have assured us it is not directed at China. For that we
are grateful, we are happy. But China cannot base its security on
assurances only,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States proceeds, ''we cannot sit on our hands,
watching our interests compromised, security interests compromised.
Impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sha said experts from China and Russia, which also is strongly
opposed to the system, ''are working together, consulting with each
other how to confront that situation.'' He gave no details.
</P>
<P>
   Sha's comments went further in their detail than previous
Chinese statements, which have mainly warned that a missile shield
could spark a costly, destabilizing arms race. China has also
warned against including Taiwan, which Beijing regards as its
territory, under a proposed regional missile shield in East Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Including Taiwan in such a system would gravely violate Chinese
sovereignty and ''surely meet with strong opposition from the
Chinese people,'' Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue told
reporters Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On a separate issue, Zhang also voiced opposition to a proposed
U.S. watchdog commission to monitor human rights in China. The
proposal is part of efforts to win support in Congress for
legislation to grant China permanent normal trade relations with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang urged passage of the trade bill without conditions,
''otherwise the business interests of the United States will be
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If the U.S. side wants to establish any special commissions or
any other mechanisms to do a balancing act, I don't think that will
be of any help,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House of Representative takes up the proposed trade
legislation May 22. Supporters suggest the proposed watchdog
commission, which could recommend sanctions against Beijing for
human rights and labor abuses, might make the trade bill more
palatable to wavering legislators.
</P>
</TEXT>
