<HEADLINE> Everglades Plan Faces Senate Doubts  </HEADLINE>
By JANELLE CARTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Florida Gov. Jeb Bush's attempts to get
Congress to pass a $7.8 billion plan to restore the Everglades ran
into powerful opposition Thursday from a fellow Republican, Sen.
John Warner of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Warner complained at a hearing that the Senate Environment and
Public Works Committee was being asked to approve projects without
completion of the necessary groundwork.
</P>
<P>
   Further, Warner contended that the amount of money allocated in
the plan ''is quite significant in contrast to what I've been able
to achieve for the Chesapeake Bay.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Bush: ''This is a federally created problem. The mess
that has been created was created by well-intended engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, neither Bush nor other lawmakers indicated
any concern that Warner's objections signaled a battle to come.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's natural these things are going to be raised by members
representing their states,'' said Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, saying he had met a day earlier with Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., declared, ''I think we're going to get
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee chairman, GOP Sen. Bob Smith of New Hampshire,
said passing an Everglades restoration bill was his ''top priority
for the committee this year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's plan seeks to save the one-time
''River of Grass'' which stretches more than 100 miles across South
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, as governments tried to guard against flooding
and ensure adequate water supplies, much-needed water was diverted
from the Everglades. As a result, there is not enough water for the
environment, causing disastrous effects for an ecosystem once
filled with panthers, alligators and flocks of birds.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal aims to capture fresh water and deliver it when and
where it is needed most in the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   It would eliminate some 240 miles of levies and canals as well
as construct aboveground reservoirs, underground aquifers and
develop new wetlands.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government would have to come up with an estimated
$200 million a year for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Tuesday will sign into law Florida's contribution of $2
billion over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''No other state has made such a substantial financial
commitment to a project yet to be authorized by the federal
government,'' Bush said, adding that he wants to see language added
to create an ''equal partnership'' with the federal government,
rather than a ''master/servant'' arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is S. 2437.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
