<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Cautious on AIDS Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) -- South Africa welcomed an offer by
five major drug companies Thursday to cut the price of HIV/AIDS
treatments -- but not if it means giving up the right to seek out
cheaper, generic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   The government has long battled pharmaceutical companies over
plans to import generic versions of drugs for which companies have
patents. An estimated 10 percent of South Africans are infected
with HIV or AIDS, and the government says it cannot afford to
provide drugs at current prices.
</P>
<P>
   When the three European and two U.S. companies announced
Thursday they would work with governments to reduce prices, South
Africa was cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ''If this offer is attached to a condition that governments like
South Africa should not pursue generic substitution, parallel
importing and compulsory licensing, then it is not genuine and
unacceptable,'' said Health Ministry spokeswoman Patricia Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   The companies made no mention of conditions in their statements.
</P>
<P>
   Mirryena Deeb, chief executive of the South African
Pharmaceutical Manufacturers Association, said she was unaware of a
link between the offer and patent protection, but added that the
pharmaceutical companies had stressed the need for their
intellectual property rights to be respected.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's announcement in Geneva involved Germany's Boehringer
Ingelheim, Bristol-Myers Squibb of New York, Roche of Switzerland,
Glaxo Wellcome in Britain, and Merck and Co. of Whitehouse Station,
N.J.
</P>
<P>
   President Thabo Mbeki's office refused to comment, saying it was
awaiting further information.
</P>
<P>
   Only Glaxo Wellcome specified one reduction it would make,
saying its Combivir drug would sell at $2 per day in the countries,
instead of the $16.50 it sells for in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But even $2 a day would put the drugs far out of reach for the
vast majority of Africa's impoverished AIDS sufferers. And the
governments in sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 70 percent of the
world's 33.6 million HIV-infected people live, do not have the
resources to subsidize the medicine to an affordable level.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a day after President Clinton issued an
executive order saying the United States will not challenge any
intellectual property law or policy imposed by a sub-Saharan
African government that promotes access to HIV/AIDS pharmaceuticals
and medical technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a step in the right direction because we bear the big
burden of the problem, and we're not being given the means to
combat the disease,'' said Dr. Sobie Mulindi, a technical adviser
to Kenya's national AIDS council. ''In addition, it's a very
complex problem that is tied to development.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mulindi said it was unclear how the executive order would be
put into effect and whether there were drug companies on the
continent capable of producing generic versions of the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Zakie Achmat, a spokesman for the HIV/AIDS Treatment Action
Campaign, which lobbies for cheaper AIDS medication, said any offer
by the drug companies had to be unconditional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
