<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Senate calls for renewal of 65 mph speed limit law  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A law that increased the speed limit to 65
mph on some New York highways should be renewed and expanded to
include additional stretches of roadways, the state Senate said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   If not renewed by Dec. 1, speed limits on the 1,181 miles of
highways around the state, including most of the New York State
Thruway, would revert to 55 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ''We should act now to extend the law so that there is no
confusion among motorists or disruption of travel and commerce that
would be caused by this sunset,'' said state Sen. Caesar Trunzo,
chairman of his chamber's transportation committee and sponsor of
the renewal bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Suffolk County Republican called for extending the law for
another five years, until Dec. 1, 2005. He cited a state study
released in March which showed that fatalities dropped
significantly on highways where the speed limit was raised from 55
mph to 65 mph by a 1995 statute.
</P>
<P>
   According to the state Department of Transportation study, fatal
accidents went down by 29 percent in the three years following the
1995 hike in speed limit, compared with the last three years of the
lower limit on the same roads.
</P>
<P>
   DOT also said the injury rate in accidents on those roads
decreased by 5 percent and the total number of accidents dipped by
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A provision on the 1995 statute required that the state perform
a safety study of the higher limit to see whether roadways were
more dangerous because of the greater speeds. There is no formal
requirement for such a study under the renewal bill, but the roads
would still be monitored regularly, an aide to Trunzo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's GOP majority is also introducing a package of bills
that would raise the speed limit to 65 mph on additional stretches
of highways including:
</P>
<P>
   --The Catskill portion of the New York State Thruway, south of
Woodbury Plaza, Exit 16.
</P>
<P>
   --Interstate 90 from Exit 8 in Rensselaer County east to the
Thruway's Berkshire spur, and the portion of the Berkshire spur of
the Thruway mainline to Exit B-1.
</P>
<P>
   --Route 481 from Interstate 81 interchange to Fulton in Oswego
County.
</P>
<P>
   --Part of the Southern Tier Expressway from east of the Town of
Lowman in Chemung County to the Pennsylvania state line, and from
Chemung to Route 26.
</P>
<P>
   --Route 12 from the Utica city line to Alder Creek.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, the state DOT or the Thruway Authority would have
to conduct safety studies before the speed limits could be
increased.
</P>
<P>
   ''This package of bills represents a common sense way of
ensuring that traffic on our highways continues to move safely and
at the speed for which these roads are designed,'' Senate Majority
Leader Joseph Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno spokesman John McArdle said the bill will be brought to
the Senate floor for a vote in the coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki also favors expanding the law, spokesman
Charles Deister said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The initial period of 65 mph limit has been successful and
safe, and we think this makes a lot of sense,'' Deister said.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Majority Leader Michael Bragman, D-Onondaga, said his
house is also interested in a renewal as well as expansion of the
speed limit law.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have an open mind as to extending the law,'' said Bragman,
who sponsored the 1995 bill in the Assembly. ''There has to be some
discussions ... as to what additional highways, if any, the law
should be extended to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
