<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sharp Profits Jump on LCD Sales  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese electronics maker Sharp Corp.'s group
profit surged by more than six times for the latest fiscal year as
sales of liquid crystal displays soared.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings growth reported Thursday follows two years of
profit declines.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected sharply higher profits for Sharp as strong
demand for liquid crystal displays outstripped supply, creating
shortages and helping push prices higher.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year ended March 31, Sharp's earnings rose to
28.13 billion yen, or $256.4 million, from 4.63 billion yen the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Group sales increased 6.3 percent to 1.855 trillion yen, or
$16.9 billion, from 1.746 trillion yen a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid crystal display sales rose 47 percent to 346 billion yen,
or $3.15 billion, from 235.6 billion yen a year ago. Among the
products that sold well were large-sized liquid crystal displays
for game machines and smaller versions for cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   For the current year through March 2001, Sharp forecast overall
group sales will rise 5.1 percent to 1.950 trillion yen.
</P>
<P>
   The company predicted sales of electronic components, including
liquid crystal displays, will increase 12 percent, helping offset
weak sales in audio equipment and home appliances.
</P>
<P>
   While conventional televisions rely on bulky vacuum tubes to
amplify electric current, much thinner liquid crystal displays use
transistors manufactured in the form of a film.
</P>
<P>
   Light passes through crystals held between plates of glass,
producing an clear full-color picture.
</P>
<P>
   The glass tube in a 19-inch television weighs about 24 pounds,
while the equivalent liquid crystal display glass weighs about 0.75
pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
