<HEADLINE> Israel's Barak Vows Lebanon Pullout  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   METULLA, Israel (AP) -- Israel will pull its soldiers out of
Lebanon by July despite the risks, Prime Minister Ehud Barak said
Thursday, responding to a demonstration by villagers who charged
that Barak is gambling with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Barak toured the regional army command post near the border as
residents of this century-old village, fearing a withdrawal will
bring cross-border attacks by guerrillas, briefly blocked work on a
new border fence to run near their houses.
</P>
<P>
   ''Risks are involved in this,'' admitted Barak, predicting ''an
exchange of blows'' with Hezbollah guerrillas during the withdrawal
''and for some time after.'' He defended his decision to pull his
soldiers out of a border strip Israel has patrolled for 15 years,
ending what he called a ''longtime tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak's prestige is at stake. After he missed a peacemaking
target with Syria, and talks with the Palestinians show little
progress, the Lebanon withdrawal is seen as a test of his ability
to carry out promises that contributed to his landslide election
victory last year.
</P>
<P>
   Barak pledged to pull Israeli forces out of Lebanon by July 7.
He was hoping to coordinate the withdrawal with Syria, the main
power in Lebanon, but talks broke down in January.
</P>
<P>
   Now Barak is working with the United Nations, which has pledged
to increase the size of UNIFIL, a peace force patrolling the border
area since 1978. The United Nations demands that Israel pull back
to a 1923 border, bringing the fence to the edge of several
villages, including Metulla.
</P>
<P>
   Worried villagers closed access roads for three hours Thursday,
stopping work on the new border fence. They attached signs to
silent bulldozers, reading, ''We are not Barak's guinea pigs'' and
''We are not the flak jacket of the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel set up its self-proclaimed security zone inside south
Lebanon as it withdrew its forces following a full-scale invasion
in 1982, aimed at driving Palestinian guerrillas out of the
country. But the continued Israeli presence spawned Hezbollah, a
Lebanese guerrilla group sponsored by Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Despite military casualties in the guerrilla war, villagers
emphasize that the ''security zone'' has fulfilled its main
objective, keeping guerrillas out of their houses. After the
demonstration, workers resumed construction of the new fence near
the village, pounding posts into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Military intelligence has warned that Hezbollah may attack
Israeli forces as they withdraw, to show that they drove the
Israelis out.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and others admit they do not know if Hezbollah will also
try to attack the villages after the withdrawal. Barak observed
that Israel's problems are ''not because we are leaving Lebanon,
but because we are in Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak warned again that Israel would respond harshly to
continued attacks. Last Thursday Israeli warplanes attacked two
Lebanese electric power stations, a highway and a Hezbollah
ammunition dump after Hezbollah fired rockets at border villages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
