<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University student assembly urges campus store to rent porn  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) -- Bring on the skin, say student leaders
at Binghamton State University who want the campus video store to
stock pornographic movies to rent.
</P>
<P>
   The university's Student Assembly voted 23-7 on a resolution
urging Take One Video to begin renting porn titles. The store is
located in the student union building.
</P>
<P>
   University officials will consider the resolution over the
summer, said university spokeswoman Katie Ellis. She said no public
money is used for the store located in the student union. The store
makes only enough from rentals of its 860 videos to cover the cost
of student salaries, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am strongly opposed to censorship or actions that would
limit student access to any kind of materials,'' said university
President Lois B. DeFleur. ''However, I do not feel the university
is obligated to make available all kinds of materials to students,
and if they are inclined to view this type of video, it is
available in the local area.''
</P>
<P>
   Acting on the resolution, Adam Weissberger, executive vice
president of the Student Association, sent a letter to University
Union Director James Koval asking that porn titles be put on the
shelves.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not trying to say that pornography is completely moral.
There are some very good arguments that can be made against the
industry. However, that does not change the fact that the Assembly
voted overwhelmingly to stock these kinds of movies,'' Weissberger
wrote in his letter.
</P>
<P>
   Student Assembly member Dave Berkowitz, who sponsored the
resolution, said although the resolution was written
tongue-in-cheek -- ending with the request that Assembly members and
other students attach their favorite porn titles -- the intent is
serious.
</P>
<P>
   While he doesn't care for pornography, he said students should
have the right to rent the videos.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly members, in passing the resolution, merely reflected
the wishes of their constituents, Weissberger said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If people don't like this type of film, they don't have to
rent them,'' said Weissberger.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly's action drew a mixed reaction on the campus.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Toner called pornographic movies ''very degrading'' and
said they should not be available on campus. X-rated videos are not
available on for rent at State University of New York campuses in
Buffalo, Plattsburgh, Albany or Cortland.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will just give the school a bad name and cause a lot of
controversy,'' said Toner, a 19-year-old freshman.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY officials in Albany did not return phone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a sex-themed conference at New Paltz that
included explicit discussions of sex toys and workshops on
sadomasochism became a flash point of controversy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
