<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Cow Disease Outbreak Hits Japan  </HEADLINE>
By ERIC PRIDEAUX
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Hours after authorities in southern Japan declared
the outbreak of foot-and-mouth cattle disease over, the government
said Thursday that hundreds of possibly sick cows in the north
would be slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   Two calves at a farm in Hokkaido, Japan's northernmost island,
were confirmed as carrying the highly contagious virus, said
Agriculture Ministry official Yoshio Morinaga.
</P>
<P>
   Foot-and-mouth disease is highly communicable and can kill
carrier animals and ruin entire beef and milk-cow herds. But unlike
mad cow disease, which is believed to cause a brain-wasting ailment
in humans, it cannot be passed on to people.
</P>
<P>
   The slaughtering of more than 700 cows at the farm in the town
of Hombetsu, 400 miles north of Tokyo, all suspected of carrying
the disease, will begin Friday, Morinaga said.
</P>
<P>
   The animals will be buried after they are killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Movement of cattle within a six-mile radius of the farm will be
restricted, and vehicles and other equipment will be disinfected,
the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, authorities in Miyazaki state, where the
deadly animal disease was first reported on March 25, had declared
the outbreak over and cattle herds safe.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was made late Wednesday after blood tests on 21,781
cattle in the prefecture found that none of them showed symptoms of
the disease, said Miyazaki livestock official Naohiro Inoue.
</P>
<P>
   Since the March outbreak, 35 cattle showing signs of the disease
at three farms in Miyazaki were slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   In tests beginning April 21, cows at 405 farms across Japan were
screened for the virus. The two calves believed to be infected
showed up in those tests, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, South Korea said it would soon reopen most of its
livestock markets as foot-and-mouth disease there has stopped
spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Japan stiffened a ban on beef, pork and livestock from South
Korea, where about 2,200 cattle and pigs have been slaughtered
since the disease broke out there around March 20.
</P>
<P>
   Outbreaks in Japan and South Korea have led governments
throughout Asia to ban imports of beef and pork from those nations.
Japan's last case of foot-and-mouth disease was in 1908.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1622 </TRAILER>
