<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medicine Journal Names New Editor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) -- The chief of pulmonary medicine at Brigham
and Women's Hospital has been named editor-in-chief of The New
England Journal of Medicine, the journal's publisher said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey M. Drazen will replace Dr. Marsha Angell, who had
assumed the post Sept. 1 until a new editor was found.
</P>
<P>
   Angell had replaced Dr. Jerome P. Kassirer, who was forced to
step down in July after eight years at the helm of the journal,
published by the Massachusetts Medical Society. Kassirer disagreed
with the society's decision to use the journal's name to promote
other publications.
</P>
<P>
   Drazen has led the Pulmonary Division at Brigham and Women's
since 1989. A specialist in asthma research, he has written or
co-written 200 original research articles and 100 review articles
in medical journals since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ''Medical journals have a vital role to play in the world,''
Drazen said in a statement. ''They are the interface between the
people who create medical knowledge -- the researchers -- and the
people who use it -- the clinicians.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal, founded in 1812, is one of the world's
most prestigious medical publications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
