<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Fights Over Elderly Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans at a congressional hearing on
Thursday questioned the affordability -- for senior citizens and the
government -- of the Democrats' latest plan to add prescription drug
coverage to Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you set up a structure within which the government holds
the bag, ... at some point, the bag gets pretty heavy,'' said Rep.
Bill Thomas, chairman of the House Ways and Means health
subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare administrator Nancy-Ann DeParle, testifying for the
Clinton administration, said financing details should be resolved
through bipartisan negotiations. But she added that, ''from our
perspective one of the principles here is that this benefit must be
affordable both to beneficiaries and to the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are sorting out some of the same money problems as
they work on rival legislation that would help retirees with drug
costs through the private sector, Thomas acknowledged, saying
''certain concerns may be more or less common to any plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats on Wednesday outlined legislation
building on President Clinton's year-old proposal to add drug
benefits to Medicare. Among changes, the Democrats added
catastrophic protection that would pay all costs for prescriptions
after a retiree spends about $3,000 out of pocket in any year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had envisioned such a feature, earmarking $35 billion
for it in his proposal, but left out specifics. So far, it's
unclear whether $35 billion would be enough.
</P>
<P>
   At Thursday's hearing, Congressional Budget Office Director Dan
Crippen said that depending on how catastrophic protection is
designed, it could potentially double the price tag Clinton has put
on his basic coverage plan -- $160 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will likely be quite expensive,'' said Crippen.
</P>
<P>
   Crippen stressed, however, that he does not have an official
estimate because Democrats have not settled final details of their
plan.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are contemplating how to include catastrophic
protections in their legislation as well.
</P>
<P>
   DeParle said one of the decisions lawmakers will have to make is
whether part of the cost should be borne by beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a tension between providing a full catastrophic
benefit with no additional cost to beneficiaries or providing one
where the ... costs to the Medicare program are lower,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Democrats' plan, senior citizens could get basic
Medicare drug coverage for about $25 a month to start. The
government would pay half the bill for each prescription up to a
$1,000 cap. That benefit cap would gradually rise to $2,500 as the
program was phased in, along with the monthly premium retirees
would pay, which would reach $50.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, House Republicans have outlined legislation that
would have the government help finance a new kind of private
insurance providing drug coverage for retirees. Medicare would
directly subsidize the cost of enrollment for those with the lowest
incomes and the highest drug bills.
</P>
<P>
   GOP lawmakers have not yet specified the cost to beneficiaries,
but have promised to put up $40 billion from government surpluses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1650 </TRAILER>
