<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> President Seeks Equal Pay for Women  </HEADLINE>
By ANNE GEARAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed for new federal
money to help narrow the wage gap for women in the burgeoning high
technology field on Thursday, saying equal pay is not a political
issue anywhere but Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton wants Congress to approve a $20 million program at the
National Science Foundation to help advance the careers of women
scientists and engineers -- two highly paid fields where women are
underrepresented.
</P>
<P>
   He is also asking Congress to fund a $27 million program to
attack the wage inequality problem in general. Both requests are
part of Clinton's budget for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a political or a partisan issue anywhere else,''
Clinton said during a White House commemoration of Equal Pay Day,
the theoretical point in the year when women and better-paid men
begin earning equal pay for equal work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether we do something or not, and whether what we do is
meaningful or is not a political or a partisan issue in America,
and it shouldn't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   House Education and the Workforce Committee Chairman Rep. Bill
Goodling said Clinton is repackaging old ideas and requests.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Clinton's comments today imply that equal pay and
related issues are not a high priority for the 106th Congress,''
said Goodling, R-Pa. ''Obviously, the president hasn't paid close
attention,'' to GOP ideas, Goodling said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, women earn about 75 percent as much as equally
qualified men, according to a variety of government and independent
studies. The results are about the same for the information
technology industry, even though the industry has experienced a
dramatic growth in jobs and wealth.
</P>
<P>
   A White House economic report released Thursday singled out the
high-technology industry as an area where there are too few women
earning too small a share of the potential wages.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fewer than one in three of these high-tech, high-wage jobs are
women,'' Clinton said. Clinton called the disparity ''another
digital divide,'' the term he uses to describe the shortage of
computer skills and access in poor and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Information technology work, which includes computer
programming, design and engineering, is growing at a furious pace.
Since 1983, employment in the industry grew 81 percent, according
to the White House report, while job growth in the general economy
was 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Women benefit from the overall affluence of the industry --
making salaries nearly 50 percent above women in the wider work
force, the White House report found.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, an important gender employment gap exists in the IT
occupations,'' said the report from the White House Council of
Economic Advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Women make up only 29 percent of the five basic information
technology job categories studied in the report, although they are
47 percent of the work force at large, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, women are scarcest in the high-tech jobs that pay the
most, the report found. For example, only 10 percent of electrical
engineers are women, the report found.
</P>
<P>
   While 20 percent of male high-tech workers earn $69,740 or more,
only 7 percent of female workers earn that much, the report found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1654 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Health Care Battle Begins  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- In Canada's cherished ''free for all'' Medicare
system, which promises universal access to state-funded health
care, ''private'' was long considered a dirty word.
</P>
<P>
   That could be changing with Alberta province's passage Wednesday
of a law allowing private clinics to perform some major surgery and
provide other services generally restricted to public hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Such clinics, which are smaller facilities that lack the
diagnostic equipment and emergency rooms of hospitals, now offer
only outpatient procedures and other minor treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, private clinics would receive state money to
perform operations -- such as hip- and knee-replacements -- that
require overnight stays.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to ease the burden on the state-funded health
system, which now forces patients to wait months for some elective
surgeries, such as cataract procedures and hip replacements.
Wealthy Canadians often choose to travel to the United States to
pay for such operations instead of waiting in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents contend, however, that the law eventually could lead
to private clinics devising ways to charge for services covered by
Medicare, such as allowing patients to pay for an insured service
to get treated more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you believe the (Alberta) government, this will add
capacity and shorten waiting lists,'' said Michael Decter, head of
the Canadian Institute for Health Information and a former Ontario
deputy health minister. ''If you believe the opponents, then it
won't shorten waiting lists and will charge for previously covered
services.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure touches on one of the most sensitive issues in a
country that embraces the 28-year-old Medicare system as a
reflection of the national social conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters shouting ''Kill the Bill!'' converged on the Alberta
legislature in the weeks leading up to its final approval, with two
demonstrators forcibly removed from the chamber Wednesday night for
disrupting the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Health Minister Allen Rock immediately warned Alberta
the government would crack down on any violations of the Canada
Health Act.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in parliament on Thursday, Rock said private clinics
permitted to perform expanded surgical procedures under the new law
would be considered hospitals as defined by the Health Act and
therefore obliged to offer Medicare-covered services for free.
</P>
<P>
   He also announced the budget for hiring staff to enforce the
federal law would be more than doubled to $2.7 million. Violators
can have federal health care funds withheld.
</P>
<P>
   According to Decter, the changes introduced by the law are less
significant than the public outcry. The measure specifically
forbids private hospitals, but authorizes the Alberta health
minister to contract out minor and non-emergency surgical work
covered by Medicare to private clinics, consistent with the Canada
Health Act.
</P>
<P>
   It also sets fines of $6,800 for a first offense and $13,600 for
a second offense for clinics that charge for services covered by
Medicare, allow paying patients to jump the waiting list or sell
additional services not covered by Medicare without properly
disclosing options.
</P>
<P>
   Decter said the new law, when enacted as expected later this
year, could lead to quicker and simpler procedures going to private
clinics while more complex, costly operations remain at public
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The risk, he said, is ''if you can make more money as a surgeon
doing a lot of procedures in a clinic, because they're easier, then
you may get the best surgeons gravitating toward the clinics.''
</P>
<P>
   Such profit-driven thinking is what scares opponents of the
bill. Dr. Walley J. Temple of the Tom Baker Cancer Center in
Calgary said focusing on profits harmed the ability to care for
patients.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent speech, Temple said overseas colleagues were ''in
awe'' of Canada's public health care system, which he called ''a
veritable treasure'' because it made patient care instead of
financial incentive the primary focus.
</P>
<P>
   ''For-profit care has very little to do with care and very much
to do with profit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Health Ministry, http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1657 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Aid Delays Said Have Costs  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A top State Department official said Wednesday
delays by Congress in approving aid money for Colombia have forced
the United States to curtail helicopter training of Colombian
pilots and spraying operations against illicit narcotics plants.
</P>
<P>
   ''There appear to be some members who lack understanding of the
urgency of the situation and the costs of this delay,'' Under
Secretary of State Thomas Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering spoke with reporters as he prepared to leave for
Colombia on Thursday for talks with President Andres Pastrana and
other officials about the joint efforts of the two countries to
curb narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee on Thursday cut the
administration's new money request for Colombia from $1.3 billion
to $1.1 billion. In addition, Senate rules will require the
approval of 60 votes for the package to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering called the adoption of the rule ''a very serious
mistake. Our hope is that it will not influence the outcome of this
very important legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Each day and week of delay spells higher costs at the end of
the day, costs in human terms in our own country, costs in human
terms in Colombia, additional costs for getting the process
reversed,'' Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
   The Appropriations Committee deleted the administration's
request for 33 Blackhawk helicopters for the counter-drug fight.
Pickering noted that the House version fully funds the Blackhawks,
and he expressed hope that the differences can be worked out to the
administration's satisfaction by House-Senate conferees.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Blackhawks are needed in Colombia because it
provides better armor, flies faster and has longer ranger than Huey
helicopters, which also are part of the administration's request.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of the committee to embrace the full
administration request reflects the concern of some lawmakers that
that the United States might become involved in Colombia's civil
war. Others believe that attempts at stopping narcotics flow are
doomed to fail and that U.S. resources should be earmarked for
treatment programs for people suffering from drug addiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1657 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0145 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Warns on Colombia Aid  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A top State Department official said Thursday
delays by Congress in approving aid money for Colombia have forced
the United States to curtail helicopter training of Colombian
pilots and spraying operations against illicit narcotics plants.
</P>
<P>
   ''There appear to be some members who lack understanding of the
urgency of the situation and the costs of this delay,'' Under
Secretary of State Thomas Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering spoke with reporters as he prepared to leave for
Colombia on Thursday for talks with President Andres Pastrana and
other officials about the joint efforts of the two countries to
curb narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee on Thursday cut the
administration's new money request for Colombia from $1.3 billion
to $1.1 billion. In addition, Senate rules will require the
approval of 60 votes for the package to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Pickering called the adoption of the rule ''a very serious
mistake. Our hope is that it will not influence the outcome of this
very important legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Each day and week of delay spells higher costs at the end of
the day, costs in human terms in our own country, costs in human
terms in Colombia, additional costs for getting the process
reversed,'' Pickering said.
</P>
<P>
   The Appropriations Committee deleted the administration's
request for 33 Blackhawk helicopters for the counter-drug fight.
Pickering noted that the House version fully funds the Blackhawks,
and he expressed hope that the differences can be worked out to the
administration's satisfaction by House-Senate conferees.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Blackhawks are needed in Colombia because it
provides better armor, flies faster and has longer ranger than Huey
helicopters, which also are part of the administration's request.
</P>
<P>
   The reluctance of the committee to embrace the full
administration request reflects the concern of some lawmakers that
that the United States might become involved in Colombia's civil
war. Others believe that attempts at stopping narcotics flow are
doomed to fail and that U.S. resources should be earmarked for
treatment programs for people suffering from drug addiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
