<HEADLINE> Letter Carriers Food Collection Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mail carriers across the country will conduct
their annual ''Stamp Out Hunger'' food drive Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers in 10,000 communities are asking residents to set out
nonperishable food items for them to collect and distribute, the
National Association of Letter Carriers said.
</P>
<P>
   The items collected go to food banks and homeless shelters in
the community where they are donated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Donations are especially needed now to stock food pantries for
the summer months when millions of children are without the
nutritional benefits of their school lunch programs,'' union
president Vince Sombrotto said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year carriers collected 58.4 million pounds of food for
community food banks.
</P>
<P>
   To assist in this year's drive, 95 million postcard flyers,
sponsored by the Campbell Soup Company and the Priority Mail
Division of the U.S. Postal Service, have been delivered to
residents in participating cities to encourage donations.
</P>
<P>
   While the carriers are collecting the food left by mailboxes in
most areas, in New York City and Chicago residents are being asked
to take their donations to their local post office.
</P>
</TEXT>
