<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford To Restructure at Dagenham  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Ford Motor Co., trying to cut its costs in the
tough European market, said it would announce on Friday major
changes in its operations at its Dagenham manufacturing complex in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Ford chairman William Clay Ford Jr. and CEO Jac Nasser declined
Thursday to offer specifics of the company's plans for the Dagenham
plants. But the two did say the site would remain an important part
of Ford's European business.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dagenham is going to continue forever,'' Nasser said. The plan
is ''really the rebirth of Dagenham.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said Ford's investments for Dagenham over the next few
years would approach $750 million dollars. But he also said Ford
would take a financial charge against earnings for its
restructuring plans.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Dagenham has been the source of speculation for
months as Ford has considered ways to improve profits at its
European division, which lost $55 million last year and $3 million
in the first quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Ford runs an assembly plant and a diesel engine plant at
Dagenham, and employs over 6,000 people there. The assembly plant,
built in 1931, has been running far below capacity, producing
191,000 vehicles last year when it was designed to handle 278,000.
Ford builds the Ford Fiesta cars and Courier vans there, mainly for
customers in Britain and Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said in February it was cutting 1,350 jobs from the
Dagenham assembly plant, and workers feared the company would close
the assembly line altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the diesel engine plant seemed more secure because
it is the only diesel engine factory Ford has and is essential to
providing diesel engines for the European market, where they are in
high demand. Nasser said the company would ''invest heavily in that
facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Nasser said the plan would be consistent with other moves Ford
has made this year, which have included ending joint manufacturing
ventures in Europe with Volkswagen and Mitsubishi. While the
strength of the British pound has driven up the cost of doing
business in Britain, Nasser said Ford's plans were based on Ford's
own production forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser and Ford also said the company had talked with the
government of British Prime Minister Tony Blair and labor unions
about its plans.
</P>
<P>
   The comments came after Ford held its annual meeting for
shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1712 </TRAILER>
