<HEADLINE> Dollar Posts Strong Gains vs. Euro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the euro Thursday, as
European leaders chose not to intervene to help revive their
sagging currency. But the dollar fell against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at 90.06 cents,
down from 91.87 cents late Wednesday. The dollar was quoted at
108.53 Japanese yen, down from 109.39.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar soared against the euro amid broad gains in the U.S.
stock markets. A government report that showed retail sales had
slowed in April eased fears of rising inflation. The Dow Jones
industrial average rose 178 points and the Nasdaq composite index
gained 115.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, European leaders chose not to raise interest rates, a
move that might have given a boost to the ailing single European
currency.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, the euro has dropped to new lows as investors
predicted that European authorities would not take an aggressive
action to stimulate the economy and make investment there
attractive. The euro is the single currency of 11 European nations
and has been trading since January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The pound sank again on Thursday, a day after the release of a
benign inflation report that dampened expectations of further
interest rate hikes in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The British pound fell to a four-year low of $1.5022, down from
$1.5115 in late trading Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar also was quoted at 1.7292 Swiss francs, up from
1.7150, and 1.4901 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4927.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.1724 German
marks, up from 2.1484; 7.2860 French francs, up from 7.2055; and
2,150.69 Italian lire, up from 2,126.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
