<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gloom Cast on Zimbabwe Peace Talks  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Threats of more violence and demands by
squatters for white-owned farmland dampened hope Thursday for a
quick end to months of farm occupations in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of farmers and the reported leader of the
squatters toured some of the worst-affected farming districts this
week. The goal was to persuade squatters to at least allow the
farms to work unhindered while the issue of land ownership was
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   But the excursion failed to ease tensions, making peace talks
seem headed toward failure.
</P>
<P>
   Violence and intimidation against farmers and their workers has
continued in most areas, the Commercial Farmers Union said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 white-owned farms have been occupied since early
February, when the government lost a constitutional referendum that
would have entrenched President Robert Mugabe's powers and allowed
the government to seize land without paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe's opponents say he allowed the violent occupations -- in
which three white farmers have been killed -- to punish farmers and
their workers for supporting the main opposition group, the
Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition group is seen as the first real challenge to
Mugabe's rule since 1980, when he led the nation to independence
from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Farm union officials and Chenjerai Hunzvi, head of the National
Liberation War Veterans Association, agreed to tour the affected
lands this week and persuade the squatters to allow farmers to
plant their seeds and tend their fields.
</P>
<P>
   Two hundred occupiers demanded food and accommodation at one
property in the Centenery District, northeast of Harare. They
insisted the owner vacate his land.
</P>
<P>
   Another 250 occupiers dispersed across two other farms and
threatened violence unless they were given plots on the land.
</P>
<P>
   The situation was similar across the country all week, the union
said. On Wednesday, occupiers held four white farmers hostage for
three hours, after which they released them unharmed from a
besieged homestead in the eastern Manicaland province.
</P>
<P>
   Hunzvi's group reportedly has been leading the movement to
occupy white-owned land. But union members across the country have
reported splits among the occupiers, simultaneous with the
emergence of local warlords over whom Hunzvi's influence was
diminishing.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jerry Grant, deputy director of the farmers union, said that
in many areas the occupations were out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ''With various warlords doing what they like ... the situation
on the farms is anarchy,'' he told a meeting of Harare business
leaders. ''Any agreements we strike with Hunzvi are likely to be
ineffective.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
