<HEADLINE> Carter Team To Visit Dominican  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- The Atlanta-based
Carter Center will send 24 elections observers to the Dominican
Republic to monitor May 16 elections, a spokeswoman said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Deanna Congileo said the delegation would not
include former President Jimmy Carter, despite reports in local
newspapers that Carter and four other former heads of state would
be observers.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping for a repeat of the 1996 elections, which were praised as
the Caribbean country's fairest vote ever, Dominican officials have
invited monitors from around the world to help observe polling.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Elections Board said Wednesday it had accredited a
host of former heads of state to serve as elections observers,
including Carter, former Spanish Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez,
ex-President Luis Herrera Campins of Venezuela and former President
Armando Calderon Sol of El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   So far only former Colombian President Belisario Betancur has
said he would attend, the board said. The Colombian Embassy said
Thursday it had received no word of a visit by Betancur.
</P>
