<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senate panel approves gun-control measures  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A Senate committee Thursday unanimously
passed a package of bills that would outlaw the sale of hand guns
without child safety features.
</P>
<P>
   Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco, R-Union, the bill
sponsor, said the rules requiring child safety locks and mechanisms
that allow only the gun owner to fire the weapon are ''a
commonsense response'' to public calls to end gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   He and other supporters say the measures will save the lives of
children by preventing accidental shootings. They also maintain
that the ''smart guns'' will cut down on gun crime, since the
weapons would be useless to thieves.
</P>
<P>
   But a Yale University Law School researcher testified that such
laws show little effect on accidental shootings. Among the other
opponents was a nursing mother who said not all families want
''smart guns.'' Supporters include Cease-Fire New Jersey and the
New Jersey Catholic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The senator admitted before the Law and Public Safety Committee
that ''smart gun'' technology is not available. His proposal allows
the state attorney general to decide when the technology is viable
and then to require every hand gun sold to be so equipped. Guns
used by police officers and antique guns would be exempt.
</P>
<P>
   ''The initiative does make it perfectly clear, however, that New
Jersey cares about its children, and is prepared to mandate, just
as we have done with car seats and bike helmets, any viable
technology that offers children greater protection from harm,''
DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   But the technology is unproven and it would force residents to
buy unsafe, untested guns, said Nancy Ross, spokeswoman for the
Association of New Jersey Rifle and Pistol Clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Ross charged that the senators were pandering to the public and
were trying to slip ''an unconstitutional ban'' on handguns into
law. The measure would make it illegal to use target pistols and
other small guns that can't be equipped with the ''smart gun''
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has nothing to do with safety. This is politics,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The same safety arguments were forwarded in 1990 when the state
required gun owners to lock up their pistols. But John Lott, a
research scholar at Yale University Law School, said his statistics
show that accidental gun deaths remained virtually unchanged after
that law was enacted. He also said crime rates have increased as
gun laws have been made tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Levin, of Rutherford, nursed her child while telling
senators she opposed the bills.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't assume children will be safe. Don't assume all parents
and families support this because they don't,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   A gun owner herself, Levin later said she felt more comfortable
training her children in gun safety than waiting for unproven
technology to become available.
</P>
<P>
   ''The easy availability of handguns makes every person
vulnerable to a murderous gun. Our concern is intensified by the
fact that the impact of crime and violence falls disproportionately
on the weakest in our society,'' said William F. Bolan, Jr., the
executive director of the New Jersey Catholic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The full Senate approved a similar measure last year, but the
Assembly never acted on the bill. DiFrancesco said the bills should
go before the full Senate by the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Jack Collins, R-Salem, said Thursday he was
unsure his branch of the Legislature would support the measure,
especially since no gun on the market now features the technology
required.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever the Legislature passes mandates, whatever they
mandate should exist,'' Collins said. ''Once it exists, the
Assembly will be in the forefront supporting the mandate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-11-00 1747 </TRAILER>
