<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Fall 0.2 Percent  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dreary weather, stock market volatility and
rising interest rates helped pull Americans back from their
free-spending ways in April, sending retail sales down for the
first time since August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But economists said the weaker-than-expected sales will not stop
the Federal Reserve from boosting interest rates again next week.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at retail stores nationwide declined 0.2 percent last
month to a seasonally adjusted $266 billion following a brisk 0.5
percent increase in March, the Commerce Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   April's performance surprised many economists who predicted
sales would rise moderately.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected decline marked the first time retail sales have
fallen since August 1998 and was the biggest decrease since a 0.8
percent drop in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''The surprise decline ... may be the first indication that
higher interest rates and faltering stock markets are causing
consumers to cut back a little on their spending,'' said economist
Joel Naroff of Naroff Economic Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Investors liked the report. The Dow Jones industrial average was
up 178.19 points to close at 10,545.97 and the Nasdaq gained 114.85
points to finish at 3,499.58.
</P>
<P>
   Economists widely expect that Fed policy-makers, which have
boosted interest rates five times by a quarter-point each since
June 30, will push rates higher when they meet Tuesday. A growing
number of economists are predicting a more aggressive half-point
increase even in light of Thursday's report.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pace of consumer spending in recent months has been
nothing short of breakneck,'' said economist Ken Mayland of
ClearView Economics. ''In order to ensure that consumer spending
growth will not flare up again, it will not deter them from raising
short-term interest rates the bigger 50 basis point step.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with April's decline, retail sales are running 9.7 percent
higher than the same month a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed raised rates in an attempt to slow the speeding economy
and its main engine, consumer spending, which accounts for
two-thirds of all economic activity. Those rate increases are
designed to make borrowing more expensive and thus cool demand for
big-ticket items such as cars and homes, a move that would help
keep inflation from escalating.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp drop in sales at gasoline stations, reflecting lower
prices at the pump, led last month's decline. But falling sales for
cars, clothing and building supplies also contributed to the
weaker-than-expected performance.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline sales fell a sharp 2.3 percent in April following a 4.3
percent gain the month before. Prices at the pump peaked in March
but edged down in April, reflecting lower crude-oil prices and
increased production.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at hardware, building and garden supply stores fell 1.6
percent after posting a 4.8 percent rise in March. Clothing store
sales declined by 0.9 percent, down from a 1.6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cold and wet weather was definitely not conducive to
traditional spring purchases,'' said Rosalind Wells, chief
economist for the National Retail Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new cars and trucks declined by 0.7 percent in April
after a 1.4 percent decrease the month before but still remain at
healthy levels.
</P>
<P>
   Showroom traffic was down last month, particularly for luxury
cars, said Paul Taylor, chief economist for the National Automobile
Dealers Association. A likely factor: stock market volatility,
which can make people feel less inclined to spend, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the volatile autos category, retail sales were
unchanged in April, weaker than many analysts expected.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at bars and restaurants, meanwhile, fell 0.4 percent in
April, down from a 1.2 percent rise in March.
</P>
<P>
   There were some bright spots in April's report. Sales at grocery
stores rose a strong 1.1 percent. Department store sales grew by
0.4 percent and furniture store sales went up 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nation's biggest chain stores last week reported
disappointing sales for April. Merchants were expecting a
blockbuster month because Easter fell later this year, shifting
most of the holiday buying into April.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the number of Americans filing new claims for
unemployment benefits last week fell by 7,000 to 297,000,
suggesting that businesses are scrambling to find qualified
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.census.gov/svsd/www/advtable.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1749 </TRAILER>
