<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Futures Soar Amid Demand  </HEADLINE>
By BENNIE M. CURRIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heavy buying in Egypt and anticipation of a promising demand
outlook for wheat sent futures soaring Thursday on the Chicago
Board of Trade, triggering speculation that U.S. wheat may be
gaining ground against global competition.
</P>
<P>
   In other commodity markets, pork bellies rallied on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange while crude oil prices surged sharply higher in
trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for U.S. wheat has been weak in foreign markets this
year, particularly due to competition within the European Community
and in Australia, which have routinely been offering lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   But wheat prices surged sharply in early trading Thursday on
word that Egypt purchased a combined 360,000 tons of soft red and
soft white U.S. wheat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Traditionally, Egypt will buy up to 500,000 tons of U.S. wheat
a week, given that breads and cereals are a major part of their
diet,'' said Tim Hannagan, chief grains analyst for Alaron Trading
Co. in Chicago. ''But (Thursday) they purchased more than half of
that in one day.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Wheat for July delivery rose 7 cents to $2.82 a
bushel.
</P>
<P>
   ''This may very well be because we're becoming a little more
fairly priced and because the U.S. crops generally are a higher
quality crop,'' Hannagan said. ''U.S. wheat generally is grown for
human consumption, so quality is more important than quantity. But
if we're becoming equal in value, then a buyer is going to go for
quality every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said investors also were acting on expectations that an
Agriculture Department report scheduled for release Friday would
bring encouraging news about demand for U.S. wheat. Wheat crops in
China and other countries have been suffering from a drought, which
could lead to lower production and a decrease in the amount of
grain left over for next season.
</P>
<P>
   In other activity on the Board of Trade, July corn rose { cent
to $2.44} a bushel; July oats rose \ cent to $1.23\ a bushel; July
soybeans fell 1{ cents to $5.68{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Chicago, a rebound in pork belly prices ended a
two-day crash on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Although analysts
said the slump may not yet be over, investors gained confidence
that demand for bacon and other pork products would heat up in the
prime summer season.
</P>
<P>
   July pork bellies rose 2.28 cents to 89.85 cents a pound as beef
and pork futures closed mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, June crude oil rose $1.01
to $29.11 a barrel behind an International Energy Agency report
that said oil stocks will be in decline in the third and fourth
quarters of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Among other energy commodities, June heating oil rose 4.03 cent
to 77.31 cents a gallon; June unleaded gasoline rose 2.44 cents to
93.64 cents a gallon; June natural gas rose 3.5 cents to $3.352 per
1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, June Brent crude from the North Sea rose $1.03 to
$27.45 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
