<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NIH To Sponsor AIDS Vaccine Trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A clinical trial testing an HIV treatment
vaccine in patients already infected with the virus will begin in
two weeks under the sponsorship of the National Institutes of
Health, officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will enlist 472 HIV-infected volunteers at 40 centers
in the United States and will last 96 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James McNamara of the division of AIDS at the National
Institute of Allergy and Infections Diseases, a part of NIH, said
the goal is to learn if a vaccine will prompt an immune system
response against HIV in patients infected with the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The trial will enroll patients who already are taking a
multi-drug therapy that has been shown to control the replication
of HIV and who have a low level of virus in their blood.
</P>
<P>
   McNamara said the study will determine if adding the vaccine
will trigger a natural immune system against HIV that many patients
lack. If the vaccine works, he said, it could prolong the
effectiveness of the multi-drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine, called Remune, is made by the Immune Response Corp.
of Carlsbad, Calif. It is made from killed HIV virus particles.
</P>
<P>
   Remune, unlike most vaccines, is not designed to prevent HIV
disease, but to provide a treatment for patients already infected.
The NIH is sponsoring two HIV preventative vaccine trials, one in
Thailand and one in the United States. Those vaccines are designed
to keep patients from becoming infected with HIV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
