<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Trade Stance, Labor at Odds  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Suggesting Al Gore's standing among union
members may be shaky, a labor leader sharply criticized the
Democratic presidential candidate Thursday for stepping forward to
advocate a trade deal with China.
</P>
<P>
   George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers of America,
said his union's endorsement of Gore is not at risk but the rank
and file probably won't mobilize for him in the fall if he
continues ''championing'' the agreement to give China normal trade
status on a permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is something where we can't just shrug our shoulders and
say it doesn't mean anything and we're together on everything
else,'' he told The Associated Press. In the fight for
congressional passage of the agreement, ''Gore should be encouraged
to step out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and many unions have a mutually acknowledged disagreement
on trade with China, and Gore's support for the deal was known when
the steelworkers' union endorsed him in October, shortly after the
AFL-CIO did the same.
</P>
<P>
   Becker, who has been one of the vice president's most vocal
critics within labor, said Gore assured him before the endorsement
that he would not take an active role in support of the agreement,
that he would ''keep a low profile on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Becker's remarks were the first open assertion by a labor leader
that Gore had promised not to lobby for the China deal.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, campaign spokesman for Gore, denied the vice
president had offered any such assurance. ''Al Gore did not make a
commitment not to lobby,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement points to strains between some union members
and their leaders over organized labor's embrace of Gore despite
his support of trade policies that industrial workers fear will
cost them their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   A Voter.com-Battleground poll out Thursday indicated Republican
George W. Bush has improved his standing with union households and
is running about even with Gore among those voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, like Gore, supports the bill to give China permanent
access to low U.S. tariffs in return for a further opening of the
Chinese market to American goods and services. A closely divided
House is expected to vote the week of May 22.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not been a principal player in the lobbying, but he has
advocated the deal in increasingly firm terms in recent public
appearances -- most forcefully this week in a White House event with
Clinton and former presidents Carter and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's allies attribute his limited contribution to the
congressional arm-twisting to the demands of his campaign; critics
say he is trying to avoid serious fissures with the labor and
environmental activists whose energy, money and organizing savvy he
will need in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, unions have been accused of glossing over
their dispute with Gore while sparing no effort to attack members
of Congress, including Democrats, who back the China deal.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-deal Democrats are being told that while unions will mount
voter-mobilization efforts on behalf of the party's candidates,
they may do so with much less enthusiasm -- and therefore less
effect -- than in recent elections.
</P>
<P>
   Becker cited no evidence that Gore is lobbying particularly
hard. What counts, he said, is that his members believe Gore is
doing too much.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our membership is viewing Gore as standing with the president
on this and as supporting (the measure) in a very real way,'' he
said. ''This bothers us tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said Gore has contacted a ''bunch'' of members of
Congress with a pitch that the deal is good for America, its
workers, the environment and the cause of human rights in China.
The campaign has repeatedly declined to say how many he's called or
to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   United Steelworkers: http://www.uswa.org
</P>
<P>
   White House working group on China: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
