<HEADLINE> Egan's elevation cheered by Bridgeport, New York faithful  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Bridgeport's loss is New York's gain,
parishioners of Bishop Edward M. Egan said Thursday as they
celebrated his appointment to succeed the late Cardinal John
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican announced Thursday that Egan, who has headed the
diocese in this gritty, blue-collar city since 1988, would become
the ninth archbishop to New York's 2.4 million Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're sad to see him go, but they're lucky to get him,'' said
Josephine LaMotta, a secretary in the Bridgeport diocese's
education office. ''He's a very caring person. He cares about the
schools and he cares about people in general.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan spent 22 years in Rome as a professor of canon law at the
Gregorian University and as a judge in a church tribunal. He also
spent 3{ years as an auxiliary bishop and vicar of education in New
York before being named bishop in Bridgeport in December 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, 68, earned high praise here for regionalizing the diocese
schools, bringing local men into the priesthood and raising
millions for church causes. The diocese spans all of Fairfield
County, which is among the fastest-growing and wealthiest in the
nation, but is centered in the poor city of Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Some pastors complained that despite successful fund-raising,
Egan closed several inner-city schools and sold to private
operators Stamford's large Catholic hospital, forcing the nuns who
ran it into retirement.
</P>
<P>
   When the Chicago archdiocese became vacant, Egan was rumored to
be the leading candidate for the post, which went instead to
Francis Cardinal George. A joke then making the rounds of the
Bridgeport diocese was that at least a dozen pastors had
volunteered to carry him to the airport. Egan himself roared when
he heard it.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Patrick's Cathedral -- the landmark seat of Egan's new
archdiocese -- prayers were offered for him at two early Masses
Thursday. Parishioners said they would welcome the new archbishop's
leadership, but noted O'Connor, who died last week, still is
greatly missed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He looks like a good man,'' said Elssy Mino, a saleswoman from
the borough of Queens. ''Nobody's going to replace O'Connor, but I
think Egan will be OK. He seems very sweet and nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan hews closely to the church's positions on issues such as
abortion, birth control and homosexual acts. Among conservative
Catholics, his stance was welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are my views also,'' said Stephen Salmon, a math and
special education teacher in Bridgeport public schools. ''The
church is not going to change on those things because that's truth.
For a while, public opinion may go the other way, but I think in
the end public opinion will be the same as the Catholic position.''
</P>
<P>
   But among more liberal Catholics, Egan's strict adherence to
church doctrine is seen as somewhat out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the church definitely needs to relax,'' said Bonnie
Genest, a training manager at an Internet company in Trumbull.
''Some values you need to keep and there are others you need to
move along with as the world moves along.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Genest disagrees with Egan and the church on
abortion and homosexuality, she praised him as a ''great leader''
and a ''great person.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He did my son's confirmation, and I don't think I've ever seen
my son sit and listen that way,'' she said. ''I was impressed with
the way he was with the children.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Bridgeport, Egan has dealt with more than two dozen
lawsuits alleging children were molested by priests from the 1960s
through the 1990s. He created controversy by asserting in one case
that priests were independent contractors who work for individual
parishes, not the diocese.
</P>
<P>
   The law firm that represents 21 plaintiffs suing the diocese
issued a statement Thursday critical of Egan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bishop Egan has never offered his support, his apologies nor
counseling to any of the plaintiffs, all of who have suffered
horrible emotional scars,'' said attorney Cindy Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Drohan, a spokesman for the Bridgeport diocese, said Egan
has strongly condemned the alleged sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plaintiffs' lawyers are transparent in trying to push
their own names onto newspaper pages when the rest of the world is
celebrating hard-earned success for Bishop Egan,'' Drohan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
