<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Victim Advocates Seek Tougher Laws  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Victim rights advocates pleaded with a House
panel Thursday to keep fighting for tougher crime laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are a nation that continues to put violent felons back on
the streets, knowing full well they will rape, molest and murder
again,'' said Fred Goldman, whose son Ron was stabbed to death in
1994 with Nicole Simpson, the ex-wife of former football star O.J.
Simpson. ''What does that say about us as a nation?''
</P>
<P>
   Goldman was joined by Gail Willard, whose daughter Aimee was
killed by a convicted murderer released from a Nevada prison after
serving 12 years of a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   They urged the House Judiciary subcommittee on crime to pass
''Aimee's law,'' which would transfer federal crime money from a
state that releases a violent felon to the state that convicts the
person the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Aimee's law is passed in 2000, states will have strong
incentive to reform their parole systems and to keep predators in
prison actually for life,'' Willard said.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee heard testimony about three other bills: the
''Two Strikes, You're Out Child Protection Act,'' which would make
any second sex offense crime against a child a federal crime;
''Matthew's Law,'' which would increase penalties against people
who commit crimes against children under 13; and the ''Stop
Material Unsuitable for Teens'' or ''SMUT'' act, which would
increase penalties for distributing obscene materials to children
under 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''While each differs from the others, each sounds a common theme
-- an attempt to provide greater protections for our most precious
national asset, our children,'' said Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla.,
the subcommittee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The House has passed similar bills before but none has become
law.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the bills has opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut state Rep. Mike Lawlor called Aimee's Law ''worse
than an unfunded mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Should this proposal become law, every state will be subject
to the loss of most, if not all, federal law enforcement
assistance,'' said Lawlor, chairman of the Connecticut House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   States will try to recoup that money by investigating the
out-of-state records of their current prisoners and charging other
states for the allowable expenses, he said. ''I'm not sure what the
point of this bureaucratic exercise would be,'' Lawlor said.
</P>
<P>
   Law professor Franklin Zimring of the University of California
at Berkeley said action on any of the bills would be premature.
</P>
<P>
   ''Symbolic gestures are easier to find than measures with strong
preventive potential,'' he said. ''None of the group of proposals
before the committee today is a promising method of legislating
public safety.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.house.gov/judiciary/3.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
