<HEADLINE> Dow Up 178; Nasdaq Gains 115  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose broadly Thursday after a report of a
slowdown in retail sales calmed investors who have been selling
stocks amid fears about rising interest rates. Blue chip shares led
the advance.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 178.19 at 10,545.97 and
the Nasdaq composite index was up 114.85 at 3,499.58.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 rose 24.76 to 1,407.81. But volume remained light, leaving
market analysts unconvinced of the rally's underlying strength.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a really rough start to the week,'' said Bob Dickey,
managing director of technical analysis at Dain Rauscher Wessels.
''So at this point, calling this an oversold bounce is about as
bullish as we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the market's gains were sparked by good news on the
economic front. Stocks rose after the Commerce Department said
retail sales fell 0.2 percent. Economists had expected a increase
of 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were quick to cite bad weather in April that kept many
Americans out of the stores. But the decline raised some hopes that
the Federal Reserve's series of interest rate increases is
succeeding in slowing consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed is widely expected to raise interest rates again at
meeting on Tuesday. Economists are divided on whether central
bankers will stick to their strategy of boosting rates by a
quarter-percentage point at a time, or whether they will opt for a
half-percentage point increase this time.
</P>
<P>
   The retail sales report alone won't dissuade the Fed from the
harsher, half-point increase, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears that the volatile stock market and higher interest
rates have started to slow consumer spending,'' said Stan Shipley,
senior economist at Merrill Lynch. ''However, this one-month
slowdown should not derail the Fed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rate-sensitive stocks rose after the retail sales report was
released. J.P. Morgan rose 5 to 127| and Citigroup rose 2{ to 58
15/16.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, which fell sharply on Wednesday, rebounded 9{ to 115 9/16
-- the biggest gainer among all 30 Dow components.
</P>
<P>
   Bargain-hunting opportunities lured some investors into the
technology sector. High-tech stocks have been battered in recent
sessions, leaving their prices significantly lower than they were
earlier this year, before the Nasdaq began its initial descent from
record levels. Texas Instruments rose 6| to 138| and Micron
Technology gained 7 11/16 to 57 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   But some skittishness lingered in high-tech stocks. Applied
Materials teetered between gains and losses before closing up | at
85\. After the close of trading Wednesday, the company reported
operating earnings of 55 cents a share, in line with analysts'
estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said Applied Materials failed to get a bounce from the
strong earnings report because many investors were hoping for the
company, a leading maker of equipment used in the semiconductor
industry, to exceed estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was light, with 1.14 billion shares changing hands as of
5:45 p.m., compared with 1.20 billion in the previous session. Low
volume can exacerbate price swings, creating volatility in even the
quietest session.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we'll see some continued volatility until the Fed's
meeting,'' said Dain Rauscher's Dickey. ''The best thing for the
market would be to get it over with. If we get the half-point
increase that many people are expecting, investors could breathe a
sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. stocks overcame a sharp selloff in Japan. The Nikkei stock
average plunged 4.63 percent to its lowest close in 7{ months.
Traders cited Wall Street's decline on Wednesday, when the Dow fell
168 points and the Nasdaq plunged 200 points.
</P>
<P>
   European markets were unscathed by the heavy selling in Japan.
Germany's Xetra DAX index rose 2.0 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
rose 2.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 gained 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a better than 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 15.11 to
489.39.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
