<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Opposes Gun Suit Bill  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- George W. Bush, in yet another disagreement
with Al Gore on guns, said Thursday he would not support federal
legislation allowing cities to sue gunmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding on comments he made last week while discussing such
legislation, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee said
such a law is ''not good public policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the governor of Texas, last year signed a state law
prohibiting cities and counties from directly suing gunmakers. He
previously has avoided directly stating whether he would support a
similar law at the federal level.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic presidential rival Gore has said he would veto any
bill prohibiting such lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Asked during an appearance on ''Lifetime Live,'' on the women's
cable channel Lifetime, if he were ''willing to go along'' with
Gore on the matter, Bush replied:
</P>
<P>
   ''No, I'm not at all. I think that's allowing trial lawyers to
sue people as an excuse for legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''It's not good public policy. These manufacturers are
manufacturing a legal product, and the interesting public policy
question is if you sue somebody for manufacturing this legal
product, are you allowed to sue somebody else for manufacturing a
legal product?''
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore have been trying to raise doubts about each
other's commitment to gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has complained that Gore frequently voted with the gun
lobby while serving in Congress, despite his criticism of the
National Rifle Association. Gore has suggested Bush would be a
puppet of the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   Gunmakers sought protection after cities began filing lawsuits
accusing them of failing to equip their products with safety
features. Negotiations between gunmakers and 31 municipalities to
settle the lawsuits are now on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gore asked whether Bush would veto any bill
prohibiting such lawsuits. Bush said in reply: ''It depends on
what's in the legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''You can get a feel for my position by looking at
what I've done in office, and what I did in office was sign a bill
that made it very difficult for local municipalities to sue
manufacturers of a legal product.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was referring to the 1999 state law that requires Texas
cities or counties that want to sue gunmakers to funnel the
litigation through the state attorney general, who may or may not
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is similar to ones supported by other Republican
governors and was a follow-up to Bush's efforts to curb other forms
of civil litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's totally irresponsible to side with weapons manufacturers
against concerned citizens in local communities,'' said Gore
campaign spokesman Doug Hattaway. ''He's turned his back on our
communities and stood with the gun lobby lock, stock and barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes said his objection to
such legislation at the federal level is rooted in his
long-standing opposition to measures that would undercut state's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''He would not support a federal law that would override state
restrictions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the Lifetime interview, Bush restated his positions
on gun control. He favors instant background checks for buyers and
swift enforcement of gun laws for violators. He also supports
requiring manufacturers to sell the guns with trigger locks, but
opposes a law mandating that the locks be used, saying it would be
unenforceable.
</P>
<P>
   Gore supports licensing all new handgun purchases, a waiting
period for buying guns and limiting individual gun sales to one per
month. He also supports mandatory child safety locks and has worked
to require background checks for gun purchases at gun shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1810 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Medicare To Clarify Coverage Rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Medicare plans to clarify criteria used to
decide which new health care products and services the nation's
insurance program for the elderly and disabled will pay for.
</P>
<P>
   The Health and Human Services Department announced Thursday that
upcoming regulations will more precisely define Medicare's
long-used rule that care must be ''reasonable and necessary'' to
qualify for coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, two tests would have to be met:
</P>
<P>
   --Clinical evidence would have to exist showing medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   --The product or service would also have to have ''added value''
over existing coverage, such as lower cost, improved health
outcomes, or a new treatment choice, such as medication in place of
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The regulations will be formally proposed after a 30-day comment
period, the agency said. Then, they would not become final until
after an additional public vetting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
