<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Referendum for Soybean Program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers who are opposed to a research and
promotion program for soybeans fell far short of getting enough
support from other producers to force a referendum on the issue,
the Agriculture Department says.
</P>
<P>
   The program is funded through a ''checkoff'' fee paid by
farmers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60,000 farmers had to request a referendum -- 10
percent of the 600,813 soybean producers nationwide -- but only
17,970 completed valid forms, the department said Thursday. Nearly
9,800 of the requests came from Illinois and Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this result, U.S. soybean farmers have validated their
support for the soybean checkoff,'' said Don Latham, chairman of
the United Soybean Board, which runs the program.
</P>
<P>
   USDA also supervises promotion programs for milk, dairy
products, watermelons, honey, popcorn, potatoes, peanuts,
mushrooms, beef, pork, cotton and eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: USDA's Agricultural Marketing Service:
http://www.ams.usda.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
