<HEADLINE> Energy Futures Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Crude oil prices surged sharply higher Thursday
in trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange, taking its products
along with it.
</P>
<P>
   Crude barreled 3.6 percent higher on an International Energy
Agency report that said oil stockpiles will decline in the third
and fourth quarters of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The IEA also said a rise in demand during the peak summer
driving season in North America and Europe threatens to trigger
another round of retail price hikes after a brief respite in April.
</P>
<P>
   June crude oil rose $1.01 to $29.11 a barrel, while June
unleaded gasoline rose 2.44 cents to 93.64 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, heating oil for June delivery settled 4.03
cents higher at 77.31 cents a gallon and June natural gas rose 3.5
cents to $3.352 per 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, June Brent crude from the North Sea rose $1.03 to
$27.45 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
