<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court: Mother's IQ test can't be required in lead claim  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER JORDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A mother cannot be forced to take an IQ test
to prove her son's mental injuries were due to lead paint exposure
and not hereditary, the state's highest court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals specified that its decision applied to
the one case it considered Thursday and did not rule out parental
IQ testing in other lead-poisoning cases. In this latter part of
the decision, it rejected the reasoning of a lower court which said
the parents could not be tested.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each request must be evaluated on a case-by-case basis,''
Judge Carmen Beauchamp Ciparick wrote for the court, with five
other members of the panel concurring and Judge Joseph Bellacosa
not taking part. The court cited New York's strong policy
supporting open disclosure and even said the woman's IQ was not
confidential, just not particularly relevant or questionable in
this case.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ruling was against the landlord, it was seen as a
success for New York City and a powerful coalition of corporate and
insurance groups that sided with the apartment owner since it did
not deny IQ testing in other cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm heartened that the court left the door open,'' said
attorney Andrew Zajac, who filed a friend-of-the-court brief for
the Defense Association of New York. ''We think it's crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence examinations of mothers and other close relatives
are important to the city's defense in the 1,300 similar lead paint
claims it faces, it argued in a friend-of-the-court brief.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are gratified,'' said New York City counsel Margaret King.
''We would view this as a qualified victory.''
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for the mother, Prudencia Andon, said she would now
move forward with her suit against 302-304 Mott Street Associates,
owner of the lower Manhattan apartment building where she lived.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Andon claimed her then 1-year-old son, Antonio, had
learning disabilities, delayed speech and language, and behavioral
problems because of lead paint in the apartment. The arguments over
the IQ test had been brought up in pretrial motions.
</P>
<P>
   A state Supreme Court had ruled that an IQ test could be
administered. But the Appellate Division had reversed that ruling,
saying that the test would raise more questions than it would
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Andon's attorney Alexander Wulwick, who had argued that forcing
the IQ test on the mother would ''extend to the hotly debated
question of whether and to what degree, IQ is inherited ... with
each side producing competing experts'' on nature vs. nurture.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's ruling also agreed that the landlord's expert
witness, a doctor, did not offer enough evidence to support his
opinion that the mother's IQ was ''extremely relevant'' in this
case.
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Trial Lawyers Association had weighed in on
the case on behalf of the mother. That group did not return a call
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   About three-quarters of housing built before 1978 contains
lead-based paint, according to the Environmental Protection Agency.
If not maintained, the federal agency, it can result, especially in
young children, in permanent damage to the brain, nervous system
and kidneys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
