<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amtrak Reports Rider, Revenue Hike  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amtrak riders and revenue increased in the
first four months of 2000 compared with the same period last year,
the railway announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak collected $638 million in revenue from January through
April, 8 percent better than last year. Ridership topped 7 million
customers, up 3.4 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ridership in April was 7 percent higher than in April 1999,
Amtrak said.
</P>
<P>
   Among long-distance trains, the New York-Chicago ''Three
Rivers'' route recorded a 10 percent gain in riders, the
Chicago-New Orleans ''City of New Orleans'' route gained 8 percent,
and the Chicago-San Antonio-Los Angeles ''Texas Eagle'' gained 11
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Among short-distance trains, the Sacramento-San Jose-Oakland
''Capitols'' corridor in California had 38 percent more riders than
a year ago, while the Eugene-Portland-Seattle-Vancouver
''Cascades'' route was up 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak took in $1.84 billion during fiscal year 1999, the
highest revenue total in its 28-year history.
</P>
<P>
   But Amtrak has needed more than $22 billion in government
subsidies since its creation in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak has until the end of fiscal year 2002 to wean itself from
federal operating subsidies or face possible liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Amtrak announced plans to add new passenger
routes and expand into package delivery to help reach financial
self-sufficiency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1909 </TRAILER>
