<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Little Changed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices were little changed Thursday
following the prior day's big gains as investors turned cautious
again before next week's expected interest rate hike by the Federal
Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 10-year Treasury note rose 3/32
point, or 93} cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which
moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.40 percent compared with
late Wednesday's level of 6.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year Treasury bond also rose 3/32 point with the yield
slipping to 6.14 percent from 6.15 percent a day earlier, according
to Bridge Telerate news service.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, worried that heavy spending is aggravating
inflationary pressures, were heartened by a morning report that
revealed a surprise 0.2 percent drop in retail sales during April.
</P>
<P>
   While it was the first decline in nearly two years, economists
said the report wouldn't be enough to stop the Federal Reserve from
boosting interest rates again next week to slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates and inflation make the fixed payoff on
bonds less appealing.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading Thursday, short-term Treasury securities ranged
from unchanged to 1/32 point lower, while intermediate maturities
were unchanged to 1/32 point higher.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills held steady at 6.09 percent
while the discount was unchanged at 5.93 percent. Six-month yields
were 6.41 percent with a discount of 6.14 percent, a gain of 0.01
percentage point. One-year yields were unchanged at 6.29 percent
while the discount held steady at 5.98 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, rose to 6.06 percent compared with late Wednesday's 5.94
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds fell 5/32 to 92\. The average yield to
maturity rose to 6.20 percent from 6.19 percent a day earlier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
