<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pledges Support For S.Leone  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Trying to halt ''a return to all-out war'' in
Sierra Leone, President Clinton on Thursday dispatched special
envoy Jesse Jackson to the African nation and directed U.S.
military officials to move faster to ferry in more international
peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he spoke Thursday with United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan, and they agreed a stronger international
response is necessary ''to restore peace in Sierra Leone and to
prevent a return to all-out civil war. The situation there has been
grave.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We intend to support the commitment West African nations have
made to send additional troops to Sierra Leone to restore peace,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton moved just as the White House fended off criticisms that
his administration is again doing too little, too late for an
African crisis. Clinton said he asked Jackson, his special envoy
for democracy in Africa, to get involved because Jackson has been
active in previous efforts to ''help the people of Sierra Leone
realize their peaceful aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   National security spokesman P.J. Crowley said he was not aware
of any new deployments to Sierra Leone, ''but we continue to work
through how to best reinforce this force and how to sequence the
arrival of these forces in the coming days and weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has a C-17 cargo plane in Jordan preparing to
airlift equipment for a special forces unit to reinforce Jordanian
troops in the region, Clinton said. Besides Jordan, Bangladesh and
India have committed forces, Crowley said, and the United States
has a logistics team working with Nigeria and other participating
West African nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are engaged deeply with them, to try to help support them
in any way we can,'' Crowley said. ''But this kind of international
response takes time to put together.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations wants to speed deployment of peacekeepers
scheduled to arrive by mid-July, bringing the U.N. force up to its
full strength of 11,100. Annan chastised the world's larger nations
for declining to send their better-trained forces to help the
peacekeepers, who have been overwhelmed in clashes with rebel
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the Sierra Leone crisis ''tragic,'' Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright said she and French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vendrine were in contact ''on a very intensive basis'' with
Nigerian President Olesegun Obasanjo about Nigeria's role in
peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're all putting our heads together about how to get the most
effective assistance to Sierra Leone,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Amnesty International USA called on Clinton to state
unequivocally that those who commit atrocities in Sierra Leone will
be prosecuted for war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''This administration continues to support a broken-down peace
agreement that only adds to the atmosphere of impunity for those
who commit atrocities,'' said executive director William F. Schulz.
''It is time to warn perpetrators and those who support or
facilitate severe human rights violations that they will be held
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   During his 1998 tour of Africa, Clinton admitted that the United
States, as well as other nations, waited too long to act after the
1994 Rwandan genocide. He called for ''global vigilance'' on deadly
conflicts, saying, ''Never again must we be shy in the face of the
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Crowley rejected the suggestion that the United States has
reneged on that pledge in the case of Sierra Leone and other
current African conflicts. He pointed out that Richard Holbrooke,
the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, was in Africa this week
trying to halt fighting between Ethiopia and Eritrea, and Rwanda
and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't let anything slide,'' Crowley said. ''Africa is
very much on our radar scope. We are deeply engaged politically and
we are willing to help militarily to help end this conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States previously committed to flying 700 to 800
Bangladeshi soldiers to Sierra Leone in coming days, and Russia is
to send 110 soldiers and four helicopters. Canada has agreed to
send a plane to ferry 1,800 Indian and Bangladeshi peacekeepers,
and British troops are prepared to defend Freetown's airport so
that reinforcements can arrive and foreign nationals can be
evacuated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
