<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore's Veep Search Hits the Hill  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The man leading Al Gore's search for a running
mate is casting a wide net on Capitol Hill, meeting with several
Senate Democrats who include possible picks for the No. 2 spot on
the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Former Secretary of State Warren Christopher, in making the
rounds this week and last, has been mostly asking questions such as
whether it was important that Gore choose an elected official and
whether a woman would increase the presumptive Democratic nominee's
chances against his GOP rival George W. Bush, according to Illinois
Sen. Dick Durbin.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ninety-five percent of this had nothing to do with me,'' said
Durbin, who met with Christopher for 20 minutes on Wednesday in his
office.
</P>
<P>
   Durbin, who has been mentioned as possible vice presidential
material, said Christopher's formal demeanor and attorney's
training made it difficult to tell whether the visit was a scouting
mission. The two had never met before. The session, he said, seemed
primarily designed to elicit advice and talk about who would help
Gore win the important Midwestern battleground of Illinois, a swing
state.
</P>
<P>
   Durbin said he suggested to Christopher that Gore consider for
the No. 2 spot Indiana Sen. Evan Bayh, former Maine Sen. George
Mitchell, California Rep. Nancy Pelosi and Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher also met Wednesday with Sen. Tom Harkin of Iowa,
according to his spokeswoman Jennifer Frost.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut met with Christopher on May
1, said his spokesman Dan Gerstein.
</P>
<P>
   Others who met with Christopher in recent days include Bayh,
John Kerry of Massachusetts, John Breaux of Louisiana, and Barbara
Boxer of California, said Democratic officials, speaking only on
condition of anonymity. Christopher also reportedly called on Sen.
Mary Landrieu of Louisiana and Dianne Feinstein of California.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway said he had no information on
Christopher's Hill activities or who is being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ''Warren Christopher is in charge of that process and it's in
his very early stages,'' Hattaway said. ''He's obviously meeting
with a variety of people but I'm not in position to discuss what
he's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Christopher-Durbin meeting, the former secretary of state
didn't ask the senator if her were interested in the No. 2 spot on
the ticket, but he asked him how he felt seeing his name on
unofficial lists.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really like the job I have,'' said Durbin, who told
Christopher he would be flattered to end up on Gore's short list --
but relieved to see the post go to someone else. ''I'm not seeking
any other position.''
</P>
<P>
   Durbin has never ruled out accepting the vice presidential
nomination if it were offered, but he said he has no ambitions to
higher office. He and his wife prefer to keep the lifestyle they
have that allows to go to the store and other places without
security and publicity, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've really tried to lead an ordinary life,'' Durbin said.
''That would of course change dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   A minor member of Senate Democratic leadership, Durbin has a
reputation as a deft politician, skilled at both behind-the-scenes
wheeling-and-dealing and delivering sharply partisan rhetoric in
public.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most importantly for Gore, Durbin is a Roman Catholic
with a strong political network in a state that carries 22
electoral votes, the nation's sixth-largest cache.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1936 </TRAILER>
