<BODY>
<HEADLINE> In Ocean County, maritime history village prepares for opening  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCKERTON, N.J. (AP) -- In the Hunting Shanty, clerks were busy
folding and stacking the embossed ''Tuckerton Seaport'' golf
shirts, ready for an onslaught of opening-day visitors. At Perrine
Boat Works, boat maker Gus Heinrichs was demonstrating the fine art
of making a sneakbox even sneakier.
</P>
<P>
   Folklorist Steve Warrick walked over clamshell paths from one
seaport building to another Thursday, running errands. Marketing
director Carla Coutts-Miners took a break from her desk in the Sea
Captain's House to take a news crew on a guided tour of the 40-acre
Seaport.
</P>
<P>
   After all, with only two days to go before the grand opening, it
was no time to stand on formality.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're plenty busy,'' said John Gormley, executive director of
the Seaport. ''We're trying to get all the interpreters and
demonstrators assigned to their places, so everyone will know what
they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   What they're doing is bringing the rich history of the decoy
carvers, oystermen and sailors of coastal New Jersey's back bays,
marshes and creeks to life.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Jersey shore's newest attraction will celebrate
some of its oldest traditions when the Seaport opens its doors to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''Barnegat Bay had so much to do with the development of the
Jersey shore as we know it today,'' Gormley said. ''People came
down here to hunt and fish. What we want here is a living history
museum where you can do things, hands-on, where you'll be able to
touch and feel and see things firsthand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seaport, which consists of 13 cedar wood buildings modeled
after real-life structures, offers a wealth of history and
education. Among the attractions:
</P>
<P>
   --Tucker's Island Lighthouse, a replica of the lighthouse on
Tucker's Island that crashed into the sea on Oct. 12, 1927, a
harbinger of the Island's eventual doom. The Island, a 19th-century
resort, was washed over by the Atlantic Ocean in the 1940s and
exists now only as a sandbar that reveals part of itself during low
tide.
</P>
<P>
   --Skeeters Seafood Cafe and Snack Bar, a replica of a famous
Tucker's Island cottage, which features a snack bar offering local
treats like Barnegat Light Scallops, Cranmer's Crab Cakes and Great
Bay Clam Strips.
</P>
<P>
   --Hurley Conklin's Decoy Shop, which features exhibits about the
duck decoys carved by locals for use in luring ducks during
hunting.
</P>
<P>
   --Perrine Boat Works, where classes will be offered in the art of
''sneakbox'' construction. Sneakboxes are duck-hunting boats,
so-called because they are small and quiet enough to allow hunters
to sneak up on waterfowl. ''If I can teach or show someone how to
do it, they can pick up some cedar and build one of these for
themselves,'' said Heinrichs, 68, of West Creek, who has built more
than 40 of them.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, live decoy carving, painting, quilting, boat
building and basketweaving demonstrations are planned as part of
the opening day festivities. Singer Tom Callinan, who has composed
a special Tuckerton Seaport song, will perform on the grounds.
Raffles, a puppet show and giveaways are also planned.
</P>
<P>
   Townspeople are thrilled about the new addition.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've done a great job over there; it's been a battle for
them to get this far, between the money and the permits and just
getting people to see their vision,'' said John Kumpel, owner of
Tuckerton Emporium, one of many downtown businesses that have
erected signs or bunting for the occasion. ''It's a great thing for
the town.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.tuckertonseaport.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-11-00 1939 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Questions Medical Marijuana  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUDAHY, Calif. (AP) -- Al Gore said Thursday that there are
better alternatives to the medical use of marijuana because ''the
science does not show ... that it is the proper medication for
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic presidential candidate, on a visit to a high
school, was asked by a student for his position on whether doctors
should be allowed to prescribe marijuana to treat pain.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that question should be decided ''strictly on the
science.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Right now, the science does not show me or the experts whose
judgment I trust that it is the proper medication for pain and that
there are not better alternatives available in every situation,''
he responded.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said it was his ''belief and understanding''
that there is ''no reliable evidence'' that marijuana ''is a
superior, effective treatment for pain in any situation where there
is not a better alternative available today.''
</P>
<P>
   ''But if the science ever shows that it is, then that should
determine the outcome,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who mentioned his sister's death from cancer in 1984, said
that it is very important that people suffering through painful
illnesses not be denied pain medication.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, during a forum in New Hampshire, Gore said he was
open to the idea of letting doctors prescribe the illegal drug for
patients to manage pain. He said sister's doctor had prescribed
marijuana for her, but that she refused to take it.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it had worked for her, then I think she should have had the
ability to get her pain relieved that way,'' Gore said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he did not favor legalizing marijuana, ''but where
you have sufficient controls, I think doctors ought to have that
option'' to prescribe it.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore administration has vigorously opposed marijuana
initiatives on state ballots, saying they would prejudge clinical
research to determine the safety of marijuana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1942 </TRAILER>
