<HEADLINE> GOP Pledge Patient Rights Progress  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican lawmakers insisted Thursday they
are making progress on a patients' rights bill but set no deadline
for completing work despite complaints by President Clinton about
the slow pace.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have spent hundreds of hours to put together a bill,'' Sen.
Don Nickles, R-Okla., said after he and 10 colleagues met for an
hour with Clinton at the White House. ''We have made good progress
despite what some may think.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cited ''painfully slow'' progress and sought
unsuccessfully for a Memorial Day deadline to complete work on the
most contentious issues remaining: how many Americans the bill
would cover and whether patients would gain the right to sue health
plans if they are harmed when plans deny medical coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the meeting to get an update on negotiations on
the measure, which the administration wants wrapped up before
lawmakers' break for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are here to determine what the issues are and what the
processes are to resolve them,'' Clinton said as the meeting began.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would give millions the right to appeal
decisions by health maintenance organizations, offer easier access
to specialists and provide other guarantees when dealing with HMOs
and other health plans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton favors the House-passed version, which would cover 161
million Americans with private insurance and expand patients' right
to sue. The Senate passed a Republican-crafted bill that would
apply to 55 million Americans whose health plans are not regulated
by states. The Senate version does not expand the right to sue.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no real substance on where we could compromise,''
said Chris Jennings, Clinton's health policy adviser, who attended
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   After 11 weeks of negotiations, lawmakers working to combine the
two bills have agreed on a few provisions, such as letting people
use hospitals not in their plans for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edward Kennedy, R-Mass., said he hoped Thursday's meeting
with Clinton would help get the negotiations ''out of the ditch.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Progress has been painfully slow,'' Kennedy said, adding that
Congress has just 30 days to 40 days to complete its work.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers agreed that time was running out to finish the bill
and told Clinton they would begin meetings in the next few days to
reach a compromise on coverage and the right to sue. Kennedy
suggested a Memorial Day deadline to complete work on those issues,
but Nickles was not ready to set a date, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, who met with Clinton on Wednesday
night to discuss the HMO issue, said negotiators were making ''slow
and steady progress.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very close to completing a balanced bill, one that will
address the issue of the uninsured as it addresses the issue of
accountability,'' the Illinois Republican said in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
