<HEADLINE> Lobbyists Come Out for Bush  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lobbyists for some of America's biggest
corporations -- including General Motors, McDonald's and AT&AMP;T -- have
signed up to host a Washington fund-raiser for George W. Bush later
this month.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-member host committee for the $1,000-per-person event May
22 also includes lobbyists for Microsoft, which is embroiled in an
antitrust suit with the federal government, and Time Warner, which
is awaiting government approval for a merger with America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also includes lobbyists for credit card issuer
Visa, which supports overhauling bankruptcy laws; the tobacco
industry, which opposes giving the Food and Drug Administration the
authority to regulate tobacco as a drug; and the American
Association of Health Plans, which is fighting legislation to allow
patients to sue managed care health organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign hopes to raise $350,000 to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the host committee members are familiar names: former
Reps. Bill Paxon and Susan Molinari; former Republican National
Committee chairman Haley Barbour; and Daniel Meyer, former chief of
staff to former House Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Others are veterans of the administration of Bush's father,
former President Bush. They include former White House counsel C.
Boyden Gray; former U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills; and
former White House political director Ron Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole name of the game is influence and ability to have
your telephone calls returned,'' said Larry Makinson, executive
director of the Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan group
that studies money and campaigns. ''Particularly when you're
dealing with a $1,000 limit, the power doesn't accrue to the donors
but the people who can corral large blocks of them. These guys are
setting themselves up to be on the list of people the next
president is grateful to.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan said the Texas governor
has attracted widespread support from across the country, not just
from Washington lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   ''We appreciate the broad-based support Governor Bush is
receiving to help spread his bipartisan message of strengthening
Social Security, improving our schools and letting working families
keep more of what they earn to save and invest,'' McClellan said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Bush of siding with special interests against
the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   ''Once again, instead of standing up for the American people and
urging Congress to act now on a real patients' bill of rights,
class-size reduction and gun safety initiatives, George Bush is
sitting down with the people who dedicate their careers to stopping
America's working families' agenda from passing,'' Democratic
National Committee spokeswoman Jenny Backus said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush raised $1 million at a Washington fund-raiser last June.
The host committee for that event also was populated with
lobbyists, including Paxon, Barbour and former House Appropriations
Committee Chairman Bob Livingston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
