<HEADLINE> Clinton Honors Teacher of the Year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton presented a California
English instructor the Teacher of the Year award on Thursday,
saying her style was a gentle version of the dogmatic law professor
in the movie ''The Paper Chase.''
</P>
<P>
   The award was given to Marilyn Jachetti Whirry, 65, who teaches
seniors dubbed ''Whirry-ites'' at Mira Costa High School in
Manhattan Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ''Her teaching style, I understand, is like a softer, more
nurturing version of Professor Kingsfield in 'The Paper Chase,'''
Clinton said in the Rose Garden ceremony. ''She paces the room,
posing questions to each student, responding to each answer with
still more questions, digging deeper and deeper into the toughest
texts until their meanings are revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   This year is the 50th anniversary of the National Teacher of the
Year program, sponsored by the Council of Chief State School
Officers and Scholastic Magazine. The winner is chosen from among
the state teachers of the year by a national selection committee
representing national education groups.
</P>
<P>
   Whirry used the opportunity to call for better recruitment and
retention of well-educated teachers for the future. ''We must
instill in our students a passion, a passion about the world,'' she
said. ''This passion puts us in touch with the dizziness that comes
from a new idea, the excitement that comes from a new challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she played schoolmarm, telling the president and the
audience to, ''Please be seated'' because she wasn't finished
speaking. Like a scolded student, Clinton sat back down.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll let Mr. Clinton respond in a minute,'' she said after
presenting him with an honorary teacher of the year award and
thanking him for his support of teachers during his presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
