<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Undecided on China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By MARTIN CRUTSINGER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The administration's point man on China
bluntly warned Republicans on Thursday that they will have to
accept a human rights monitoring panel to win passage of landmark
trade legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary William Daley said he believed that chances
for congressional approval of permanent normal trade relations with
China were ''slim to none'' without legislation to create a
congressional-executive commission to monitor China's human rights
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Clinton warned members of his own party
that Democrats would be hurt if their opposition killed the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would make it possible for people to question whether the
Democrats were running away from our global responsibilities,''
Clinton said in a National Public Radio interview.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for a watchdog commission has been put forward by Reps.
Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Doug Bereuter, R-Neb, although some
Republicans have questioned the need for such a panel.
</P>
<P>
   The commission would consist of members appointed by Congress
and the White House and would issue an annual report to Congress on
China's performance on human rights issues. It could recommend
economic sanctions against China outside of the trade area, such as
withholding U.S. loans.
</P>
<P>
   The commission report would replace the current annual
congressional vote on China's trade status with the United States.
That vote has been used as leverage to apply pressure to China on a
range of issues from human rights to religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and China reached agreement last
November on a measure to lower China's high trade barriers to
American products in return for U.S. support for China's entry into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   However, for American exporters to gain the benefits, Congress
must grant China permanent normal trade relations with the United
States, eliminating the annual review.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, which sees this as one of the biggest items
left on Clinton's final year agenda, continued efforts Thursday to
round up stray votes, dispatching members of the Cabinet to meet
with undecided lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are hoping to get between 140 and 145 votes, meaning
that Democrats will have to produce close to 80 votes to get the
218 needed for a House victory when the vote comes up the week of
May 22. Senate passage is considered more assured
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters Thursday that he believed Majority Whip
Tom DeLay, R-Texas, would come up with the needed GOP votes despite
complaints from DeLay that Republican support was proving to be
shallower than first thought.
</P>
<P>
   ''I noticed that he's quite effective at getting votes when the
time comes, sometimes when I like it and sometimes when I don't,''
Clinton said of DeLay, one of the leaders of the House impeachment
effort in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we'll get there. We've just got a lot of hard work to
do,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president was traveling on Friday to the districts of Reps.
Thomas Sawyer, D-Ohio, who is undecided, and David Minge, D-Minn.,
who is backing the measure, to talk about how the China deal will
benefit U.S. manufacturing companies and farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers told the House Banking
Committee on Thursday that it would be ''catastrophic'' for
American banks, securities firms and insurance companies if the
trade bill did not pass because their competitors would be able to
enter China's huge market and they would not.
</P>
<P>
   Summers also indicated that the administration was still in
discussions on what changes could be made to the Levin-Bereuter
commission proposal in order to attract more votes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are receptive to ideas that make good sense and can garner
bipartisan support,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., one of the undecided Democrats, said
during the hearing that he would not be able to commit until
Republican House leaders specified what accompanying legislation
they will allow the House to vote on.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Bernard Sanders, I-Vt., said he viewed the proposal as
a way to benefit American corporations by making it easier for them
to move jobs to China to take advantage of cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Trade should represent the best interests of the American
people and not just corporate greed,'' Sanders told Summers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House working group on China:
http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO campaign to stop China trade bill:
http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
