<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mom of Rail Killer Suspect Testifies  </HEADLINE>
By C. BRYSON HULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- The sister of admitted serial killer Angel
Maturino Resendiz testified Thursday she knew he could face the
death penalty before he turned himself in to U.S. authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has argued the Mexican drifter's family was given
false promises that Maturino Resendiz would not be subject to the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross examination from prosecutor Devon Anderson,
Manuela Maturino Karkiewicz acknowledged the topic of the death
penalty was broached in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Karkiewicz brokered a deal with Texas Ranger Sgt. Drew Carter
that led Maturino Resendiz to turn himself in on the American side
of an international bridge spanning El Paso and Ciudad Juarez,
Mexico, on July 13.
</P>
<P>
   Karkiewicz initially said the negotiations only covered jail
visitation rights for the family, a guarantee of psychiatric help
and a promise of ''humane treatment,'' which the defense has
construed as no death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But she acknowledged under cross examination that she asked
Carter about the death penalty the night before Maturino Resendiz
surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said 'It's not up to us, it's up to the jury,''' Karkiewicz
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''So you knew that going in, didn't you,'' Anderson asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes,'' Karkiewicz replied.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, has admitted to nine killings from
1997-99 -- six in Texas, two in Illinois and one in Kentucky. He is
being tried for the death of Houston-area physician Dr. Claudia
Benton.
</P>
<P>
   The rail-riding migrant worker faces death by injection if found
guilty of raping, stabbing and bludgeoning Benton during a Dec. 18,
1998, break-in at her home in a Houston suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz pleaded innocent by reason of insanity.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys questioned Dr. Bruce Cohen, a forensic
psychiatrist who examined Maturino Resendiz' background and is the
centerpiece witness of the insanity defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the time of that offense, as a result of schizophrenia, he
did not know that his conduct was wrong,'' Cohen testified.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz said he was propelled by an ''evil force,'' to
enter the houses where he killed, Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''In each case, there was something that led to a feeling of
certainty, a conviction that he had been sent to this house to do
what he needed to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring earlier testimony by a defense psychologist, Cohen
said drug abuse -- glue sniffing -- and head injuries could have
played a role in the development of Maturino Resendiz'
schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Maturino Resendiz' mother, Virginia Maturino
Resendiz, testified her son was dropped on his head right after he
was born.
</P>
<P>
   ''Angel was born, and he did hit himself on his head. He was
very purple,'' she said through an interpreter, describing her
son's delivery at the hands of a midwife.
</P>
<P>
   She also recalled how her son was smashed in the head with a
rock by other students when he was in his early teens and witnessed
her being attacked by men with knives on two occasions. Cohen said
Maturino Resendiz was twice raped by a neighborhood man when he was
8.
</P>
</TEXT>
