<HEADLINE> Columbine Autopsy Report Is Blocked  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN K. PAULSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- A Colorado appeals court Thursday blocked the
release of the autopsy report on Columbine High gunman Dylan
Klebold at his parents' request.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel of the Court of Appeals rejected arguments
by news organizations that release of the report would not harm the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our view, the trial court properly determined that the
overwhelming grief caused by the nature and extent of this tragedy
constituted an extraordinary situation,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
   The Klebolds' lawyers had no immediate comment.
</P>
<P>
   Media attorney Tom Kelley said he was disappointed. He said
autopsy reports often cause grief but are considered public records
under law.
</P>
<P>
   In June, District Judge Henry Nieto sealed the autopsy reports
for all 15 victims of the shooting rampage, including the gunmen,
Klebold and Eric Harris, who committed suicide. He ruled the
reports would harm the public interest by prolonging the families'
grief.
</P>
<P>
   When The Denver Rocky Mountain News and The Denver Post sued to
have the gunmen's reports released, Nieto relented, pending an
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris report was made public because his parents did not
contest its release. The coroner found that Harris, 18, died of of
wounds consistent with a self-inflicted shotgun blast to the roof
of the mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, a Jefferson County District Court judge ordered
911 tapes recorded during the shootings to be edited and released
to the parents of Harris and Klebold and the parents of some of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   The victims' parents sought the tapes from the sheriff's
department to gather information in support of their lawsuit
against the department, which they allege could have prevented the
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Although the order from judge R. Brooke Jackson does not release
the tapes to the public, the he noted the recipients are not
restricted in what they can do with them.
</P>
<P>
   The 22 tapes, each about 90 minutes long, range from an early
call about a diversionary bomb placed on a street to later calls
inside the school and include conversations from law enforcement,
victims and the assailants.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered names, addresses and telephone numbers edited
out, as well as a sequence of conversations recorded from an open
telephone line in the library, where most of the deaths and
injuries occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said that recording, which was technologically
enhanced by the FBI, picks up details that could cause ''a degree
of anguish for the surviving victims and victim families ... that
outweighs the public interest in disclosure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 1958 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insanity plea accepted from former success story  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- A law professor -- once celebrated for
overcoming schizophrenia -- killed his pregnant fiancee because he
thought she was ''a nonhuman impostor'' conspiring to hospitalize
him for torture, experimentation and death.
</P>
<P>
   The findings, according to psychiatric reports released
Thursday, were summarized in court as prosecutors accepted Michael
Laudor's insanity plea, conceding that no jury would convict him of
murder in the face of three doctors' unanimous conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   But the victim's mother and sister, given the rare opportunity
to speak in court in connection with an insanity case, railed
against the idea that Laudor was not responsible for the death of
Caroline Costello.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is horrifying for us to accept that our daughter was
murdered by someone she loved and trusted,'' said Marilyn Costello,
the victim's mother. ''It is horrifying for us to accept that she
died all alone, bleeding, terrified and in pain. ... Michael Laudor
alone must bear the responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Laudor reddened and closed his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's sister, Joyce Costello, said, ''Regardless of
whether he is or was insane, Michael knew he had done something to
hurt Carrie and he knew enough to run. He deserves to be locked up
forever and never released, for who's to say that once released, he
won't kill somebody else?''
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Daniel Angiolillo, taking Laudor's
plea of not responsible by means of mental defect, asked him, ''Do
you understand that you killed Caroline Costello by stabbing her?''
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, sir,'' Laudor replied.
</P>
<P>
   Costello, 37, was found slashed to death on June 17, 1998, in
the kitchen of the apartment she shared with Laudor in
Hastings-on-Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Barbara Egenhauser said bloody knives were found in
the kitchen and bathroom, along with Band-Aid wrappings apparently
used by Laudor for cuts he suffered on his hands during the
killing.
</P>
<P>
   The victim's mother looked down and leaned against her husband.
He held her hand tightly.
</P>
<P>
   Laudor, now 37, had won some fame for succeeding as a Yale Law
School graduate and instructor despite his schizophrenia. He had
sold book and movie rights to his story and was considered a role
model for victims who control schizophrenia through medication.
</P>
<P>
   But at some point after the death of his father in 1997, his
condition deteriorated and he stopped taking his medication,
apparently believing it to be part of a conspiracy against him, the
prosecutor said. Laudor believed he was being monitored or was
receiving messages from televisions and roadside transmitters.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the killing, Costello stayed home from work to try
to help. Laudor's mother and doctor arranged for a visit from a
crisis intervention team from the Westchester County Medical
Center. But that impending visit, according to one psychiatric
report, precipitated the killing because Laudor thought he would be
tortured and lobotomized.
</P>
<P>
   He called his mother and doctor, telling them ''he had killed
Carrie or a windup doll,'' Egenhauser said. They called police, who
found Costello's body and tracked Laudor to the campus of Cornell
University in Ithaca.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after the killing, his lawyer said Laudor still did
not realize that Miss Costello was dead. Doctors originally found
him unfit to stand trial, then reversed that decision a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution, anticipating an insanity defense, hired
forensic psychiatrist Park Dietz, who Egenhauser said was ''known
for having a high threshold'' for insanity. But Dietz agreed with
the defense psychiatrists that Laudor believed his fiancee was ''a
nonperson, a robot or a doll ... planning to kill or torture him.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, saying she had no choice but to
accept the insanity plea, complained about ''a criminal justice
system that allows a psychiatrist to decide whether an individual
stands trial.'' She said psychiatric reports should be considered
only at sentencing, after ''it is decided in a courtroom who
committed a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered a new mental evaluation to help determine what
kind of treatment Laudor should now receive. Laudor told the judge
he was expecting to be returned to the Mid-Hudson Forensic
Psychiatric Center in New Hampton, where he has been treated for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules governing insanity pleas, if the state Office of
Mental Health and the court ever agreed that Laudor was no longer a
danger to himself or others, he could eventually be released.
</P>
<P>
   That rarely happens in New York, lawyers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-11-00 1958 </TRAILER>
