<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bishop Egan Is Staunch and Friendly  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The new head of the New York
Archdiocese is described as friendly and down-to-earth but a
staunch defender of the Roman Catholic Church's conservative
positions on issues such as abortion and homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Edward M. Egan, 68, spent two decades in Rome, teaching
church law and serving on a church court that rules on annulments
of marriages, among other things. In the early 1980s he spent a
summer at the side of Pope John Paul II, reviewing the draft of a
new code of canon law.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he was equally comfortable in more casual settings.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Ruane, now a Bridgeport lawyer, was an altar boy at Egan's
1988 installation as bishop and later traveled with him throughout
the diocese. He recalled how Egan showed a sense of humor when the
teen-age boys grew restless in the back of the church.
</P>
<P>
   ''He wasn't afraid to raise an eyebrow or smirk along with us,''
Ruane said.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican announced Thursday that Egan would replace Cardinal
John O'Connor, who died of a brain tumor last week at age 80.
Egan's promotion from bishop of Bridgeport, a diocese with 367,000
Catholics, to archbishop of New York, which has 2.4 million, will
be formalized June 19 at St. Patrick's Cathedral in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A friend from Egan's college days in Rome summed up the new
archbishop as ''affable but very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Roger Roensch, director of the office in Rome that
assists American visitors to the Vatican, said Egan quickly stood
out as a brilliant student because of his fluency in Latin. In
those days, seminary classes were entirely taught in that ancient
language.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all expected big things of him,'' Roensch said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Oak Park, Ill., Egan was ordained in Rome in 1957. He
spent 22 years there as a professor of canon law at the Gregorian
University and as a judge in the Sacred Roman Rota. He has also
worked in the Chicago and New York archdioceses.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, he headed up education programs. Nora Murphy, a
spokeswoman for the parochial schools there, said she was impressed
by Egan's commitment to Catholic education.
</P>
<P>
   ''He made that quite clear to us -- that he wanted strong
Catholic schools, quality schools, that we were here to serve them
and to help them grow,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Egan hews close to church teachings on social issues. In 1997 he
canceled a weekend conference for Catholic parents of gays and
lesbians that had been scheduled at a diocesan retreat house.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers were a nun and a priest whose ministry to
homosexuals had placed them at odds with the Vatican. The event was
held at another location in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1997, Egan, O'Connor, several other bishops and numerous
religious and academic officials signed a declaration of
''Christian conscience and citizenship.''
</P>
<P>
   The declaration called for ''ordered liberty'' based on moral
truth, saying that the consequences of ''disordered liberty ... are
by now painfully familiar'' -- including abortion, suicide, divorce
and drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The statement also strongly condemned the Supreme Court, which
it said had begun considering any law predicated upon Christian
morality as automatically unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Pieczynski, a spokeswoman for Call to Action, a
Chicago-based group seeking reforms in the Catholic church, called
Egan conservative and legalistic -- yet ''very personable.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall and stately with a stentorian voice, the bishop is a fine
speaker who often dispenses with a microphone. His regular column
in the diocesan newspaper is frequently picked up in Connecticut's
secular papers.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's diocese included both the poor city of Bridgeport and the
wealthy New York City suburbs of Greenwich, New Canaan and Darien.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Joseph Ehrenkranz, executive director of the Center for
Christian-Jewish Understanding at Sacred Heart University in
Fairfield, where Egan sits on the board of directors, called Egan a
strong leader who has reached out to diverse populations such as
New York's.
</P>
<P>
   While in Bridgeport, Egan had to deal with more than two dozen
lawsuits accusing priests of molesting children from the 1960s
through the 1990s. He triggered controversy by asserting in
videotaped testimony in one of those cases that priests were
independent contractors who work for individual parishes, not the
diocese.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has never offered counseling or any type of apology for the
horrific events that went on with Bridgeport diocesan priests,''
said Cindy Robinson, an attorney for the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Drohan, a spokesman for Egan, said the bishop has repeatedly
condemned sexual abuse by priests. ''There is no example in the
past when that hasn't been true,'' Drohan said.
</P>
<P>
   Egan also reorganized diocesan schools and was a successful
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they could pick anybody better,'' said
Bridgeport parishioner Stephen Salmon, a math and special education
teacher in the city schools. ''There's a great spirituality about
him and a great sense of faith.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 2003 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
