<HEADLINE> Italians Seek Surrogate Mom Abroad  </HEADLINE>
By PETER W. MAYER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- An Italian couple who won permission to use a
surrogate mother in a landmark court ruling has left the country to
have a baby because of continuing opposition in Italy, their doctor
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Pasquale Bilotta said the decision was ''inevitable given
the climate of hostility they were facing in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   The February court decision ignited a debate over surrogate
motherhood in Italy, including attacks on the practice from the
Roman Catholic church and the medical establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Then Health Minister Rosy Bindi decried it as a
''commercialization of motherhood,'' and the national physicians'
association threatened Bilotta with disciplinary action if he
carried out the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The association has had a ban on surrogate motherhood in its
code of ethics since 1995, the year the couple began searching for
someone to bear their child.
</P>
<P>
   Italian law does not forbid surrogate motherhood, although
legislation is pending that would make it illegal in Italy, as it
is in most European countries.
</P>
<P>
   Bilotta froze five artificially inseminated embryos from the
couple, whose identity has not been made public. They only recently
found a surrogate mother, a family friend. He said the couple will
have the embryo implanted in the surrogate mother outside of Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The couple went to court at Bilotta's urging, winning a legal
endorsement for the surrogate pregnancy. But the physicians'
association remained adamantly opposed, citing the possibility of
legal wrangles between surrogate and biological parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would have had the right to discipline Dr. Pasquale Bilotta
for breaking our code of conduct,'' said Dr. Aldo Pagni, president
of the physicians' association, the Federation of the Order of
Medical Doctors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
