<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill Lets Me. To Bargain for Drugs  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCIS X. QUINN
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) -- Legislation enabling the state to
negotiate lower prices for prescription drugs on behalf of more
than 300,000 residents won overwhelming support from lawmakers
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Angus King is expected to sign the legislation after the
state House and Senate gave final approval Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The measure allows the state to seek substantial discounts from
suppliers similar to those provided to other large purchasers and
to pass those savings to consumers. If negotiations with
manufacturers fail to reduce prices significantly, price controls
could be imposed in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier legislation that would have created a state board to
impose maximum prices tied to pricing levels in Canada raised the
threat of a veto from King, who questioned the constitutionality of
linking Maine prices to an out-of-state standard.
</P>
<P>
   The new version dropped reference to Canadian prices and put off
decisions on price controls that originally were scheduled for
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Chellie Pingree, a Democrat, predicted
that having the state serve as a pharmaceutical benefit manager for
about 325,000 Maine residents without insurance that covers drugs
would avoid the necessity of imposing limits on prices.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the new measure could win price discounts of
between 12 percent and 15 percent by Jan. 1. They predict discounts
would increase over time as more favorable rebate arrangements were
arranged with manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic House Speaker Steven Rowe said all Maine citizens
should be able to share in savings already available for people in
health maintenance organizations or on Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to use our purchasing power,'' Rowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers criticized as vague or coercive an
anti-profiteering section of the legislation, which could be used
to assess civil penalties of up to $100,000 for drug manufacturers
or distributors who charge what is judged to be an excessive price
or who restrict supplies in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Some opponents denounced the legislation generally as an
unjustifiable intrusion into the free market.
</P>
<P>
   ''So it looks like we're going into competition again with the
private sector,'' complained Republican Rep. Debra Plowman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
