<HEADLINE> Corzine, Florio Kick Off Debates  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Ex-Gov. Jim Florio and former Wall Street
executive Jon Corzine attacked each other's plans for Social
Security on Thursday in the first of the four debates they have
planned before their Democratic Senate primary.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates, who are seeking the seat of retiring Democratic
Sen. Frank Lautenberg, claimed to have positions in line with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine supports gradually investing Social Security funds in
the stock market up to 15 percent of the total reserve, saying
market gains will shore up the strength of retirement benefits. He
called it the Clinton-Corzine plan.
</P>
<P>
   Florio denounced the proposal as ''privatization'' that would
allow Wall Street brokers to ''play with our money'' at the risk of
great losses. He claimed Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic candidate for president, have now denounced it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last year proposed stock-market investment for Social
Security, and the idea was included in his budget proposal now
before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the president has backed off in the face of congressional
opposition and to give Gore leeway to attack his Republican
presidential opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, for his
stock-market investment proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, who has engaged in a $1 million-a-week TV ad blitz,
also attempted to explain his ''bold ideas'' platform for mandatory
health insurance coverage, an $8-an-hour minimum wage, government
financing for urban business and universal education for all.
</P>
<P>
   Florio countered that Corzine's proposals were so sweeping as to
be fantasy and would have ruinous impact on the federal budget.
''This is not bold, this is baloney,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have some tangible accomplishments,'' Florio said. ''I have
experience money can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine stumbled and fumbled nervously for some answers, unable
to match Florio's clipped statements and direct attacks. But he
also avoided any significant blunder that could haunt him in the
final three weeks of the campaign. The primary is June 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
