<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Releases Gulf War Records  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE CASS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Army investigators looking into allegations of
Persian Gulf war crimes by troops under retired Gen. Barry
McCaffrey interviewed dozens of soldiers and found no wrongdoing,
newly released documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to allegations first made in an anonymous letter, the
Army Criminal Investigation Command in August 1991 investigated
whether members of the 24th Infantry Division killed enemy
prisoners or violated the cease-fire that ended the war.
</P>
<P>
   The documents, released under a Freedom of Information request,
come as the allegations have been revived in a dispute between
McCaffrey and journalist Seymour Hersh, who researched the events
for an upcoming New Yorker magazine article.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, now President Clinton's top drug policy adviser,
accused Hersh of spreading false allegations and ''journalistic
stalking'' through a series of interviews with friends and former
Army colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Hersh has declined to comment on his work before publication but
said in a letter to McCaffrey's office that he was simply ''asking
questions, listening to answers and trying to verify and assess
what I've been told.''
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of pages of Army records provide new details about
a fiery attack on a division of Iraq's elite Republican Guard on
March 2, 1991 -- two days after President Bush declared a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although the engagement occurred after the cease fire, this
inquiry has substantiated that the engagement was clearly provoked
by the Iraqis,'' said a Sep. 9, 1991, memo from the Criminal
Investigation Command. The fight ''was within the cease fire rules
of engagement.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investigative documents were withheld by the Army, citing
privacy and other concerns, and others were missing. Other
documents record interviews with soldiers and officers, whose names
were blocked out, describing what became known as the ''Battle of
Rumaylah.''
</P>
<P>
   A battalion of the 24th Infantry Division was surprised in the
early morning darkness of March 2 by the appearance of a convoy of
several hundred vehicles, including tanks, artillery, rocket
launchers and trucks. The Iraqis apparently were leaving Kuwait and
looking for a way to cross U.S. lines to the safety of home.
</P>
<P>
   But soldiers of the 24th Division reported receiving fire from
an Iraqi tank and a missile and saw other weapons among the convoy
pointed toward them. As a result, commanders ordered them to open
fire.
</P>
<P>
   One officer at McCaffrey's command post told investigators that
while the attack was under way, ''I thought it was a slaughter. But
the bottom line was he (McCaffrey) was doing what was necessary to
protect the force because they had been fired on and nobody knew
what these guys were liable to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey, who flew to the front lines to lead the attack, later
told a Senate panel that his forces destroyed at least 630 vehicles
and pieces of equipment. He didn't estimate the number of Iraqi
soldiers killed but said many fled their vehicles and escaped
unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that my actions at Rumaylah were completely
appropriate and warranted in order to defend my troops against
unknown and largely unknowable enemy forces and intentions,''
McCaffrey said in a May 8 letter to The New Yorker responding to
Hersh's questions.
</P>
<P>
   The Army investigators' memo also said that ''after extensive
interviews with personnel from brigade and battalion commanders to
privates, there was no evidence'' that soldiers at Jalibah Airfield
''killed or mistreated'' prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators did find that one Iraqi prisoner was
''accidentally shot'' two days before the U.S. attack at the
airfield. But they said that shooting was reported up the chain of
command and ''properly determined to have been an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The allegations surfaced in August 1991 in an anonymous letter
alleging the attack after the cease-fire was ''a war crime''
covered up by military leaders and that soldiers ''slaughtered some
prisoners after the Jaliba Airfield attack.''
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey was a four-star general when he retired to take the
drug policy post. He has waged a pre-emptive strike against the New
Yorker article, complaining to reporters and editors about Hersh's
tactics in interviews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 2023 </TRAILER>
