<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USDA Sugar To Stabilize Prices  </HEADLINE>
By PHILIP BRASHER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Agriculture Department announced plans
Thursday to buy and store 150,000 tons of surplus sugar, worth an
estimated $60 million, to prop up domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
   The department put off the decision about what to do with the
sugar. The department has considered donating it overseas or
selling it at a steep discount for refining into ethanol, a fuel
additive normally made from corn.
</P>
<P>
   With domestic sugar prices down 25 percent from a year ago,
growers have been threatening to forfeit to the government as much
as $550 million worth of sugar pledged as collateral on federal
marketing loans.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are acting to help address dramatically low sugar prices,''
said Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman. ''By buying U.S. sugar
now, we expect to save as much as $6 million in administrative
costs that the government might otherwise incur from expected loan
forfeitures later this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of candy and food makers, consumer advocates, and
environmental groups that opposes the sugar program has urged
Glickman to allow prices to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman's decision, announced Thursday night, came on the eve
of a visit by President Clinton to Minnesota, a major sugar-growing
state. Clinton and Glickman were to visit a farm outside of the
Minneapolis-St. Paul area Friday to appeal for Congress to approve
permanent trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   The government guarantees farmers a minimum price for domestic
sugar through the loan program and quotas on imports, but increases
in domestic production are making it difficult for USDA to control
domestic prices.
</P>
<P>
   Growers who put their sugar up as collateral for a federal loan
have the right to forfeit the crop to the government if prices fall
below the guaranteed price.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sugar program does not need Band-Aids, it needs major
surgery,'' groups opposed to the program said in a letter last
month to Glickman.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman urged sugar growers to cut back on plantings by idling
land in the government's Conservation Reserve Program, which pays
farmers to take acreage out of production.
</P>
<P>
   ''We expect the sugar industry to rapidly develop conservation
and production options that can form the basis of a sustainable
sugar policy,'' Glickman said. ''Simply relying on continued
government purchases over the longer term is neither feasible nor
realistic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 2046 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
