<HEADLINE> Miami Mayor Charges Review Ordered  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Gov. Jeb Bush assigned a special
prosecutor Thursday to review the flury of accusations made by
Miami Mayor Joe Carollo and the former city manager in the
aftermath of the Elian Gonzalez raid.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney Bernie McCabe, who works in Pinellas and Pasco
counties, was assigned to review whether criminal charges should be
brought regarding allegations made by former Miami City Manager
Donald Warshaw and Carollo.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo fired Warshaw days after Warshaw refused to fire former
Police Chief William O'Brien, who was alerted to the April 22
federal raid but did not inform the mayor. O'Brien later resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo maintains Warshaw was fired for criticizing him, lying
and trying to turn department heads against him, and not for his
actions in the Elian case.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo also accused Warshaw of extortion, saying Warshaw
threatened to file baseless criminal charges against the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Warshaw later accused Carollo of ordering the police department
to investigate rival politicians, journalists, Spanish-language
radio hosts and supporters of his political opponents. Carollo
denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left Thursday evening for McCabe was not
immediately returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
