<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Congress OKs Labor Bill  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- The Argentine Congress on
Thursday approved a labor reform bill that has sparked weeks of
protests by union groups angry over the bid to overhaul the
country's labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was approved by a vote of 121 to 84 and nearly a week
after dissident union groups staged a 24-hour nationwide strike
against the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the bill was expected and is largely seen as the
centerpiece of the efforts by President Fernando de la Rua to
jump-start Argentina's stalled economy.
</P>
<P>
   It calls for extending the trial period of newly hired workers
from 30 days to 90 days. Companies will have more say in their pay
scales and other issues that kept some foreign investors at bay.
Critics have long claimed too much power rested in the hands of
national union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The government says the new reforms will boost wage flexibility
and create more jobs while reducing the cost of doing business.
Labor leaders claim the new law will hurt workers and do nothing to
ease the country's 14 percent unemployment rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
