<HEADLINE> Braves Turn Triple Play  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- The Atlanta Braves turned their first triple play
in nearly 14 years Thursday against the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   With runners at first and second in the fifth inning, Mike
Lowell hit a grounder that third baseman Chipper Jones backhanded.
Jones took one step and stepped on third, then threw to second
baseman Quilvio Veras, whose relay to first was backhanded on one
hop by Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   Lowell was out by less than half a step.
</P>
<P>
   The last triple play by the Braves was June 5, 1986 at San
Diego. The Marlins last hit into a triple play Sept. 12, 1995
against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   The triple play was the first in the major leagues this year.
There were four last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
