<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan: Economy Improving Modestly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan on Friday slightly upgraded its general
economic assessment, saying improvements were led by growing
activity in the corporate sector.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic Planning Agency said the economy was improving at a
''modest pace,'' but personal consumption and capital spending --
the two main pillars of private demand -- were unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   ''Signs are gradually emerging, primarily in the corporate
sector, of a self-sustaining recovery,'' the EPA said in its
monthly report.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's pronouncements are closely watched by businesses
and economists as key indicators of government thinking on the
state of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of improvement in the corporate sector was a 1.4
percent rise in industrial production from January to March
compared to the same quarter a year ago, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency emphasized that industry surveys estimated industrial
production would rise another 1.3 percent in May after slipping 1.0
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is fighting to overcome a decade-long economic downturn.
The economy fell back into recession late last year after a short
period of uneven growth. Unemployment is at a record high of 4.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs of hope, however. Many corporations have
restructured over the past year, and industrial activity has begun
to show signs of perking up.
</P>
<P>
   The government has also tried boosting the economy through
massive injections of public money.
</P>
<P>
   Takashi Omori, the EPA's director of domestic economic affairs,
cited growing inventories at companies as a sign that businesses
are ''stocking up in a forward-looking manner.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal consumption, however, continues to suffer from flagging
incomes, while capital spending is expected to be lower than
year-earlier levels for the January to March quarter, Omori said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
