<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Getting Corzine out in the open, Florio goes after him hard in TV debate </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Thrilled to get his wealthy opponent out in
the open, Jim Florio tirelessly attacked Jon Corzine on Thursday in
the first of their four debates in the Democratic primary for U.S.
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Corzine stumbled and fumbled nervously for some of
his answers, unable to match Florio's clipped statements and direct
attacks. But the former Wall Street executive new to elective
politics also avoided any significant blunder that could haunt him
in the final three weeks of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidates are scheduled to face off three more
times next week. Thursday's debate was taped at New Jersey Network
studios here and aired on NJN at 9 p.m. Thursday. It also was
scheduled to air at 3 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The debating comes on the heels of a poll by Quinnipiac College
of Hamden, Conn., that concluded Corzine had gained a 48-33 percent
lead over Florio, a dramatic turn of the tables from a poll by the
same institute in March that had given Florio a 2-to-1 edge. Many
doubted the accuracy of the latest poll, including both campaign
staffs, because it did not screen for likely voters, but most did
accept the notion that Corzine was gaining rapidly as his $1
million-a-week TV ad blitz was starting to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   The chief issue in the debate Thursday was Social Security, with
both Democrats claiming positions in line with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine supports gradually investing Social Security funds in
the stock market up to 15 percent of the total reserve, saying
market gains will shore up the strength of retirement benefits. He
called it the Clinton-Corzine plan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stand with President Clinton for securing and strengthening
Social Security,'' Corzine said.
</P>
<P>
   Florio denounced the proposal as ''privatization'' that would
allow Wall Street brokers to ''play with our money'' at the risk of
great losses. He claimed Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic candidate for president, have now denounced it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am pleased that the president rejects it, the vice president
rejects, I do and most members of the New Jersey congressional
delegation reject it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton last year proposed stock-market investment for Social
Security, and the idea was included in his budget proposal now
before Congress. But the president has backed off in the face of
Congressional opposition and to give Gore leeway to attack his
Republican presidential opponent, Texas Gov. George Bush, for his
stock-market investment proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine on Thursday attempted to explain his ''bold ideas''
platform for mandatory health insurance coverage, an $8-an-hour
minimum wage, government financing for urban business and universal
education for all, regardless of ability to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Florio countered that Corzine's proposals were so sweeping as to
be fantasy and would have ruinous impact on the federal budget.
''This is not bold, this is baloney,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have some tangible accomplishments,'' Florio said. ''I have
experience money can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio's attack was constant as he ignored several questions in
order to use the allotted debate time to pick on Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when asked about the crisis in Sierra Leone,
Florio criticized Corzine's former firm, Goldman Sachs, for
financing oil enterprises in Sudan, claiming the firm's actions
provided financial support to a repressive government.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about racial profiling, Florio talked about ethnic
jokes attributed to Corzine which the candidate has said he does
not recall making but for which he has nevertheless apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
</TEXT>
