<HEADLINE> Grenade Eyed in Salvador Blast  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- A massive explosion at a
military arms depot that injured at least 55 people and damaged
hundreds of homes was probably triggered by the accidental
explosion of a grenade, the defense minister said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Juan Martinez Varela told a news conference that the
explosion of a grenade is what ''we believe set off a chain
reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion occurred Wednesday afternoon in a storage area
beneath a former military barracks on the northern edge of the
capital. Officials say 408 nearby houses were damaged or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said the site had been built with safety in mind: ''It
is precisely because the storehouse was built that way that the
damage has not been so grave.''
</P>
<P>
   He said police and military explosives experts were removing
grenades and other weapons that the explosion had hurled hundreds
of yards around the site. Thousands of people live in that area.
</P>
</TEXT>
