<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A rally on Wall Street helped Tokyo stocks rebound
somewhat early Friday from the previous day's plunge. The dollar
was lower against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 344.75
points, or 2.04 percent, to 17,227.21 in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Thursday, the average closed down 819.01 points, or
4.63 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 107.76 yen, down 1.94 yen from late Thursday
in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 108.53 yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, prices started higher with buying centered
on information technology issues in line with a similar move in
U.S. stocks Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index rose
114.85 points to 3,499.58 at Thursday's finish. The Dow Jones
industrial average climbed 178.19 points to close at 10,545.97.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's rebound on Wall Street came after a report of a
slowdown in U.S. retail sales calmed investors who have been
selling stocks amid fears about rising interest rates ahead of a
Federal Reserve policy-board meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 29.40 points, or 1.84 percent, to 1,630.13.
The TOPIX closed down 59.13 points, or 3.56 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar moved lower
against the yen as some investors locked in profits following the
greenback's recent gains.
</P>
<P>
   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 97.38 yen, down from
99.52 yen late Thursday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.6950 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.6800 percent. Its
price fell 0.13 point to 100.90.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
