<DOCNO> APW20000511.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayors, Clinton administration endorse march for gun control  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton plans a kickoff reception
for 1,000 mothers attending Sunday's rally for gun control, while
city leaders from around the country endorsed the Mother's Day
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Million Mom March'' has special meaning for Scott King,
mayor of Gary, Ind. His 17-year-old nephew was shot to death in
June after fighting with another teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a different ball game when you sit in a church and you
hear sobbing behind you, and it's your own children sobbing for
their cousin,'' said King, who was representing the U.S. Conference
of Mayor's with Anthony Williams of the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The rally for licensing of gun owners and registration of their
handguns will take place on the National Mall and in more than 70
other communities nationwide. Donna Dees-Thomases, a Short Hills,
N.J., mother came up with the idea for the march.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reception by the president and Hillary Rodham
Clinton is intended to launch the march. Mrs. Clinton, running for
the Senate from New York, is expected to join numerous celebrities
and politicians in the demonstration. The president will not attend
because of security precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also told reporters he did not want to steal the
limelight from organizers. Asked whether the march could motivate
Congress to pass more gun control, Clinton said, ''I don't know,
but it ought to.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore was slated to baby sit his grandson,
Wyatt, on Sunday so that his wife, Tipper, and their daughter,
Karenna, could join the march.
</P>
<P>
   The president said that ''if a couple hundred thousand people
show up here and several hundred thousand at these sites around the
country it ought to send a signal that we want America to be a safe
country and common sense gun legislation is part of the strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno told her weekly news conference that
she hopes to finish a commencement address at Northwestern
University law school in the Chicago area in time to attend a march
there.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush, when asked about
the rally, said, ''I'm glad there's a lot of people talking about
gun violence. Gun violence concerns a lot of folks and it should.''
Bush said he supports use of trigger locks on guns.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, members of a pro-gun organization, Second Amendment
Sisters, plan speeches on the Washington Monument grounds and a
march to the Capitol. The event is independent of the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled as the keynote speaker for the self-defense advocacy
group is Texas state Rep. Suzanna Gratia-Hupp. Nearly a decade ago,
she was a patron in a restaurant in Killeen, Texas, when an armed
man entered and killed 21 people, including her parents.
</P>
<P>
   Gratia-Hupp has said that if she had been allowed by law to
carry her legally owned sidearm into the restaurant, she would have
been able to stop the man with a clear shot from less than 5 yards
away.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor King from Indiana spoke to reporters in front of the U.S.
Conference of Mayors' ''Wall of Death,'' which has 4,001 names of
gun violence victims since the April 1999 shootings at Columbine
High School in Colorado. The name of his nephew, Blake King, was
among those listed.
</P>
<P>
   King said that after Blake had a scuffle with a friend, the
other teen-ager went to his home next door and returned with his
father's handgun. King said that while he was growing up in
Chicago, ''I got into the same kind of fights. But no guns were
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-fourths of women surveyed in a new Gallup poll said they
support more strict gun controls, compared with about half of the
men questioned.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 1,031 adults was taken May 5-7 and has an error
margin of 3 percentage points, larger for subgroups.
</P>
<P>
