<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild animal sanctuaries will find homes for Tiger Lady's big cats  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Several wild animal sanctuaries across the
country have agreed to take in 26 Bengal tigers from a Jackson
Township preserve that has lost its permit to keep them.
</P>
<P>
   ''We got commitments from (several members), we're just trying
to figure out how to split them up amicably,'' said Carol Asvestas,
a board member of the American Sanctuary Association, a 27-member
coalition of wild animal preserves nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Asvestas, president of the Wild Animal Orphanage in San Antonio,
Texas, said Thursday that her organization has worked to place the
animals since officials from the New Jersey Division of Fish and
Wildlife contacted her 1{ years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We agreed to take them if necessary,'' Asvestas said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Joan Byron-Marasek had 16 big cats at her Tigers
Only Preservation Society. Today, there are 26. Asvestas was
dismayed that Byron-Marasek has allowed her brood to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has not been responsible enough to stop any breeding, but
that has not altered our commitment. It's just making it a little
more difficult,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Page, a spokesman for the state Department of
Environmental Protection, said the department is considering what
legal steps it can take to thwart any further breeding at the
preserve.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's already a substandard, overcrowded facility. We're hoping
it doesn't get even more overcrowded,'' said Page.
</P>
<P>
   Byron-Marasek's permit to keep the tigers on her Ocean County
compound was revoked after a state investigation revealed the
animals were not receiving proper care. The state also faulted her
for poor record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began when a 431-pound tiger was spotted
roaming about a mile from the compound. It was shot by a police
officer after officials failed to capture it.
</P>
<P>
   Byron-Marasek denied that the tiger belonged to her. The site
also is near Six Flags Great Adventure, which has tigers at its
safari park. DNA tests later confirmed that the tiger had escaped
from the Tigers Only preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Administrative Law Judge John Tassini recommended
that Byron-Marasek's permit not be renewed. She has said she would
fight to keep the big cats on her property.
</P>
<P>
   Page said Byron-Marasek has until Monday to file an exception to
that finding, or she could wait until Department of Environmental
Protection Commissioner Robert Shinn makes his final ruling on the
matter, and then appeal through the court system.
</P>
<P>
   Valter Must, a Lakewood attorney who is representing
Byron-Marasek, told The Times of Trenton for Thursday's edition
that he planned to file a challenge to Tassini's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Although it would be Byron-Marasek's responsibility to relocate
the tigers, state officials took the precautionary measure of
finding them homes.
</P>
<P>
   Asvestas, of the American Sanctuary Association, said the tigers
would be split into groups of five or so and sent to preserves in
California, Illinois, Texas and Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   First they would go to her 50-acre compound in San Antonio for
about 90 days. There, they would receive veterinary care and be
neutered, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asvestas' group worked with the state to find homes for dozens
of wild animals removed from a Scotch Plains zoo three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those animals are thriving beautifully,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
