<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Educators Oppose Fund, Score Tie  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Voluntary national tests given to
schoolchildren should not be used to punish or reward the schools
they attend, a congressional hearing on funding the exams was told
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and the top contenders for his job have
suggested tying federal education grants to student scores on the
National Assessment of Educational Progress, sampled tests in math,
reading and other subjects. But a panel of education experts,
including those who administer the tests, gave House lawmakers
varied reasons for their opposition to changing a yardstick into a
carrot and stick.
</P>
<P>
   The test ''should not be used for high stakes decisions,'' said
Michael E. Ward, North Carolina's superintendent of public
instruction. ''It is critical we preserve and maintain the existing
use for NAEP results.''
</P>
<P>
   The tests -- some given for 30 years in subjects ranging from
math and reading to art and civics -- are generally considered the
only way to compare student progress nationwide, because states'
tests vary so widely.
</P>
<P>
   Their funding and purpose -- along with other education research
programs -- were being reviewed Thursday by a House Education and
Workforce subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   Mark D. Musick, who chairs the board that sets the test
standards, said the tests should mainly be used to track state
progress over time and help validate results from states' own
tests. Consequences, he suggested, could jeopardize the credibility
and integrity of the program: ''Congress should take steps to
ensure that the National Assessment is buffered from partisan
politics. The trusts of the public are too precious to leave up to
good will, personalities and, in a word, chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del., who chairs the House subcommittee,
said Thursday there were many reasons to question a ''high-stakes''
use of the tests. For one, he said, just 40 states give the tests.
Delaware is among ones that can't get enough schools to sign up for
the tests because teachers and students already are burdened with
mandatory exams, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the national exams are not based on any
particular state's academic standards, could skew true measures of
schools by exempting disabled children and non-native English
speakers, and need more independence from local administration
officials who may have a political stake in how the test scores are
recorded and released. But no one said the government should stop
funding the voluntary sampling program, which has cropped up in
various policy speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's budget plan includes $50 million to reward large, but
unspecified, improvements on the math and science tests. Vice
President Al Gore -- accused of using 1998 reading scores to tout
administration successes -- drafted a plan to measure state's
progress based on the scores. And George W. Bush, the presumptive
GOP nominee, said he would reward states, using the tests, the SAT
and other exams.
</P>
<P>
   Gore believes NAEP can be used as a tool to hold states
accountable for improving student achievement, said spokesman Doug
Hattaway.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under his state accountability plan, states would be required
to use NAEP, or develop another means to benchmark their state
assessments against the national standards in NAEP,'' Hattaway said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The National Assessment of Educational Progress:
http://nces.ed.gov/nationsreportcard/site/home.asp
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 2208 </TRAILER>
