<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worker Admits Education Dept. Theft  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Bell Atlantic technician under contract with
the Education Department has pleaded guilty to taking part in a
scheme that defrauded the agency of $1 million since 1997, federal
officials said Thursday. Several Education Department employees and
contract workers could be charged, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The fraud involved stealing television sets, digital cameras,
computers and falsely charging for overtime, said Wilma Lewis, the
U.S. attorney for the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Six Education Department workers, who were not further
identified, have been suspended without pay indefinitely, said
Erica Lepping, a department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Three contract workers with Bell Atlantic and another
undisclosed company have been fired, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have zero tolerance for illegal activity,'' said Lepping,
who said two-thirds of the stolen property had been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The technician, Robert J. Sweeney, 42, of Upper Marlboro, Md.,
pleaded guilty to conspiracy and theft charges in U.S. District
Court on Wednesday. He faces a maximum 15 years in prison and a
$500,000 fine when he is sentenced at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   ''Bell Atlantic cooperated fully with the federal authorities
throughout their investigation,'' said spokesman Steven Marcus, who
added that the telecommunications company fired Sweeney last
December after its own investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Sweeney, assigned full-time to install phones in
department offices, began sometime in the mid-1990s ordering
equipment such as phones and answering machines unrelated to his
work. He picked them up from a warehouse and gave them to
co-workers for personal use. The stolen items included a 61-inch
television, computers, digital cameras and more than 100 cordless
phones.
</P>
<P>
   These purchases alone costs the department more than $300,000,
investigators said. Sweeney charged the department overtime for
driving employees and their family members to doctors appointments
and one trip to Baltimore to get one co-worker crabcakes for her
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery of the scheme comes as the department has tried to
defend itself against congressional charges of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Pete Hoekstra, R-Mich., chairman the House Education and
Workforce Committee panel that oversees Education Department
spending, said the $1 million may only be the ''tip of the
iceberg.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We have received several tips from people within the
department about other examples of potential waste, fraud and
abuse,'' he said. ''We have already found several examples of
duplicate payments made by the department and other examples of
waste.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an internal audit found that the department forgave
nearly $4 million in student loans for borrowers who were supposed
to be dead but were alive and drawing income.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
