<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Leads Gore Among Women  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush has pulled even with Al Gore in
women's support, helping the Republican edge ahead in a broader
survey of likely presidential voters. Americans say they also feel
Bush is more charismatic, has a better sense of humor and is more
inspiring.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, people in the new polling said they find
Gore, the Democratic vice president, more attractive and more
caring about people.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign polls out Thursday suggested that Bush, the Texas
governor, has largely recovered from his slump in the polls in
March and has made gains among several key voter groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''You get the sense that Bush has repaired some of the damage
from the campaign,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew
Research Center for the People and the Press, although he noted
that voter preferences are still fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made significant progress with many voter groups,
according to a Voter.com-Battleground poll, which showed him doing
especially well among women and better than he had been among union
households.
</P>
<P>
   It also suggested voters are increasingly pessimistic that the
country is on the wrong track -- a bad sign for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   When the potential margin of sampling error is taken into
account, Gore and Bush were essentially tied in the Battleground
poll among women, a group that Gore very much needs if he is to win
in November. President Clinton carried the women's vote by 16
points in 1996 while splitting the men's vote with Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lead over Gore among men has remained in double digits
this year, while women's support for the Republican is now 4 points
higher than for Gore, a reversal of the 5-point Gore advantage in
March.
</P>
<P>
   ''Women voters in particular are more negative about the
direction of the country,'' said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake,
who helped conduct the bipartisan Battleground poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll comes at a time when Gore repeatedly describes the
likely Republican presidential nominee's proposals as ''risky'' or
''reckless.'' Democrats are hoping that tactic eventually will
create a sense of unease about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ''All the indications are that Bush has an edge in the race and
that Gore is the underdog, which is unbelievable given the strong
economy and what Bush went through in the primaries,'' said
political analyst Stuart Rothenberg.
</P>
<P>
   The Voter.com-Battleground poll highlighted Gore's challenges in
the race. Nationally, Bush led Gore 48 percent to 42 percent among
likely voters in the bipartisan survey by Democratic pollster Lake
and Republican pollster Ed Goeas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a Los Angeles Times poll showed Bush leading among
registered voters by 51 percent to 43 percent. A Pew poll of
registered voters showed the race essentially even.
</P>
<P>
   While such results give an indication of support nationwide, the
presidential contest will be settled by separate elections in each
state, with candidates competing for electoral votes en route to
the required 270.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's improved performance was reflected in an ABC-Washington
Post poll released late Thursday. Bush had a 49 percent to 44
percent edge over Gore in the poll, compared to a dead heat in the
same poll in April. Gore led on the question of who would do a
better job on the issues of gun control, Social Security and
prescription drug benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Voters feel the country is going in the wrong direction by 49
percent to 39 percent, according to the Voter.com-Battleground
poll. Both pollsters agreed the negative sentiment is bad for
incumbents, especially Democrats. Voters' top issues were moral
values and education, with both polls reflecting a focus on concern
about children.
</P>
<P>
   The Battleground poll found that Bush had a 55 percent to 41
percent lead among so-called Reagan Democrats. Gore had a 12-point
lead among Hispanics, a group that once favored Bush, and a big
advantage among single women and blacks.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 1,000 likely voters was taken May 1-3 and had an
error margin of plus or minus 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In six state polls released Thursday, Bush and Gore were
competitive in Michigan and New Jersey, while Bush had an edge in
Georgia, North Carolina and Ohio. Bush was 20 points ahead in
Virginia, according to the polls by the American Research Group.
</P>
<P>
   The scant attention being paid to the campaign at this stage
''means the background dynamics of the election come to the fore,''
said political scientist Bruce Buchanan of the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though the economy is good, among key groups like
independent voters there is an element of wanting to move toward
change, but in a safe way,'' he said. ''And the governor looks
acceptable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
