<HEADLINE> Notes From Thursday's Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Royals-Indians:
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Kansas City is in a 32-day stretch where it plays
21 of 27 games on the road. ... The Royals have the best home
record in the AL at 14-4. The Royals have batted .334 and averaged
6.9 runs a game at home. ... RHP Miguel Batista, acquired recently
from Montreal, is scheduled to make his first appearance against
Cleveland on Friday. ... When Kansas City shut out Detroit on
Wednesday, the Royals became the final major-league team to
participate in a shutout this season.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: Acting manager Grady Little said the Indians will
activate OF Kenny Lofton and RHP Bartolo Colon on Friday. Lofton
has been sidelined with a strained left biceps since April 30.
Colon, out since April 16 with a pulled left oblique muscle, is
scheduled to start Friday night. ... Lofton's return means
Cleveland's lineup will be at full strength for the first time
since April 18 -- when catcher Sandy Alomar went out with a strained
hamstring. Alomar returned Monday. ... Reliever Steve Karsay said
he does not feel any adverse effects of warming up during five
straight games and appearing in four of them. ''The more I throw,
the sharper I feel,'' said Karsay, who had arthroscopic surgery on
his right elbow last winter. ... From 1995 through last season,
Cleveland compiled a 41-19 record against Kansas City.
Red Sox-Orioles:
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: Tim Wakefield got his first start of the year Thursday
against Baltimore, and it followed a relief appearance one night
earlier against the White Sox. He's the first Boston pitcher to
start a game after making a relief appearance since Vaughn
Eschelman in 1996. ... Jose Offerman singled on the first pitch to
bring his batting average eight points to .206.
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: RHP Pat Rapp got his first start against the Red Sox
since they let him go during the offseason rather than pick up his
$3 million option. ... The Orioles have won only one of the last
five season series against Boston. ... Jeff Conine started at 1B,
his 12th straight start, despite a lifetime .083 average against
Wakefield. ... Baltimore's top two starters, Mike Mussina and Scott
Erickson, are a combined 1-5.
Devil Rays-Yankees:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: The Devil Rays completed a nine-game stretch against
teams that made the playoffs last season. They were 2-6 in the
first eight games against Texas, Boston and New York. ... Of the
Devil Rays first 32 games, 13 were decided in the game's final
inning including Tuesday night's 4-3, 10-inning loss at New York.
Wednesday's rainout was only the sixth in Tampa Bay history, three
of them this season (two in April at Baltimore). ... Before
Saturday's home game against Toronto, Piniellas County officials
will unveil the Millennium quilt that illustrates educational
programs in the county aimed at children in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: SS Derek Jeter left the game after the second inning
with an abdominal strain in his left side. He is listed as
day-to-day. Jeter has been mired in a slump and flied out in his
only at-bat to extend his hitless streak to 13 at bats over his
last four games. ... Chuck Knoblauch played his second straight
game at second base for only the second time since April 22-23 at
Toronto when he injured his left wrist while swinging a bat in the
on-deck circle. He returned to the lineup Tuesday night after
missing six games and had a pop-fly double that helped set up the
winning run in the l0th inning. ... The Yankees opening day
starting lineup played only its seventh game as a unit Thursday.
Mariners-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: Manager Lou Piniella said LHP Jamie Moyer, who is on
the DL with a strained muscle in the back of his left shoulder,
will try to throw off a mound for the first time Friday. ''He's
getting close. (Friday) the first true test comes. He's thrown long
tosses a few times and there's been no pain,'' Piniella said. ''We
feel fairly comfortable he's in the neighborhood of two weeks away
(from returning).'' ... Piniella said LHP Rob Ramsay, who has a
sore left shoulder, should be available sometime in this weekend's
series against Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: OF Terrence Long, who was struck in the face by a ball
during warmups Wednesday, had surgery Thursday and had his lip
stitched. The swelling in his mouth will have to subside before it
can be determined if he has any nerve damage, but X-rays showed he
has no facial fractures. Manager Art Howe said it was hard to
determine when Long, who was in a lot of pain Thursday, can return.
... Howe said DH John Jaha, who is on the disabled list with a left
shoulder strain, is not likely to return before June. He has begun
hitting fungoes, but still has to heal and then go through a
rehabilitation assignment. ''The end of the month would be
optimistic,'' Howe said. ''That may be a reach.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: David Segui, who came into this season with a lifetime
.285 batting average, entered the game against Anaheim hitting .387
-- one point ahead of Anaheim's Darin Erstad. ''I've always thought
I was a pretty decent hitter, so this doesn't surprise me,'' said
Segui, who hit .301 over his previous five seasons. ''I'm glad I'm
doing well, but we've only been playing for a month and a half. If
I'm still hitting this well in August and September, I think I'll
get a little more excited about it.'' ... The only batting champion
in Rangers history was Julio Franco, who hit .341 in 1991. ... LHP
Justin Thompson is scheduled to undergo season-ending arthroscopic
surgery on Friday in Fort Worth to repair a torn rotator cuff.
Thompson had surgery last August to repair a torn labrum in his
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: Mo Vaughn feels that Darin Erstad, who set a major
league record for hits in April with 48, has as good a chance as
anyone to become the second player in Angels history to win a
batting title -- and the first since Alex Johnson in 1970. ''He's
got a great opportunity to do it. It's right there for him,''
Vaughn said. ''It's not something he'll be thinking about now, but
he'll look up in late September and realize where he is. He has a
nice approach and a good stroke, so he'll get his hits. But you
also have to have a lot of luck for things to be going that well,
because it isn't always going to be like that.'' ... Garret
Anderson already has hit four home runs against left-handed
pitchers, one more than he did last season. ... Of Vaughn's nine
home runs, seven have come leading off an inning. ... Angels
pitchers had given up an AL-leading 53 home runs entering
Thursday's games.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Padres-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: Reliever Rodney Myers, who tore the tendon below his
right kneecap while fielding a bunt, will become the seventh San
Diego pitcher and the 12th Padre on the disabled list this season.
... Bret Boone had the ninth multihomer game of his career,
including the 13th inside-the-park homer by a Padre. The last one
was Gwynn's grand slam in Los Angeles on June 26, 1997. ... Bret
and Aaron Boone both hit homers, marking the first time that two
brothers homered against each other in the same game since the
Boones did it last Sept. 1. It was only the eighth time that
brothers playing against each other homered in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Ken Griffey Jr. hit his 408th career homer, tying
Cal Ripken Jr. for 28th on the list. ... Dmitri Young, who missed
the last two games because of a stomach virus, doubled in his
second at-bat, extending his hitting streak to a career-high 16
games. It's the longest streak by a Red since Hal Morris hit in 29
games in 1996.
Brewers-Cubs:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: OF Jeromy Burnitz was hitting .111 in the Brewers
last homestand and went 6-for-18 with nine RBIs in four games
against the Cubs. ... Mark Loretta had five hits, equaling his
career high which he also achieved July 17 against Kansas City. ...
Right-hander John Snyder made his second rehab start Wednesday for
Class A Huntsville and gave up three runs, four hits and two walks
in 6 2-3 innings. Snyder has been on the DL with a strained left
oblique muscle since the end of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: An MRI Thursday showed a slight tear in 1B Mark Grace's
left hamstring. He was placed on the 15-day disabled list and 1B
Julio Zuleta was recalled from Class AAA Iowa. Grace was injured
running to first in the ninth inning. Zuleta hit .302 at Iowa. ...
Manager Don Baylor gave 2B Eric Young a day off Thursday. ''There
was no argument on his part,'' Baylor said of Young, who was
hitting .318. ... Television broadcaster Steve Stone will miss the
weekend series in Montreal to continue recuperating from removal of
kidney stones. ... Jose Nieves replaced Jeff Huson at second base
in the third inning when Huson strained a muscle in his left rib
cage during an at-bat. Huson's status was day to day. It was
Nieves' first major league appearance at second.
Braves-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Tom Glavine, who lost for the first time this season
Wednesday, is 2-8 at Pro Player Stadium with a 5.25 ERA. He hasn't
won in Miami in his past six starts, dating back to May 3, 1995.
... Florida left-handed slugger Cliff Floyd, who had a two-run
double against Glavine, hiked his average against lefties to .333.
Against right-handers he was hitting .200. ... Through Wednesday,
the Braves were hitting .143 (5-for-35) with the bases loaded,
worst in the National League. Twice Wednesday they loaded the bases
with none out and failed to score.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: The Marlins transferred left-hander Michael Tejera to
the 60-day DL from the 15-day disabled list. Tejera is recovering
from a torn ligament in his pitching elbow.
Phillies-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: 1B Rico Brogna was placed on the 15-day DL with a
broken bone in his left wrist. Brogna, who was hit on the wrist by
a Matt Blank pitch in the ninth inning of Wednesday's 8-0 win over
the Expos, returned to Philadelphia. He had his wrist examined by
team physician Dr. Michael Ciccotti and hand specialist Dr. Randall
Culp, who will operate on Brogna's wrist on Friday. Brogna is
expected to be out for the next 10-12 weeks. ... The Phillies
purchased the contract of 1B Chris Pritchett from Triple-A
Scranton/Wilkes-Barre.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Closer Ugueth Urbina had an MRI performed on his
injured right elbow. Urbina felt pain in his elbow after throwing
his first pitch while warming up during Tuesday's 3-2 win over the
Phillies. X-rays were taken on Wednesday, leading to Thursday's
MRI. Urbina, who had bone chips removed from his right elbow
following the 1996 season, has eight saves and 22 strikeouts in 13
1-3 innings. With Urbina and setup men Graeme Lloyd and Scott
Strickland all sidelined by arm injuries, staff ace Dustin
Hermanson, who was scheduled to face Chicago's Kerry Wood on
Friday, was asked to assume the closer's role. ''I thought it
wouldn't be a problem,'' Hermanson said. ''I have the mentality of
a closer.'' ... Hermanson's move to the bullpen moved Mike
Thurman's season debut up a day to Friday. Tony Armas Jr. will be
called up from Triple-A Ottawa to start on Saturday. 
Mets-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Rickey Henderson remains with the Mets -- and continues
to start in LF -- despite clearing waivers. The Mets now can send
him to the minors between now and July 31 without sending him
through waivers, though he probably would decline such an
assignment. ... Grant Roberts is expected to make his major league
debut Saturday against the Marlins. Roberts, who last pitched
Saturday, is 1-2 with a 3.44 and 34 strikeouts in 36 2-3 innings at
Triple-A Norfolk. ... Bobby J. Jones, hurt during the Mets' visit
to Pittsburgh last month, will make his second rehabilitation start
at Norfolk on Friday night. He allowed nine hits and one run in
seven innings against Syracuse in his first start.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Pirates right-hander Francisco Cordova is apparently
headed to the DL with a sore right elbow after experiencing
additional discomfort while throwing on the sideline. The Pirates
probably will call up a pitcher from the minors to start Saturday
against Milwaukee. ... The Pirates were 4-8 against the Brewers
last season, 0-6 at Three Rivers Stadium. ... Right-hander Brad
Clontz, who spent some time with the Pirates before returning
recently to Triple-A Nashville. ... Pirates 1B Kevin Young went on
a 9-for-18 tear after noticing he wasn't keeping his left elbow
tucked in properly. ... Pirates starters have failed to retire the
side in the first inning in every game since April 30. Jimmy
Anderson allowed two runs and two hits Thursday against the Mets.
</P>
