<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
The Associated Press
Lewis Allen
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Lewis Allen, who directed the ghost
story classic ''The Uninvited'' starring Ray Milland and the
presidential assassin movie ''Suddenly'' with Frank Sinatra, died
May 3. He was 94.
</P>
<P>
   Allen also directed ''Our Hearts Were Young and Gay'' with Diana
Lynn, ''The Perfect Marriage'' with David Niven and Loretta Young,
''Another Time, Another Place'' with Lana Turner and Sean Connery,
''Desert Fury'' with Burt Lancaster and the Alan Ladd pictures
''Appointment with Danger'' and ''Chicago Deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen directed television shows that included ''Bonanza,''
''Little House on the Prairie,'' ''Mission Impossible,'' ''The
Fugitive,'' ''The Rifleman,'' ''Perry Mason'' and ''I Dream of
Jeannie.''
</P>
<P>
William J. Boyle
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- William J. Boyle, a banker who played a major
role in devising the first bank-issued credit card, died April 30.
He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, Boyle developed the Franklin Charge Account Plan, which
charged interest and let customers make partial payments each
month, at the Franklin National Bank in Rockville Centre, N.Y. It
was a forerunner of Visa and Mastercard.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, charge plans were largely limited to big New York
department stores. In 1950, Diners Club introduced the first charge
card, meaning that balances had to be paid in full. Franklin's
plan, which used the slogan ''Just charge it,'' was the first
credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle left Franklin in the early 1950s and founded Eastern
National Bank in 1956 in Smithtown, N.Y. He served as chairman and
president for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Robert L. Helms
</P>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Construction entrepreneur Robert L. Helms,
whose name became synonymous with Interstate 80, subdivisions, a
Sparks gravel pit and, eventually, bankruptcy, died Tuesday. He was
78.
</P>
<P>
   Helms was working as a Sierra Pacific lineman in 1951 when he
bought five trucks at auction and turned them into the multimillion
dollar Robert L. Helms Construction and Development Co.
</P>
<P>
   In two years, Helms made $20,000 and used it to buy construction
equipment. Projects included old U.S. 40 and its successor, I-80.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, Helms' holdings were worth an estimated $200 million
and included everything from the construction company to Double
Diamond Ranch in south Reno.
</P>
<P>
   By December of that year, the construction company was closed as
part of a bankruptcy proceeding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 2214 </TRAILER>
