<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Insanity Plea Accepted in NY Murder  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) -- A law professor who once was
celebrated for overcoming schizophrenia will not stand trial for
killing his pregnant fiancee after prosecutors accepted his
insanity plea Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they accepted Michael Laudor's plea of not
responsible by means of mental defect because they conceded that no
jury would convict him of murder in the face of three doctors'
conclusions that Laudor was insane.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered that Laudor be re-evaluated to determine his
treatment. Laudor told the judge he was expecting to be returned to
the Mid-Hudson Forensic Psychiatric Center in New Hampton, where he
has been receiving treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Under state rules governing insanity pleas, if the state Office
of Mental Health and the court ever agreed that Laudor was no
longer a danger to himself or others, he could be released.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Costello, 37, was found slashed to death June 17, 1998,
in the kitchen of the apartment she shared with Laudor in
Hastings-on-Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatric reports summarized in court found that Laudor killed
Costello because he thought she was ''a nonhuman impostor''
conspiring to hospitalize him for torture, experimentation and
death.
</P>
<P>
   Laudor, 37, had won some fame for succeeding as a Yale Law
School graduate and instructor despite his schizophrenia. He had
sold book and movie rights to his story and was considered a role
model for victims who control schizophrenia through medication.
</P>
<P>
   At some point after the death of his father in 1997, he stopped
taking his medication, apparently believing it to be part of a
conspiracy against him, and his condition deteriorated, Prosecutor
Barbara Egenhauser said.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the killing, Costello stayed home from work to try
to help. Laudor's mother and doctor arranged for a visit from a
crisis intervention team. That impending visit, according to one
psychiatric report, precipitated the killing because Laudor thought
he would be tortured and lobotomized.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after the killing, his lawyer said Laudor still did
not realize Costello was dead. Doctors originally found him unfit
to stand trial, then reversed that decision a year later.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution, anticipating an insanity defense, hired
forensic psychiatrist Park Dietz, who Egenhauser said was ''known
for having a high threshold'' for insanity. But Dietz agreed with
the defense psychiatrists that Laudor believed his fiancee was ''a
nonperson, a robot or a doll ... planning to kill or torture him.''
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, saying she had no choice but to
accept the insanity plea, complained about ''a criminal justice
system that allows a psychiatrist to decide whether an individual
stands trial.'' She said psychiatric reports should be considered
only at sentencing, after ''it is decided in a courtroom who
committed a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim's mother and sister railed against the idea that
Laudor was not responsible for Costello's death.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is horrifying for us to accept that our daughter was
murdered by someone she loved and trusted,'' said Marilyn Costello.
''It is horrifying for us to accept that she died all alone,
bleeding, terrified and in pain. ... Michael Laudor alone must bear
the responsibility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 2214 </TRAILER>
