<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Hints at More S.Leone Troops  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Embattled U.N. forces in Sierra Leone
might need reinforcements and an expanded mandate to combat rebel
attacks and salvage the country's battered peace process,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan suggested Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a late-night emergency meeting of the Security
Council, Annan welcomed the deployment of about 800 British troops
as well as offers by West African countries to contribute extra
forces -- including a possible rapid-reaction force that could take
on a combat role in enforcing the country's peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   But he stressed that wealthy nations would have to pay for it
and contribute logistical support to have ''the capacity to carry
out the tasks this mandate implies.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is vital that the world should not now abandon the people
of Sierra Leone in their hour of greatest need,'' Annan told the
council.
</P>
<P>
   ''I plead with you,'' he said, clasping his hands in front of
him. ''Let us not fail Sierra Leone. Let us not fail Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan's comments, delivered quietly in a hushed chamber, began a
lengthy debate by the council and a dozen other U.N. member states
on how the United Nations can reinforce its 8,700-member mission to
save a crumbling peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 500 U.N. peacekeepers have been taken hostage since
May 1 in attacks by rebels, which have posed a major challenge to
the U.N. peace mission.
</P>
<P>
   ''This test of the U.N. mission in Sierra Leone shows very
clearly that the mandate and resources are not and never were
appropriate to the situation,'' said Abdallah Baali, Algeria's U.N.
ambassador who spoke on behalf of the Organization of African
Unity.
</P>
<P>
   He urged the council adopt a more combat-oriented mandate for
the peacekeepers, who currently are authorized to use force to
protect themselves and civilians in danger but have refrained from
any offensive attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But deputy British Ambassador Stuart Eldon cautioned against
such an ''over-hasty approach,'' saying the focus should be on
getting the existing force up to speed to implement its current
mandate.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations has mobilized the remaining three battalions
that would bring the force up to its authorized strength of 11,100,
and the force is now expected to be fully deployed by the end of
the month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-11-00 2222 </TRAILER>
