<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000511.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies 6, Expos 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Montreal third baseman Michael Barrett's error
with two outs in the seventh inning allowed the go-ahead run to
score in the Philadelphia Phillies' 6-4 win over the Expos on
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Wolf (2-2) allowed four runs -- three earned -- and seven
hits in six innings as the Phillies won for the sixth time in their
last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   With Philadelphia trailing 4-3, Mickey Morandini singled off
Carl Pavano (3-1) and scored on Tom Prince's double to tie the
game.
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Prince advanced to third on Kevin Sefcik's
grounder to first. Desi Relaford walked and left-hander Matt Blank
came in to face Bobby Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   Abreu hit a grounder which caromed off Barrett into short left
field, as Prince scored to make it 5-4. Shortstop Orlando Cabrera
recovered the ball and threw to Barrett to cut down Relaford, who
was trying to advance to third. It was Barrett's ninth error of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gomes, who allowed three runs in Tuesday's 3-2 loss for
his second blown save, pitched the ninth for his sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal lost its first home series in six at Olympic Stadium
this season. The Expos are 11-7 at home.
</P>
<P>
   Pavano, who struck out a career-high seven in 6 2-3 innings,
allowed Kevin Jordan's two-run triple in the first and Scott
Rolen's RBI double in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vidro's three-run homer in the bottom half tied it at 3.
Montreal took a 4-3 lead in the fourth when Cabrera's double to the
left field corner rolled past Ron Gant for a two-base error.
Cabrera slid home safely just ahead of the relay.
</P>
<P>
   Morandini hit an RBI triple off Anthony Telford to drive in
Philadelphia's sixth run in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan started at first base in place of Rico Brogna, who was
lost to the Phillies for the next 10-12 weeks with a broken left
wrist.
Notes: A season-low crowd of 8,311 was on hand for the game. ...
... Pavano allowed five runs -- three earned -- and five hits. ...
Phillies reliever Jeff Brantley allowed one hit in two innings in
his second appearance of the season. ... Expos closer Ugueth Urbina
had an MRI performed on his injured right elbow Thursday. Dustin
Hermanson moved to the bullpen and Mike Thurman will start Friday.
Tony Armas Jr. will be called up from Triple-A Ottawa to start on
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
