<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Drug Leaders May Head to US  </HEADLINE>
By BEN FOX
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO (AP) -- U.S. authorities unsealed a criminal indictment
Thursday against the alleged leaders of one of Mexico's most
violent and powerful drug gangs, offered a $2 million reward for
their capture and warned they might flee north of the border to
escape Mexican police.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers Ramon and Benjamin Arellano Felix were charged with
operating a smuggling organization that shipped large quantities of
drugs into Southern California from Mexico and maintained it
through violence, intimidation and bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Arellano Felix has been on the FBI's 10 most wanted list
for three years and the U.S. State Department has offered a $2
million reward for information leading to his arrest since then.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. authorities decided to include Benjamin Arellano Felix
in the reward and detail the contents of the Nov. 16, 1999
indictment to bring additional pressure on the drug organization,
which has been weakened by a series of arrests in Mexico in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those arrests, and the possibility that Mexican
authorities might be closing in on Felixes, authorities believe the
brothers may attempt to flee to the United States, said prosecutor
Gregory Vega.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because they are so notorious in Mexico, we want to make sure
that the American public knows who these individuals are,'' Vega
said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the drug charges, the indictment accuses them of
kidnapping and murdering rival drug traffickers, suspected
informants and law enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   If caught and convicted, the brothers could face up to life in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the two are wanted on charges including murder,
illegal weapons possession and drug smuggling, said Mariano Herran
Salvatti, the country's top anti-drug prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Either Mexico or the United States could prosecute the men and
then extradite them to the other country to face additional charges
under current treaty agreements, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We want to take them out of the drug business and put them in
jail,'' said William Gore, the agent in charge of the FBI's San
Diego division. ''Whether it's in Mexico or the United States, I
don't care.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
