<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Attys. Win Fugitive Trial Delay  </HEADLINE>
By LINDA DEUTSCH
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A judge Thursday delayed the trial of a
former Symbionese Liberation Army fugitive until next year, giving
her new defense lawyers time to prepare for the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Jane Olson, facing trial 25 years after she was charged in
a bomb conspiracy, appeared in court and said she wanted the
postponement.
</P>
<P>
   With three lawyers having bowed out of the case in recent
months, Olson's new defenders, J. Tony Serra and Shawn Chapman,
said they could not be ready by the previous trial date of Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ms. Olson has had just plain bad luck in that her attorneys
were not able to continue,'' said Superior Court Judge James
Ideman.
</P>
<P>
   He reluctantly granted the defense request to delay until Jan.
8.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Eleanor Hunter opposed the delay, arguing that in
such an old case witnesses are elderly and could die in the
interim.
</P>
<P>
   Olson, 53, is charged with attempting to murder police officers
with pipe bombs placed under patrol cars in Los Angeles in 1975.
The bombs, allegedly planted as revenge for the killings of six SLA
members in a Los Angeles police shootout, never went off. She has
said she was not involved in planting the bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Olson was a fugitive until her arrest last year in St. Paul,
Minn. She had married a doctor, had three children and became a
pillar of the community. Her friends and church members posted $1
million for her bail, allowing her to remain free while the case is
pending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
