<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, May 11, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GOP Weighs Primary Schedule Changes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Republicans who believe their states were practically
shut out of the presidential nominating process are backing a proposal to let
smaller states vote first in early March, with clusters of larger states voting
later through June. But representatives of some of those big states, including
California, Florida, Illinois and Texas, opposed the plan, debated today by the
Republican National Committee's rules panel. A vote was expected tomorrow, when
the RNC's state chairmen's meeting reconvenes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Pulls Even With Gore Among Women
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- George Bush has pulled even with Al Gore in women's
support, helping the Republican edge ahead in a broader survey of likely
presidential voters. Americans say they also feel Bush is more charismatic, has
a better sense of humor and is more inspiring. On the other hand, people in the
new polling said they find Gore, the Democratic vice president, more attractive
and more caring about people. Campaign polls out today suggested that Bush, the
Texas governor, has largely recovered from his slump in the polls in March and
has made gains among several key voter groups.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Review of Miami Mayor Charges Ordered
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Gov. Jeb Bush assigned a special prosecutor today
to review the flury of accusations made by Miami Mayor Joe Carollo and the
former city manager in the aftermath of the Elian Gonzalez raid. State Attorney
Bernie McCabe, who works in Pinellas and Pasco counties, was assigned to review
whether criminal charges should be brought regarding allegations made by former
Miami City Manager Donald Warshaw and Carollo. Carollo fired Warshaw days after
Warshaw refused to fire former Police Chief William O'Brien, who was alerted to
the April 22 federal raid but did not inform the mayor. O'Brien later resigned.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fire Sweeps Through Los Alamos, N.M.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ALAMOS, N.M. (AP) -- Driven by swirling wind of up 55 mph, fire rolled
from block to block in abandoned Los Alamos today, burning scores of homes down
to their foundations in the town where the atomic bomb was built. Firefighters
rushed to save houses as orange flames and billowing smoke rose over the town.
Whole neighborhoods were reduced to ruins, with everything from trailers to
mansions going up in smoke in a blaze that had been set by the government to
clear away brush in the wilderness but raged out of control over the weekend.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sierra Leone Drives Rebels Back
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Sierra Leone soldiers and pro-government
militia drove rebel forces farther from the capital today, an army spokesman
said, as the government moved to head off a feared guerilla offensive on
Freetown. The fighting near the town of Newton, 25 miles east of Freetown, came
as U.N. peacekeeping troops and pro-government forces geared up for a possible
Revolutionary United Front advance on the nervous capital, where thousands of
frightened villagers have sought sanctuary.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Wounded Near Arkansas School
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PRAIRIE GROVE, Ark. (AP) -- A police officer exchanged gunshots with a
seventh-grader today as the boy headed toward his junior high school with a
shotgun, authorities said. Both were wounded. The officer, who was assigned
part-time to the school, was treated and released from a hospital. The
12-year-old was in stable condition after being shot in the abdomen. Prairie
Grove Superintendent Tom Louks said the boy had skipped school Tuesday and
yesterday after being involved in a dispute Monday. The boy was brought to
school by at least one of his parents today but left shortly after classes
began, Louks said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- A rally on Wall Street helped Tokyo stocks rebound somewhat
early Friday from the previous day's plunge. The Nikkei gained 344.75 points to
17,227.21 in the first 30 minutes of trading. In New York, the Nasdaq rose
114.85 points to 3,499.58 at Thursday's finish. The Dow climbed 178.19 points to
close at 10,545.97.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mets Defeat Pirates 3-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The New York Mets remained unbeaten with Al Leiter on the
mound, getting an eight-hitter from the left-hander and a solo homer and two
RBIs from Todd Zeile to beat the Pittsburgh Pirates 3-2 tonight. Leiter (4-0)
struck out eight as the Mets improved to 7-0 when he starts this season. The
Pirates had won four of five and had scored at least 11 runs in each of their
last three victories, including a 13-9 decision Wednesday.
</P>
